\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Boy Who Lived\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Mr. and Mrs. Dursley, of number four, Privet Drive, were proud to say that they were perfectly normal, thank you very much. They were the last people you\rquote d expect to be in\-volved in anything strange or mysterious, because they just didn\rquote t hold with such nonsense.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Mr. Dursley was the director of a firm called Grunnings, which made drills. He was a big, beefy man with hardly any neck, al\-though he did have a very large mustache. Mrs. Dursley was thin and blonde and had nearly twice the usual amount of neck, which came in very useful as she spent so much of her time craning over garden fences, spying on the neighbors. The Dursleys had a small son called Dudley and in their opinion there was no finer boy any\-where.\par
The Dursleys had everything they wanted, but they also had a secret, and their greatest fear was that somebody would discover it. They didn\rquote t think they could bear it if anyone found out about the Potters. Mrs. Potter was Mrs. Dursley\rquote s sister, but they hadn\rquote t met for several years; in fact, Mrs. Dursley pretended she didn\rquote t have a sister, because her sister and her good-for-nothing husband were as unDursleyish as it was possible to be. The Dursleys shuddered to think what the neighbors would say if the Potters arrived in the street. The Dursleys knew that the Potters had a small son, too, but they had never even seen him. This boy was another good reason for keeping the Potters away; they didn\rquote t want Dudley mixing with a child like that.\par
When Mr. and Mrs. Dursley woke up on the dull, gray Tuesday our story starts, there was nothing about the cloudy sky outside to suggest that strange and mysterious things would soon be happen\-ing all over the country. Mr. Dursley hummed as he picked out his most boring tie for work, and Mrs. Dursley gossiped away happily as she wrestled a screaming Dudley into his high chair.\par
None of them noticed a large, tawny owl flutter past the window.\par
At half past eight, Mr. Dursley picked up his briefcase, pecked Mrs. Dursley on the cheek, and tried to kiss Dudley good-bye but missed, because Dudley was now having a tantrum and throwing his cereal at the walls. \ldblquote Little tyke,\rdblquote  chortled Mr. Dursley as he left the house. He got into his car and backed out of number four\rquote s drive.\par
It was on the corner of the street that he noticed the first sign of something peculiar \emdash  a cat reading a map. For a second, Mr. Dursley didn\rquote t realize what he had seen \emdash  then he jerked his head around to look again. There was a tabby cat standing on the corner of Privet Drive, but there wasn\rquote t a map in sight. What could he have been thinking of? It must have been a trick of the light. Mr. Dursley blinked and stared at the cat. It stared back. As Mr. Durs\-ley drove around the corner and up the road, he watched the cat in his mirror. It was now reading the sign that said Privet Drive \emdash  no, \i looking\i0  at the sign; cats couldn\rquote t read maps \i or\i0  signs. Mr. Dursley gave himself a little shake and put the cat out of his mind. As he drove toward town he thought of nothing except a large order of drills he was hoping to get that day.\par
But on the edge of town, drills were driven out of his mind by something else. As he sat in the usual morning traffic jam, he couldn\rquote t help noticing that there seemed to be a lot of strangely dressed people about. People in cloaks. Mr. Dursley couldn\rquote t bear people who dressed in funny clothes \emdash  the getups you saw on young people! He supposed this was some stupid new fashion. He drummed his fingers on the steering wheel and his eyes fell on a huddle of these weirdos standing quite close by. They were whis\-pering excitedly together. Mr. Dursley was enraged to see that a couple of them weren\rquote t young at all; why, that man had to be older than he was, and wearing an emerald-green cloak! The nerve of him! But then it struck Mr. Dursley that this was probably some silly stunt \emdash  these people were obviously collecting for some\-thing \'85 yes, that would be it. The traffic moved on and a few minutes later, Mr. Dursley arrived in the Grunnings parking lot, his mind back on drills.\par
Mr. Dursley always sat with his back to the window in his office on the ninth floor. If he hadn\rquote t, he might have found it harder to concentrate on drills that morning. \i He\i0  didn\rquote t see the owls swooping past in broad daylight, though people down in the street did; they pointed and gazed open-mouthed as owl after owl sped over\-head. Most of them had never seen an owl even at nighttime. Mr. Dursley, however, had a perfectly normal, owl-free morning. He yelled at five different people. He made several important tele\-phone calls and shouted a bit more. He was in a very good mood until lunchtime, when he thought he\rquote d stretch his legs and walk across the road to buy himself a bun from the bakery.\par
He\rquote d forgotten all about the people in cloaks until he passed a group of them next to the baker\rquote s. He eyed them angrily as he passed. He didn\rquote t know why, but they made him uneasy. This bunch were whispering excitedly, too, and he couldn\rquote t see a single collecting tin. It was on his way back past them, clutching a large doughnut in a bag, that he caught a few words of what they were saying.\par
\ldblquote The Potters, that\rquote s right, that\rquote s what I heard \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\emdash  yes, their son, Harry \emdash\rdblquote\par
Mr. Dursley stopped dead. Fear flooded him. He looked back at the whisperers as if he wanted to say something to them, but thought better of it.\par
He dashed back across the road, hurried up to his office, snapped at his secretary not to disturb him, seized his telephone, and had almost finished dialing his home number when he changed his mind. He put the receiver back down and stroked his mustache, thinking \'85 no, he was being stupid. Potter wasn\rquote t such an unusual name. He was sure there were lots of people called Pot\-ter who had a son called Harry. Come to think of it, he wasn\rquote t even sure his nephew \i was\i0  called Harry. He\rquote d never even seen the boy. It might have been Harvey. Or Harold. There was no point in wor\-rying Mrs. Dursley; she always got so upset at any mention of her sister. He didn\rquote t blame her \emdash  if \i he\rquote d\i0  had\i  \i0 a sister like that \'85 but all the same, those people in cloaks \'85\par
He found it a lot harder to concentrate on drills that afternoon and when he left the building at five o\rquote clock, he was still so worried that he walked straight into someone just outside the door.\par
\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  he grunted, as the tiny old man stumbled and almost fell. It was a few seconds before Mr. Dursley realized that the man was wearing a violet cloak. He didn\rquote t seem at all upset at being al\-most knocked to the ground. On the contrary, his face split into a wide smile and he said in a squeaky voice that made passersby stare, \ldblquote Don\rquote t be sorry, my dear sir, for nothing could upset me today! Re\-joice, for You-Know-Who has gone at last! Even Muggles like your\-self should be celebrating, this happy, happy day!\rdblquote\par
And the old man hugged Mr. Dursley around the middle and walked off.\par
Mr. Dursley stood rooted to the spot. He had been hugged by a complete stranger. He also thought he had been called a Muggle, whatever that was. He was rattled. He hurried to his car and set off for home, hoping he was imagining things, which he had never hoped before, because he didn\rquote t approve of imagination.\par
As he pulled into the driveway of number four, the first thing he saw \emdash  and it didn\rquote t improve his mood \emdash  was the tabby cat he\rquote d spotted that morning. It was now sitting on his garden wall. He was sure it was the same one; it had the same markings around its eyes.\par
\ldblquote Shoo!\rdblquote  said Mr. Dursley loudly.\par
The cat didn\rquote t move. It just gave him a stern look. Was this nor\-mal cat behavior? Mr. Dursley wondered. Trying to pull himself to\-gether, he let himself into the house. He was still determined not to mention anything to his wife.\par
Mrs. Dursley had had a nice, normal day. She told him over din\-ner all about Mrs. Next Door\rquote s problems with her daughter and how Dudley had learned a new word (\ldblquote Won\rquote t!\rdblquote ). Mr. Dursley tried to act normally. When Dudley had been put to bed, he went into the living room in time to catch the last report on the evening news:\par
\ldblquote And finally, bird-watchers everywhere have reported that the nation\rquote s owls have been behaving very unusually today. Although owls normally hunt at night and are hardly ever seen in daylight, there have been hundreds of sightings of these birds flying in every direction since sunrise. Experts are unable to explain why the owls have suddenly changed their sleeping pattern.\rdblquote  The newscaster al\-lowed himself a grin. \ldblquote Most mysterious. And now, over to Jim McGuffin with the weather. Going to be any more showers of owls tonight, Jim?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, Ted,\rdblquote  said the weatherman, \ldblquote I don\rquote t know about that, but it\rquote s not only the owls that have been acting oddly today. Viewers as far apart as Kent, Yorkshire, and Dundee have been phoning in to tell me that instead of the rain I promised yesterday, they\rquote ve had a downpour of shooting stars! Perhaps people have been celebrating Bonfire Night early \emdash  it\rquote s not until next week, folks! But I can promise a wet night tonight.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Dursley sat frozen in his armchair. Shooting stars all over Britain? Owls flying by daylight? Mysterious people in cloaks all over the place? And a whisper, a whisper about the Potters \'85\par
Mrs. Dursley came into the living room carrying two cups of tea. It was no good. He\rquote d have to say something to her. He cleared his throat nervously. \ldblquote Er \emdash  Petunia, dear \emdash  you haven\rquote t heard from your sister lately, have you?\rdblquote\par
As he had expected, Mrs. Dursley looked shocked and angry. Af\-ter all, they normally pretended she didn\rquote t have a sister.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she said sharply. \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Funny stuff on the news,\rdblquote  Mr. Dursley mumbled. \ldblquote Owls \'85 shooting stars \'85 and there were a lot of funny-looking people in town today \'85\rdblquote\par
\i\ldblquote So?\rdblquote\i0  snapped Mrs. Dursley.\par
\ldblquote Well, I just thought \'85 maybe \'85 it was something to do with \'85 you know \'85 \i her\i0  crowd.\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Dursley sipped her tea through pursed lips. Mr. Dursley wondered whether he dared tell her he\rquote d heard the name \ldblquote Potter.\rdblquote  He decided he didn\rquote t dare. Instead he said, as casually as he could, \ldblquote Their son \emdash  he\rquote d be about Dudley\rquote s age now, wouldn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I suppose so,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Dursley stiffly.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s his name again? Howard, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry. Nasty, common name, if you ask me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, yes,\rdblquote  said Mr. Dursley, his heart sinking horribly. \ldblquote Yes, I quite agree.\rdblquote\par
He didn\rquote t say another word on the subject as they went upstairs to bed. While Mrs. Dursley was in the bathroom, Mr. Dursley crept to the bedroom window and peered down into the front gar\-den. The cat was still there. It was staring down Privet Drive as though it were waiting for something.\par
Was he imagining things? Could all this have anything to do with the Potters? If it did \'85 if it got out that they were related to a pair of \emdash  well, he didn\rquote t think he could bear it.\par
The Dursleys got into bed. Mrs. Dursley fell asleep quickly but Mr. Dursley lay awake, turning it all over in his mind. His last, comforting thought before he fell asleep was that even if the Potters \i were \i0 involved, there was no reason for them to come near him and Mrs. Dursley. The Potters knew very well what he and Petunia thought about them and their kind. \'85 He couldn\rquote t see how he and Petunia could get mixed up in anything that might be going on \emdash  he yawned and turned over \emdash  it couldn\rquote t affect \i them. \'85\i0\par
How very wrong he was.\par
Mr. Dursley might have been drifting into an uneasy sleep, but the cat on the wall outside was showing no sign of sleepiness. It was sitting as still as a statue, its eyes fixed unblinkingly on the far cor\-ner of Privet Drive. It didn\rquote t so much as quiver when a car door slammed on the next street, nor when two owls swooped overhead. In fact, it was nearly midnight before the cat moved at all.\par
A man appeared on the corner the cat had been watching, ap\-peared so suddenly and silently you\rquote d have thought he\rquote d just popped out of the ground. The cat\rquote s tail twitched and its eyes nar\-rowed.\par
Nothing like this man had ever been seen on Privet Drive. He was tall, thin, and very old, judging by the silver of his hair and beard, which were both long enough to tuck into his belt. He was wearing long robes, a purple cloak that swept the ground, and high-heeled, buckled boots. His blue eyes were light, bright, and sparkling behind half-moon spectacles and his nose was very long and crooked, as though it had been broken at least twice. This man\rquote s name was Albus Dumbledore.\par
Albus Dumbledore didn\rquote t seem to realize that he had just arrived in a street where everything from his name to his boots was unwel\-come. He was busy rummaging in his cloak, looking for some\-thing. But he did seem to realize he was being watched, because he looked up suddenly at the cat, which was still staring at him from the other end of the street. For some reason, the sight of the cat seemed to amuse him. He chuckled and muttered, \ldblquote I should have known.\rdblquote\par
He found what he was looking for in his inside pocket. It seemed to be a silver cigarette lighter. He flicked it open, held it up in the air, and clicked it. The nearest street lamp went out with a little pop. He clicked it again \emdash  the next lamp flickered into dark\-ness. Twelve times he clicked the Put-Outer, until the only lights left on the whole street were two tiny pinpricks in the distance, which were the eyes of the cat watching him. If anyone looked out of their window now, even beady-eyed Mrs. Dursley, they wouldn\rquote t be able to see anything that was happening down on the pavement. Dumbledore slipped the Put-Outer back inside his cloak and set off down the street toward number four, where he sat down on the wall next to the cat. He didn\rquote t look at it, but after a moment he spoke to it.\par
\ldblquote Fancy seeing you here, Professor McGonagall.\rdblquote\par
He turned to smile at the tabby, but it had gone. Instead he was smiling at a rather severe-looking woman who was wearing square glasses exactly the shape of the markings the cat had had around its eyes. She, too, was wearing a cloak, an emerald one. Her black hair was drawn into a tight bun. She looked distinctly ruffled.\par
\ldblquote How did you know it was me?\rdblquote  she asked.\par
\ldblquote My dear Professor, I\rquote ve never seen a cat sit so stiffly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote d be stiff if you\rquote d been sitting on a brick wall all day,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\par
\ldblquote All day? When you could have been celebrating? I must have passed a dozen feasts and parties on my way here.\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall sniffed angrily.\par
\ldblquote Oh yes, everyone\rquote s celebrating, all right,\rdblquote  she said impatiently. \ldblquote You\rquote d think they\rquote d be a bit more careful, but no \emdash  even the Mug\-gles have noticed something\rquote s going on. It was on their news.\rdblquote  She jerked her head back at the Dursleys\rquote  dark living-room window. \ldblquote I heard it. Flocks of owls \'85 shooting stars. \'85 Well, they\rquote re not completely stupid. They were bound to notice something. Shoot\-ing stars down in Kent \emdash  I\rquote ll bet that was Dedalus Diggle. He never had much sense.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You can\rquote t blame them,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore gently. \ldblquote We\rquote ve had precious little to celebrate for eleven years.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know that,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall irritably. \ldblquote But that\rquote s no reason to lose our heads. People are being downright careless, out on the streets in broad daylight, not even dressed in Muggle clothes, swapping rumors.\rdblquote\par
She threw a sharp, sideways glance at Dumbledore here, as though hoping he was going to tell her something, but he didn\rquote t, so she went on. \ldblquote A fine thing it would be if, on the very day You-Know-Who seems to have disappeared at last, the Muggles found out about us all. I suppose he really \i has\i0  gone, Dumbledore?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It certainly seems so,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote We have much to be thankful for. Would you care for a lemon drop?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A \i what\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A lemon drop. They\rquote re a kind of Muggle sweet I\rquote m rather fond of.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, thank you,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall coldly, as though she didn\rquote t think this was the moment for lemon drops. \ldblquote As I say, even if You-Know-Who \i has\i0  gone \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My dear Professor, surely a sensible person like yourself can call him by his name? All this \lquote You-Know-Who\rquote  nonsense \emdash  for eleven years I have been trying to persuade people to call him by his proper name: \i Voldemort.\rdblquote  \i0 Professor McGonagall flinched, but Dum\-bledore, who was unsticking two lemon drops, seemed not to no\-tice. \ldblquote It all gets so confusing if we keep saying \lquote You-Know-Who.\rquote  I have never seen any reason to be frightened of saying Voldemort\rquote s name.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know you haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, sounding half exasperated, half admiring. \ldblquote But you\rquote re different. Everyone knows you\rquote re the only one You-Know- oh, all right, \i Voldemort, \i0 was fright\-ened of.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You flatter me,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly. \ldblquote Voldemort had powers I will never have.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Only because you\rquote re too \emdash  well \emdash  \i noble \i0 to use them.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s lucky it\rquote s dark. I haven\rquote t blushed so much since Madam Pomfrey told me she liked my new earmuffs.\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall shot a sharp look at Dumbledore and said, \ldblquote The owls are nothing next to the \i rumors \i0 that are flying around. You know what everyone\rquote s saying? About why he\rquote s disap\-peared? About what finally stopped him?\rdblquote\par
It seemed that Professor McGonagall had reached the point she was most anxious to discuss, the real reason she had been waiting on a cold, hard wall all day, for neither as a cat nor as a woman had she fixed Dumbledore with such a piercing stare as she did now. It was plain that whatever \ldblquote everyone\rdblquote  was saying, she was not going to believe it until Dumbledore told her it was true. Dumbledore, however, was choosing another lemon drop and did not answer.\par
\ldblquote What they\rquote re \i saying,\rdblquote  \i0 she pressed on, \ldblquote is that last night Vol\-demort turned up in Godric\rquote s Hollow. He went to find the Pot\-ters. The rumor is that Lily and James Potter are \emdash  are \emdash  that they\rquote re \emdash  \i dead.\rdblquote\i0\par
Dumbledore bowed his head. Professor McGonagall gasped.\par
\ldblquote Lily and James \'85 I can\rquote t believe it \'85 I didn\rquote t want to believe it \'85 Oh, Albus \'85\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore reached out and patted her on the shoulder. \ldblquote I know \'85 I know \'85\rdblquote  he said heavily.\par
Professor McGonagall\rquote s voice trembled as she went on. \ldblquote That\rquote s not all. They\rquote re saying he tried to kill the Potters\rquote  son, Harry. But \emdash  he couldn\rquote t. He couldn\rquote t kill that little boy. No one knows why, or how, but they\rquote re saying that when he couldn\rquote t kill Harry Potter, Voldemort\rquote s power somehow broke \emdash  and that\rquote s why he\rquote s gone.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore nodded glumly.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s \emdash  it\rquote s \i true?\rdblquote  \i0 faltered Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote After all he\rquote s done \'85 all the people he\rquote s killed \'85 he couldn\rquote t kill a little boy? It\rquote s just astounding \'85 of all the things to stop him \'85 but how in the name of heaven did Harry survive?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We can only guess,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote We may never know.\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall pulled out a lace handkerchief and dabbed at her eyes beneath her spectacles. Dumbledore gave a great sniff as he took a golden watch from his pocket and examined it. It was a very odd watch. It had twelve hands but no numbers; in\-stead, little planets were moving around the edge. It must have made sense to Dumbledore, though, because he put it back in his pocket and said, \ldblquote Hagrid\rquote s late. I suppose it was he who told you I\rquote d be here, by the way?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote And I don\rquote t suppose you\rquote re going to tell me \i why \i0 you\rquote re here, of all places?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve come to bring Harry to his aunt and uncle. They\rquote re the only family he has left now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t mean \emdash  you \i can\rquote t \i0 mean the people who live \i here?\rdblquote\i0  cried Professor McGonagall, jumping to her feet and pointing at number four. \ldblquote Dumbledore \emdash  you can\rquote t. I\rquote ve been watching them all day. You couldn\rquote t find two people who are less like us. And they\rquote ve got this son \emdash  I saw him kicking his mother all the way up the street, screaming for sweets. Harry Potter come and live here!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s the best place for him,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore firmly. \ldblquote His aunt and uncle will be able to explain everything to him when he\rquote s older. I\rquote ve written them a letter.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A letter?\rdblquote  repeated Professor McGonagall faintly, sitting back down on the wall. \ldblquote Really, Dumbledore, you think you can explain all this in a letter? These people will never understand him! He\rquote ll be famous \emdash  a legend \emdash  I wouldn\rquote t be surprised if today was known as Harry Potter Day in the future \emdash  there will be books written about Harry \emdash  every child in our world will know his name!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, looking very seriously over the top of his half-moon glasses. \ldblquote It would be enough to turn any boy\rquote s head. Famous before he can walk and talk! Famous for something he won\rquote t even remember! Can\rquote t you see how much better off he\rquote ll be, growing up away from all that until he\rquote s ready to take it?\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall opened her mouth, changed her mind, swallowed, and then said, \ldblquote Yes \emdash  yes, you\rquote re right, of course. But how is the boy getting here, Dumbledore?\rdblquote  She eyed his cloak sud\-denly as though she thought he might be hiding Harry underneath it.\par
\ldblquote Hagrid\rquote s bringing him.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You think it \emdash  \i wise \i0\emdash  to trust Hagrid with something as im\-portant as this?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I would trust Hagrid with my life,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not saying his heart isn\rquote t in the right place,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall grudgingly, \ldblquote but you can\rquote t pretend he\rquote s not careless. He does tend to \emdash  what was that?\rdblquote\par
A low rumbling sound had broken the silence around them. It grew steadily louder as they looked up and down the street for some sign of a headlight; it swelled to a roar as they both looked up at the sky \emdash  and a huge motorcycle fell out of the air and landed on the road in front of them.\par
If the motorcycle was huge, it was nothing to the man sitting astride it. He was almost twice as tall as a normal man and at least five times as wide. He looked simply too big to be allowed, and so \i wild\i0  \emdash  long tangles of bushy black hair and beard hid most of his face, he had hands the size of trash can lids, and his feet in their leather boots were like baby dolphins. In his vast, muscular arms he was holding a bundle of blankets.\par
\ldblquote Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, sounding relieved. \ldblquote At last. And where did you get that motorcycle?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Borrowed it, Professor Dumbledore, sir,\rdblquote  said the giant, climb\-ing carefully off the motorcycle as he spoke. \ldblquote Young Sirius Black lent it to me. I\rquote ve got him, sir.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No problems, were there?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, sir \emdash  house was almost destroyed, but I got him out all right before the Muggles started swarmin\rquote  around. He fell asleep as we was flyin\rquote  over Bristol.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore and Professor McGonagall bent forward over the bundle of blankets. Inside, just visible, was a baby boy, fast asleep. Under a tuft of jet-black hair over his forehead they could see a cu\-riously shaped cut, like a bolt of lightning.\par
\ldblquote Is that where \emdash  ?\rdblquote  whispered Professor McGonagall.\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He\rquote ll have that scar forever.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t you do something about it, Dumbledore?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Even if I could, I wouldn\rquote t. Scars can come in handy. I have one myself above my left knee that is a perfect map of the London Un\-derground. Well \emdash  give him here, Hagrid \emdash  we\rquote d better get this over with.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore took Harry in his arms and turned toward the Dursleys\rquote  house.\par
\ldblquote Could I \emdash  could I say good-bye to him, sir?\rdblquote  asked Hagrid. He bent his great, shaggy head over Harry and gave him what must have been a very scratchy, whiskery kiss. Then, suddenly, Hagrid let out a howl like a wounded dog.\par
\ldblquote Shhh!\rdblquote  hissed Professor McGonagall, \ldblquote you\rquote ll wake the Mug\-gles!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote S-s-sorry,\rdblquote  sobbed Hagrid, taking out a large, spotted handker\-chief and burying his face in it. \ldblquote But I c-c-can\rquote t stand it \emdash  Lily an\rquote  James dead \emdash  an\rquote  poor little Harry off ter live with Muggles \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, yes, it\rquote s all very sad, but get a grip on yourself, Hagrid, or we\rquote ll be found,\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall whispered, patting Hagrid gingerly on the arm as Dumbledore stepped over the low garden wall and walked to the front door. He laid Harry gently on the doorstep, took a letter out of his cloak, tucked it inside Harry\rquote s blankets, and then came back to the other two. For a full minute the three of them stood and looked at the little bundle; Hagrid\rquote s shoulders shook, Professor McGonagall blinked furiously, and the twinkling light that usually shone from Dumbledore\rquote s eyes seemed to have gone out.\par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore finally, \ldblquote that\rquote s that. We\rquote ve no business staying here. We may as well go and join the celebrations.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Hagrid in a very muffled voice, \ldblquote I\rquote d best get this bike away. G\rquote night, Professor McGonagall \emdash  Professor Dumble\-dore, sir.\rdblquote\par
Wiping his streaming eyes on his jacket sleeve, Hagrid swung himself onto the motorcycle and kicked the engine into life; with a roar it rose into the air and off into the night.\par
\ldblquote I shall see you soon, I expect, Professor McGonagall,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, nodding to her. Professor McGonagall blew her nose in reply.\par
Dumbledore turned and walked back down the street. On the corner he stopped and took out the silver Put-Outer. He clicked it once, and twelve balls of light sped back to their street lamps so that Privet Drive glowed suddenly orange and he could make out a tabby cat slinking around the corner at the other end of the street. He could just see the bundle of blankets on the step of number four.\par
\ldblquote Good luck, Harry,\rdblquote  he murmured. He turned on his heel and with a swish of his cloak, he was gone.\par
A breeze ruffled the neat hedges of Privet Drive, which lay silent and tidy under the inky sky, the very last place you would expect astonishing things to happen. Harry Potter rolled over inside his blankets without waking up. One small hand closed on the letter beside him and he slept on, not knowing he was special, not know\-ing he was famous, not knowing he would be woken in a few hours\rquote  time by Mrs. Dursley\rquote s scream as she opened the front door to put out the milk bottles, nor that he would spend the next few weeks being prodded and pinched by his cousin Dudley. \'85 He couldn\rquote t know that at this very moment, people meeting in secret all over the country were holding up their glasses and saying in hushed voices: \ldblquote To Harry Potter \emdash  the boy who lived!\rdblquote\par
