\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\lang3081\fs36 Chapter 2\lang1033\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Vanishing Glass\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Nearly ten years had passed since the Dursleys had woken up to find their nephew on the front step, but Privet Drive had hardly changed at all. The sun rose on the same tidy front gar\-dens and lit up the brass number four on the Dursleys\rquote  front door; it crept into their living room, which was almost exactly the same as it had been on the night when Mr. Dursley had seen that fateful news report about the owls. Only the photographs on the mantel\-piece really showed how much time had passed. Ten years ago, there had been lots of pictures of what looked like a large pink beach ball wearing different-colored bonnets \emdash  but Dudley Durs\-ley was no longer a baby, and now the photographs showed a large blond boy riding his first bicycle, on a carousel at the fair, playing a computer game with his father, being hugged and kissed by his mother. The room held no sign at all that another boy lived in the house, too.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Yet Harry Potter was still there, asleep at the moment, but not for long. His Aunt Petunia was awake and it was her shrill voice that made the first noise of the day.\par
\ldblquote Up! Get up! Now!\rdblquote\par
Harry woke with a start. His aunt rapped on the door again.\par
\ldblquote Up!\rdblquote  she screeched. Harry heard her walking toward the kitchen and then the sound of the frying pan being put on the stove. He rolled onto his back and tried to remember the dream he had been having. It had been a good one. There had been a flying motorcycle in it. He had a funny feeling he\rquote d had the same dream before.\par
His aunt was back outside the door.\par
\ldblquote Are you up yet?\rdblquote  she demanded.\par
\ldblquote Nearly,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Well, get a move on, I want you to look after the bacon. And don\rquote t you dare let it burn, I want everything perfect on Duddy\rquote s birthday.\rdblquote\par
Harry groaned.\par
\ldblquote What did you say?\rdblquote  his aunt snapped through the door.\par
\ldblquote Nothing, nothing \'85\rdblquote\par
Dudley\rquote s birthday \emdash  how could he have forgotten? Harry got slowly out of bed and started looking for socks. He found a pair under his bed and, after pulling a spider off one of them, put them on. Harry was used to spiders, because the cupboard under the stairs was full of them, and that was where he slept.\par
When he was dressed he went down the hall into the kitchen. The table was almost hidden beneath all Dudley\rquote s birthday pres\-ents. It looked as though Dudley had gotten the new computer he wanted, not to mention the second television and the racing bike. Exactly why Dudley wanted a racing bike was a mystery to Harry, as Dudley was very fat and hated exercise \emdash  unless of course it in\-volved punching somebody. Dudley\rquote s favorite punching bag was Harry, but he couldn\rquote t often catch him. Harry didn\rquote t look it, but he was very fast.\par
Perhaps it had something to do with living in a dark cupboard, but Harry had always been small and skinny for his age. He looked even smaller and skinnier than he really was because all he had to wear were old clothes of Dudley\rquote s, and Dudley was about four times bigger than he was. Harry had a thin face, knobbly knees, black hair, and bright green eyes. He wore round glasses held to\-gether with a lot of Scotch tape because of all the times Dudley had punched him on the nose. The only thing Harry liked about his own appearance was a very thin scar on his forehead that was shaped like a bolt of lightning. He had had it as long as he could re\-member, and the first question he could ever remember asking his Aunt Petunia was how he had gotten it.\par
\ldblquote In the car crash when your parents died,\rdblquote  she had said. \ldblquote And don\rquote t ask questions.\rdblquote\par
\i Don\rquote t ask questions \i0\emdash  that was the first rule for a quiet life with the Dursleys.\par
Uncle Vernon entered the kitchen as Harry was turning over the bacon.\par
\ldblquote Comb your hair!\rdblquote  he barked, by way of a morning greeting.\par
About once a week, Uncle Vernon looked over the top of his newspaper and shouted that Harry needed a haircut. Harry must have had more haircuts than the rest of the boys in his class put together, but it made no difference, his hair simply grew that way \emdash  all over the place.\par
Harry was frying eggs by the time Dudley arrived in the kitchen with his mother. Dudley looked a lot like Uncle Vernon. He had a large pink face, not much neck, small, watery blue eyes, and thick blond hair that lay smoothly on his thick, fat head. Aunt Petunia often said that Dudley looked like a baby angel \emdash  Harry often said that Dudley looked like a pig in a wig.\par
Harry put the plates of egg and bacon on the table, which was difficult as there wasn\rquote t much room. Dudley, meanwhile, was counting his presents. His face fell.\par
\ldblquote Thirty-six,\rdblquote  he said, looking up at his mother and father. \ldblquote That\rquote s two less than last year.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Darling, you haven\rquote t counted Auntie Marge\rquote s present, see, it\rquote s here under this big one from Mommy and Daddy.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, thirty-seven then,\rdblquote  said Dudley, going red in the face. Harry, who could see a huge Dudley tantrum coming on, began wolfing down his bacon as fast as possible in case Dudley turned the table over.\par
Aunt Petunia obviously scented danger, too, because she said quickly, \ldblquote And we\rquote ll buy you another \i two\i0  presents while we\rquote re out today. How\rquote s that, popkin? \i Two\i0  more presents. Is that all right?\rdblquote\par
Dudley thought for a moment. It looked like hard work. Finally he said slowly, \ldblquote So I\rquote ll have thirty \'85 thirty \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thirty-nine, sweetums,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia.\par
\ldblquote Oh.\rdblquote  Dudley sat down heavily and grabbed the nearest parcel. \ldblquote All right then.\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon chuckled.\par
\ldblquote Little tyke wants his money\rquote s worth, just like his father. \rquote Atta boy, Dudley!\rdblquote  He ruffled Dudley\rquote s hair.\par
At that moment the telephone rang and Aunt Petunia went to answer it while Harry and Uncle Vernon watched Dudley unwrap the racing bike, a video camera, a remote control airplane, sixteen new computer games, and a VCR. He was ripping the paper off a gold wristwatch when Aunt Petunia came back from the telephone looking both angry and worried.\par
\ldblquote Bad news, Vernon,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Mrs. Figg\rquote s broken her leg. She can\rquote t take him.\rdblquote  She jerked her head in Harry\rquote s direction.\par
Dudley\rquote s mouth fell open in horror, but Harry\rquote s heart gave a leap. Every year on Dudley\rquote s birthday, his parents took him and a friend out for the day, to adventure parks, hamburger restaurants, or the movies. Every year, Harry was left behind with Mrs. Figg, a mad old lady who lived two streets away. Harry hated it there. The whole house smelled of cabbage and Mrs. Figg made him look at photographs of all the cats she\rquote d ever owned.\par
\ldblquote Now what?\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia, looking furiously at Harry as though he\rquote d planned this. Harry knew he ought to feel sorry that Mrs. Figg had broken her leg, but it wasn\rquote t easy when he reminded himself it would be a whole year before he had to look at Tibbies, Snowy, Mr. Paws, and Tufty again.\par
\ldblquote We could phone Marge,\rdblquote  Uncle Vernon suggested.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be silly, Vernon, she hates the boy.\rdblquote\par
The Dursleys often spoke about Harry like this, as though he wasn\rquote t there \emdash  or rather, as though he was something very nasty that couldn\rquote t understand them, like a slug.\par
\ldblquote What about what\rquote s-her-name, your friend \emdash  Yvonne?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote On vacation in Majorca,\rdblquote  snapped Aunt Petunia.\par
\ldblquote You could just leave me here,\rdblquote  Harry put in hopefully (he\rquote d be able to watch what he wanted on television for a change and maybe even have a go on Dudley\rquote s computer).\par
Aunt Petunia looked as though she\rquote d just swallowed a lemon.\par
\ldblquote And come back and find the house in ruins?\rdblquote  she snarled.\par
\ldblquote I won\rquote t blow up the house,\rdblquote  said Harry, but they weren\rquote t listen\-ing.\par
\ldblquote I suppose we could take him to the zoo,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia slowly, \ldblquote\'85 and leave him in the car. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That cars new, he\rquote s not sitting in it alone. \'85\rdblquote\par
Dudley began to cry loudly. In fact, he wasn\rquote t really crying \emdash  it had been years since he\rquote d really cried \emdash  but he knew that if he screwed up his face and wailed, his mother would give him any\-thing he wanted.\par
\ldblquote Dinky Duddydums, don\rquote t cry, Mummy won\rquote t let him spoil your special day!\rdblquote  she cried, flinging her arms around him.\par
\ldblquote I \'85 don\rquote t \'85 want \'85 him \'85 t-t-to come!\rdblquote  Dudley yelled between huge, pretend sobs. \ldblquote He always sp-spoils everything!\rdblquote  He shot Harry a nasty grin through the gap in his mothers arms.\par
Just then, the doorbell rang \emdash  \ldblquote Oh, good Lord, they\rquote re here!\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia frantically \emdash  and a moment later, Dudley\rquote s best friend, Piers Polkiss, walked in with his mother. Piers was a scrawny boy with a face like a rat. He was usually the one who held people\rquote s arms behind their backs while Dudley hit them. Dudley stopped pretending to cry at once.\par
Half an hour later, Harry, who couldn\rquote t believe his luck, was sit\-ting in the back of the Dursleys\rquote  car with Piers and Dudley, on the way to the zoo for the first time in his life. His aunt and uncle hadn\rquote t been able to think of anything else to do with him, but be\-fore they\rquote d left, Uncle Vernon had taken Harry aside.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m warning you,\rdblquote  he had said, putting his large purple face right up close to Harry\rquote s, \ldblquote I\rquote m warning you now, boy \emdash  any funny business, anything at all \emdash  and you\rquote ll be in that cupboard from now until Christmas.\rdblquote\par
I\rquote m not going to do anything,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote honestly \'85\rdblquote\par
But Uncle Vernon didn\rquote t believe him. No one ever did.\par
The problem was, strange things often happened around Harry and it was just no good telling the Dursleys he didn\rquote t make them happen.\par
Once, Aunt Petunia, tired of Harry coming back from the bar\-bers looking as though he hadn\rquote t been at all, had taken a pair of kitchen scissors and cut his hair so short he was almost bald except for his bangs, which she left \ldblquote to hide that horrible scar.\rdblquote  Dudley had laughed himself silly at Harry, who spent a sleepless night imagining school the next day, where he was already laughed at for his baggy clothes and taped glasses. Next morning, however, he had gotten up to find his hair exactly as it had been before Aunt Petu\-nia had sheared it off. He had been given a week in his cupboard for this, even though he had tried to explain that he \i couldn\rquote t\i0  explain how it had grown back so quickly.\par
Another time, Aunt Petunia had been trying to force him into a revolting old sweater of Dudley\rquote s (brown with orange puff balls). The harder she tried to pull it over his head, the smaller it seemed to become, until finally it might have fitted a hand puppet, but certainly wouldn\rquote t fit Harry. Aunt Petunia had decided it must have shrunk in the wash and, to his great relief, Harry wasn\rquote t pun\-ished.\par
On the other hand, he\rquote d gotten into terrible trouble for being found on the roof of the school kitchens. Dudley\rquote s gang had been chasing him as usual when, as much to Harry\rquote s surprise as anyone else\rquote s, there he was sitting on the chimney. The Dursleys had re\-ceived a very angry letter from Harry\rquote s headmistress telling them Harry had been climbing school buildings. But all he\rquote d tried to do (as he shouted at Uncle Vernon through the locked door of his cup\-board) was jump behind the big trash cans outside the kitchen doors. Harry supposed that the wind must have caught him in mid-jump.\par
But today, nothing was going to go wrong. It was even worth be\-ing with Dudley and Piers to be spending the day somewhere that wasn\rquote t school, his cupboard, or Mrs. Figg\rquote s cabbage-smelling living room.\par
While he drove, Uncle Vernon complained to Aunt Petunia. He liked to complain about things: people at work, Harry, the council, Harry, the bank, and Harry were just a few of his favorite subjects. This morning, it was motorcycles.\par
\ldblquote\'85 roaring along like maniacs, the young hoodlums,\rdblquote  he said, as a motorcycle overtook them.\par
\ldblquote I had a dream about a motorcycle,\rdblquote  said Harry, remembering suddenly. \ldblquote It was flying.\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon nearly crashed into the car in front. He turned right around in his seat and yelled at Harry, his face like a gigantic beet with a mustache: \ldblquote MOTORCYCLES DON\rquote T FLY!\rdblquote\par
Dudley and Piers sniggered.\par
\ldblquote I know they don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote It was only a dream.\rdblquote\par
But he wished he hadn\rquote t said anything. If there was one thing the Dursleys hated even more than his asking questions, it was his talk\-ing about anything acting in a way it shouldn\rquote t, no matter if it was in a dream or even a cartoon \emdash  they seemed to think he might get dangerous ideas.\par
It was a very sunny Saturday and the zoo was crowded with fam\-ilies. The Dursleys bought Dudley and Piers large chocolate ice creams at the entrance and then, because the smiling lady in the van had asked Harry what he wanted before they could hurry him away, they bought him a cheap lemon ice pop. It wasn\rquote t bad, either, Harry thought, licking it as they watched a gorilla scratching its head who looked remarkably like Dudley, except that it wasn\rquote t blond.\par
Harry had the best morning he\rquote d had in a long time. He was careful to walk a little way apart from the Dursleys so that Dudley and Piers, who were starting to get bored with the animals by lunchtime, wouldn\rquote t fall back on their favorite hobby of hitting him. They ate in the zoo restaurant, and when Dudley had a tantrum because his knickerbocker glory didn\rquote t have enough ice cream on top, Uncle Vernon bought him another one and Harry was allowed to finish the first.\par
Harry felt, afterward, that he should have known it was all too good to last.\par
After lunch they went to the reptile house. It was cool and dark in there, with lit windows all along the walls. Behind the glass, all sorts of lizards and snakes were crawling and slithering over bits of wood and stone. Dudley and Piers wanted to see huge, poisonous cobras and thick, man-crushing pythons. Dudley quickly found the largest snake in the place. It could have wrapped its body twice around Uncle Vernon\rquote s car and crushed it into a trash can \emdash  but at the moment it didn\rquote t look in the mood. In fact, it was fast asleep.\par
Dudley stood with his nose pressed against the glass, staring at the glistening brown coils.\par
\ldblquote Make it move,\rdblquote  he whined at his father. Uncle Vernon tapped on the glass, but the snake didn\rquote t budge.\par
\ldblquote Do it again,\rdblquote  Dudley ordered. Uncle Vernon rapped the glass smartly with his knuckles, but the snake just snoozed on.\par
\ldblquote This is boring,\rdblquote  Dudley moaned. He shuffled away.\par
Harry moved in front of the tank and looked intently at the snake. He wouldn\rquote t have been surprised if it had died of boredom itself \emdash  no company except stupid people drumming their fingers on the glass trying to disturb it all day long. It was worse than hav\-ing a cupboard as a bedroom, where the only visitor was Aunt Petu\-nia hammering on the door to wake you up; at least he got to visit the rest of the house.\par
The snake suddenly opened its beady eyes. Slowly, very slowly, it raised its head until its eyes were on a level with Harry\rquote s.\par
\i It winked.\i0\par
Harry stared. Then he looked quickly around to see if anyone was watching. They weren\rquote t. He looked back at the snake and winked, too.\par
The snake jerked its head toward Uncle Vernon and Dudley, then raised its eyes to the ceiling. It gave Harry a look that said quite plainly:\par
\i\ldblquote I get that all the time.\rdblquote\par
\i0\ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  Harry murmured through the glass, though he wasn\rquote t sure the snake could hear him. \ldblquote It must be really annoying.\rdblquote\par
The snake nodded vigorously.\par
\ldblquote Where do you come from, anyway?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
The snake jabbed its tail at a little sign next to the glass. Harry peered at it.\par
B\fs20 OA \fs24 C\fs20 ONSTRICTOR, \fs24 B\fs20 RAZIL.\par
\fs24\ldblquote Was it nice there?\rdblquote\par
The boa constrictor jabbed its tail at the sign again and Harry read on: This specimen was bred in the zoo. \ldblquote Oh, I see \emdash  so you\rquote ve never been to Brazil?\rdblquote\par
As the snake shook its head, a deafening shout behind Harry made both of them jump. \ldblquote DUDLEY! MR. DURSLEY! COME AND LOOK AT THIS SNAKE! YOU WON\rquote T \i BELIEVE \i0 WHAT IT\rquote S DOING!\rdblquote\par
Dudley came waddling toward them as fast as he could.\par
\ldblquote Out of the way, you,\rdblquote  he said, punching Harry in the ribs. Caught by surprise, Harry fell hard on the concrete floor. What came next happened so fast no one saw how it happened \emdash  one second, Piers and Dudley were leaning right up close to the glass, the next, they had leapt back with howls of horror.\par
Harry sat up and gasped; the glass front of the boa constrictor\rquote s tank had vanished. The great snake was uncoiling itself rapidly, slithering out onto the floor. People throughout the reptile house screamed and started running for the exits.\par
As the snake slid swiftly past him, Harry could have sworn a low, hissing voice said, \ldblquote Brazil, here I come. \'85 Thanksss, amigo.\rdblquote\par
The keeper of the reptile house was in shock.\par
\ldblquote But the glass,\rdblquote  he kept saying, \ldblquote where did the glass go?\rdblquote\par
The zoo director himself made Aunt Petunia a cup of strong, sweet tea while he apologized over and over again. Piers and Dud\-ley could only gibber. As far as Harry had seen, the snake hadn\rquote t done anything except snap playfully at their heels as it passed, but by the time they were all back in Uncle Vernon\rquote s car, Dudley was telling them how it had nearly bitten off his leg, while Piers was swearing it had tried to squeeze him to death. But worst of all, for Harry at least, was Piers calming down enough to say, \ldblquote Harry was talking to it, weren\rquote t you, Harry?\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon waited until Piers was safely out of the house be\-fore starting on Harry. He was so angry he could hardly speak. He managed to say, \ldblquote Go \emdash  cupboard \emdash  stay \emdash  no meals,\rdblquote  before he collapsed into a chair, and Aunt Petunia had to run and get him a large brandy.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry lay in his dark cupboard much later, wishing he had a watch. He didn\rquote t know what time it was and he couldn\rquote t be sure the Durs\-leys were asleep yet. Until they were, he couldn\rquote t risk sneaking to the kitchen for some food.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj He\rquote d lived with the Dursleys almost ten years, ten miserable years, as long as he could remember, ever since he\rquote d been a baby and his parents had died in that car crash. He couldn\rquote t remember being in the car when his parents had died. Sometimes, when he strained his memory during long hours in his cupboard, he came up with a strange vision: a blinding flash of green light and a burn\-ing pain on his forehead. This, he supposed, was the crash, though he couldn\rquote t imagine where all the green light came from. He couldn\rquote t remember his parents at all. His aunt and uncle never spoke about them, and of course he was forbidden to ask questions. There were no photographs of them in the house.\par
When he had been younger, Harry had dreamed and dreamed of some unknown relation coming to take him away, but it had never happened; the Dursleys were his only family. Yet sometimes he thought (or maybe hoped) that strangers in the street seemed to know him. Very strange strangers they were, too. A tiny man in a violet top hat had bowed to him once while out shopping with Aunt Petunia and Dudley. After asking Harry furiously if he knew the man, Aunt Petunia had rushed them out of the shop without buying anything. A wild-looking old woman dressed all in green had waved merrily at him once on a bus. A bald man in a very long purple coat had actually shaken his hand in the street the other day and then walked away without a word. The weirdest thing about all these people was the way they seemed to vanish the second Harry tried to get a closer look.\par
At school, Harry had no one. Everybody knew that Dudley\rquote s gang hated that odd Harry Potter in his baggy old clothes and bro\-ken glasses, and nobody liked to disagree with Dudley\rquote s gang.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\lang3081\fs36 Chapter 3\lang1033\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\lang3081 The Letters From No One\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The escape of the Brazilian boa constrictor earned Harry his longest-ever punishment. By the time he was allowed out of his cupboard again, the summer holidays had started and Dudley had already broken his new video camera, crashed his remote con\-trol airplane, and, first time out on his racing bike, knocked down old Mrs. Figg as she crossed Privet Drive on her crutches.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Harry was glad school was over, but there was no escaping Dud\-ley\rquote s gang, who visited the house every single day. Piers, Dennis, Malcolm, and Gordon were all big and stupid, but as Dudley was the biggest and stupidest of the lot, he was the leader. The rest of them were all quite happy to join in Dudley\rquote s favorite sport: Harry Hunting.\par
This was why Harry spent as much time as possible out of the house, wandering around and thinking about the end of the holi\-days, where he could see a tiny ray of hope. When September came he would be going off to secondary school and, for the first time in his life, he wouldn\rquote t be with Dudley. Dudley had been accepted at Uncle Vernon\rquote s old private school, Smeltings. Piers Polkiss was go\-ing there too. Harry, on the other hand, was going to Stonewall High, the local public school. Dudley thought this was very funny.\par
\ldblquote They stuff people\rquote s heads down the toilet the first day at Stonewall,\rdblquote  he told Harry. \ldblquote Want to come upstairs and practice?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote The poor toilet\rquote s never had anything as horrible as your head down it \emdash  it might be sick.\rdblquote  Then he ran, before Dudley could work out what he\rquote d said.\par
One day in July, Aunt Petunia took Dudley to London to buy his Smeltings uniform, leaving Harry at Mrs. Figg\rquote s. Mrs. Figg wasn\rquote t as bad as usual. It turned out she\rquote d broken her leg tripping over one of her cats, and she didn\rquote t seem quite as fond of them as before. She let Harry watch television and gave him a bit of choco\-late cake that tasted as though she\rquote d had it for several years.\par
That evening, Dudley paraded around the living room for the family in his brand-new uniform. Smeltings boys wore maroon tailcoats, orange knickerbockers, and flat straw hats called boaters. They also carried knobbly sticks, used for hitting each other while the teachers weren\rquote t looking. This was supposed to be good train\-ing for later life.\par
As he looked at Dudley in his new knickerbockers, Uncle Ver\-non said gruffly that it was the proudest moment of his life. Aunt Petunia burst into tears and said she couldn\rquote t believe it was her Ickle Dudleykins, he looked so handsome and grown-up. Harry didn\rquote t trust himself to speak. He thought two of his ribs might already have cracked from trying not to laugh.\par
