\pard\nowidctlpar\qj There was a horrible smell in the kitchen the next morning when Harry went in for breakfast. It seemed to be coming from a large metal tub in the sink. He went to have a look. The tub was full of what looked like dirty rags swimming in gray water.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote What\rquote s this?\rdblquote  he asked Aunt Petunia. Her lips tightened as they always did if he dared to ask a question.\par
\ldblquote Your new school uniform,\rdblquote  she said.\par
Harry looked in the bowl again.\par
\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I didn\rquote t realize it had to be so wet.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid,\rdblquote  snapped Aunt Petunia. \ldblquote I\rquote m dyeing some of Dudley\rquote s old things gray for you. It\rquote ll look just like everyone else\rquote s when I\rquote ve finished.\rdblquote\par
Harry seriously doubted this, but thought it best not to argue. He sat down at the table and tried not to think about how he was going to look on his first day at Stonewall High \emdash  like he was wearing bits of old elephant skin, probably.\par
Dudley and Uncle Vernon came in, both with wrinkled noses because of the smell from Harry\rquote s new uniform. Uncle Vernon opened his newspaper as usual and Dudley banged his Smelting stick, which he carried everywhere, on the table.\par
They heard the click of the mail slot and flop of letters on the doormat.\par
\ldblquote Get the mail, Dudley,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon from behind his pa\-per.\par
\ldblquote Make Harry get it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Get the mail, Harry.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Make Dudley get it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Poke him with your Smelting stick, Dudley.\rdblquote\par
Harry dodged the Smelting stick and went to get the mail. Three things lay on the doormat: a postcard from Uncle Vernon\rquote s sister Marge, who was vacationing on the Isle of Wight, a brown enve\-lope that looked like a bill, and \emdash  \i a letter for Harry.\i0\par
Harry picked it up and stared at it, his heart twanging like a gi\-ant elastic band. No one, ever, in his whole life, had written to him. Who would? He had no friends, no other relatives \emdash  he didn\rquote t be\-long to the library, so he\rquote d never even got rude notes asking for books back. Yet here it was, a letter, addressed so plainly there could be no mistake:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li567\ri567\qj\i Mr. H. Potter\par
The Cupboard under the Stairs\par
4 Privet Drive\par
Little Whinging\par
Surrey\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The envelope was thick and heavy, made of yellowish parchment, and the address was written in emerald-green ink. There was no stamp.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Turning the envelope over, his hand trembling, Harry saw a pur\-ple wax seal bearing a coat of arms; a lion, an eagle, a badger, and a snake surrounding a large letter \i H.\i0\par
\ldblquote Hurry up, boy!\rdblquote  shouted Uncle Vernon from the kitchen. \ldblquote What are you doing, checking for letter bombs?\rdblquote  He chuckled at his own joke.\par
Harry went back to the kitchen, still staring at his letter. He handed Uncle Vernon the bill and the postcard, sat down, and slowly began to open the yellow envelope.\par
Uncle Vernon ripped open the bill, snorted in disgust, and flipped over the postcard.\par
\ldblquote Marge\rquote s ill,\rdblquote  he informed Aunt Petunia. \ldblquote Ate a funny whelk \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Dad!\rdblquote  said Dudley suddenly. \ldblquote Dad, Harry\rquote s got something!\rdblquote\par
Harry was on the point of unfolding his letter, which was writ\-ten on the same heavy parchment as the envelope, when it was jerked sharply out of his hand by Uncle Vernon.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s \i mine\i0 !\rdblquote\i  \i0 said Harry, trying to snatch it back.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote d be writing to you?\rdblquote  sneered Uncle Vernon, shaking the letter open with one hand and glancing at it. His face went from red to green faster than a set of traffic lights. And it didn\rquote t stop there. Within seconds it was the grayish white of old porridge.\par
\ldblquote P-P-Petunia!\rdblquote  he gasped.\par
Dudley tried to grab the letter to read it, but Uncle Vernon held it high out of his reach. Aunt Petunia took it curiously and read the first line. For a moment it looked as though she might faint. She clutched her throat and made a choking noise.\par
\ldblquote Vernon! Oh my goodness \emdash  Vernon!\rdblquote\par
They stared at each other, seeming to have forgotten that Harry and Dudley were still in the room. Dudley wasn\rquote t used to being ig\-nored. He gave his father a sharp tap on the head with his Smelting stick.\par
\ldblquote I want to read that letter,\rdblquote  he said loudly.\par
\i\ldblquote I\i0  want to read it,\rdblquote  said Harry furiously, \ldblquote as it\rquote s \i mine.\rdblquote\i0\par
\ldblquote Get out, both of you,\rdblquote  croaked Uncle Vernon, stuffing the let\-ter back inside its envelope.\par
Harry didn\rquote t move.\par
\ldblquote I WANT MY LETTER!\rdblquote  he shouted.\par
\ldblquote Let \i me\i0  see it!\rdblquote  demanded Dudley.\par
\ldblquote OUT!\rdblquote  roared Uncle Vernon, and he took both Harry and Dudley by the scruffs of their necks and threw them into the hall, slamming the kitchen door behind them. Harry and Dudley promptly had a furious but silent fight over who would listen at the keyhole; Dudley won, so Harry, his glasses dangling from one ear, lay flat on his stomach to listen at the crack between door and floor.\par
\ldblquote Vernon,\rdblquote  Aunt Petunia was saying in a quivering voice, \ldblquote look at the address \emdash  how could they possibly know where he sleeps? You don\rquote t think they\rquote re watching the house?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Watching \emdash  spying \emdash  might be following us,\rdblquote  muttered Un\-cle Vernon wildly.\par
\ldblquote But what should we do, Vernon? Should we write back? Tell them we don\rquote t want \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry could see Uncle Vernon\rquote s shiny black shoes pacing up and down the kitchen.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  he said finally. \ldblquote No, we\rquote ll ignore it. If they don\rquote t get an an\-swer. \'85 Yes, that\rquote s best \'85 we won\rquote t do anything. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not having one in the house, Petunia! Didn\rquote t we swear when we took him in we\rquote d stamp out that dangerous nonsense?\rdblquote\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj That evening when he got back from work, Uncle Vernon did something he\rquote d never done before; he visited Harry in his cup\-board.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Where\rquote s my letter?\rdblquote  said Harry, the moment Uncle Vernon had squeezed through the door. \ldblquote Who\rquote s writing to me?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No one. It was addressed to you by mistake,\rdblquote  said Uncle Ver\-non shortly. \ldblquote I have burned it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was \i not \i0 a mistake,\rdblquote  said Harry angrily, \ldblquote it had my cupboard on it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote SILENCE!\rdblquote  yelled Uncle Vernon, and a couple of spiders fell from the ceiling. He took a few deep breaths and then forced his face into a smile, which looked quite painful.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  yes, Harry \emdash  about this cupboard. Your aunt and I have been thinking \'85 you\rquote re really getting a bit big for it \'85 we think it might be nice if you moved into Dudley\rquote s second bed\-room.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t ask questions!\rdblquote  snapped his uncle. \ldblquote Take this stuff up\-stairs, now.\rdblquote\par
The Dursleys\rquote  house had four bedrooms: one for Uncle Vernon and Aunt Petunia, one for visitors (usually Uncle Vernon\rquote s sister, Marge), one where Dudley slept, and one where Dudley kept all the toys and things that wouldn\rquote t fit into his first bedroom. It only took Harry one trip upstairs to move everything he owned from the cupboard to this room. He sat down on the bed and stared around him. Nearly everything in here was broken. The month-old video camera was lying on top of a small, working tank Dudley had once driven over the next door neighbor\rquote s dog; in the corner was Dudley\rquote s first-ever television set, which he\rquote d put his foot through when his favorite program had been canceled; there was a large birdcage, which had once held a parrot that Dudley had swapped at school for a real air rifle, which was up on a shelf with the end all bent because Dudley had sat on it. Other shelves were full of books. They were the only things in the room that looked as though they\rquote d never been touched.\par
From downstairs came the sound of Dudley bawling at his mother, \ldblquote I don\rquote t \i want \i0 him in there \'85 I \i need\i0  that room \'85 make him get out. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry sighed and stretched out on the bed. Yesterday he\rquote d have given anything to be up here. Today he\rquote d rather be back in his cup\-board with that letter than up here without it.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Next morning at breakfast, everyone was rather quiet. Dudley was in shock. He\rquote d screamed, whacked his father with his Smelting stick, been sick on purpose, kicked his mother, and thrown his tor\-toise through the greenhouse roof, and he still didn\rquote t have his room back. Harry was thinking about this time yesterday and bitterly wishing he\rquote d opened the letter in the hall. Uncle Vernon and Aunt Petunia kept looking at each other darkly.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj When the mail arrived, Uncle Vernon, who seemed to be trying to be nice to Harry, made Dudley go and get it. They heard him banging things with his Smelting stick all the way down the hall. Then he shouted, \ldblquote There\rquote s another one! \lquote Mr. H. Potter, The Small\-est Bedroom, 4 Privet Drive \emdash\rquote  \rdblquote\par
With a strangled cry, Uncle Vernon leapt from his seat and ran down the hall, Harry right behind him. Uncle Vernon had to wres\-tle Dudley to the ground to get the letter from him, which was made difficult by the fact that Harry had grabbed Uncle Vernon around the neck from behind. After a minute of confused fighting, in which everyone got hit a lot by the Smelting stick, Uncle Vernon straightened up, gasping for breath, with Harry\rquote s letter clutched in his hand.\par
\ldblquote Go to your cupboard \emdash  I mean, your bedroom,\rdblquote  he wheezed at Harry. \ldblquote Dudley \emdash  go \emdash  just go.\rdblquote\par
Harry walked round and round his new room. Someone knew he had moved out of his cupboard and they seemed to know he hadn\rquote t received his first letter. Surely that meant they\rquote d try again? And this time he\rquote d make sure they didn\rquote t fail. He had a plan.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The repaired alarm clock rang at six o\rquote clock the next morning. Harry turned it off quickly and dressed silently He mustn\rquote t wake the Dursleys. He stole downstairs without turning on any of the lights.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj He was going to wait for the postman on the corner of Privet Drive and get the letters for number four first. His heart hammered as he crept across the dark hall toward the front door \emdash\par
\ldblquote AAAAARRRGH!\rdblquote\par
Harry leapt into the air; he\rquote d trodden on something big and squashy on the doormat \emdash  something \i alive\i0 !\par
Lights clicked on upstairs and to his horror Harry realized that the big, squashy something had been his uncle\rquote s face. Uncle Vernon had been lying at the foot of the front door in a sleeping bag, clearly making sure that Harry didn\rquote t do exactly what he\rquote d been try\-ing to do. He shouted at Harry for about half an hour and then told him to go and make a cup of tea. Harry shuffled miserably off into the kitchen and by the time he got back, the mail had arrived, right into Uncle Vernon\rquote s lap. Harry could see three letters ad\-dressed in green ink.\par
\ldblquote I want \emdash\rdblquote  he began, but Uncle Vernon was tearing the letters into pieces before his eyes.\par
Uncle Vernon didn\rquote t go to work that day. He stayed at home and nailed up the mail slot.\par
\ldblquote See,\rdblquote  he explained to Aunt Petunia through a mouthful of nails, \ldblquote if they can\rquote t \i deliver \i0 them they\rquote ll just give up.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not sure that\rquote ll work, Vernon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, these peoples minds work in strange ways, Petunia, they\rquote re not like you and me,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, trying to knock in a nail with the piece of fruitcake Aunt Petunia had just brought him.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj On Friday, no less than twelve letters arrived for Harry. As they couldn\rquote t go through the mail slot they had been pushed under the door, slotted through the sides, and a few even forced through the small window in the downstairs bathroom.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Uncle Vernon stayed at home again. After burning all the letters, he got out a hammer and nails and boarded up the cracks around the front and back doors so no one could go out. He hummed \ldblquote Tiptoe Through the Tulips\rdblquote  as he worked, and jumped at small noises.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj On Saturday, things began to get out of hand. Twenty-four letters to Harry found their way into the house, rolled up and hidden in\-side each of the two dozen eggs that their very confused milkman had handed Aunt Petunia through the living room window. While Uncle Vernon made furious telephone calls to the post office and the dairy trying to find someone to complain to, Aunt Petunia shredded the letters in her food processor.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Who on earth wants to talk to \i you\i0  this badly?\rdblquote  Dudley asked Harry in amazement.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc *   *   *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj On Sunday morning, Uncle Vernon sat down at the breakfast table looking tired and rather ill, but happy.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote No post on Sundays,\rdblquote  he reminded them cheerfully as he spread marmalade on his newspapers, \ldblquote no damn letters today \emdash\rdblquote\par
Something came whizzing down the kitchen chimney as he spoke and caught him sharply on the back of the head. Next mo\-ment, thirty or forty letters came pelting out of the fireplace like bullets. The Dursleys ducked, but Harry leapt into the air trying to catch one \emdash\par
\ldblquote Out! OUT!\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon seized Harry around the waist and threw him into the hall. When Aunt Petunia and Dudley had run out with their arms over their faces, Uncle Vernon slammed the door shut. They could hear the letters still streaming into the room, bouncing off the walls and floor.\par
\ldblquote That does it,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, trying to speak calmly but pulling great tufts out of his mustache at the same time. \ldblquote I want you all back here in five minutes ready to leave. We\rquote re going away. Just pack some clothes. No arguments!\rdblquote\par
He looked so dangerous with half his mustache missing that no one dared argue. Ten minutes later they had wrenched their way through the boarded-up doors and were in the car, speeding toward the highway. Dudley was sniffling in the back seat; his father had hit him round the head for holding them up while he tried to pack his television, VCR, and computer in his sports bag.\par
They drove. And they drove. Even Aunt Petunia didn\rquote t dare ask where they were going. Every now and then Uncle Vernon would take a sharp turn and drive in the opposite direction for a while.\par
\ldblquote Shake \rquote em off \'85 shake \rquote em off,\rdblquote  he would mutter whenever he did this.\par
They didn\rquote t stop to eat or drink all day. By nightfall Dudley was howling. He\rquote d never had such a bad day in his life. He was hungry, he\rquote d missed five television programs he\rquote d wanted to see, and he\rquote d never gone so long without blowing up an alien on his computer.\par
Uncle Vernon stopped at last outside a gloomy-looking hotel on the outskirts of a big city. Dudley and Harry shared a room with twin beds and damp, musty sheets. Dudley snored but Harry stayed awake, sitting on the windowsill, staring down at the lights of passing cars and wondering. \'85\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj They ate stale cornflakes and cold tinned tomatoes on toast for breakfast the next day. They had just finished when the owner of the hotel came over to their table.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote  \rquote Scuse me, but is one of you Mr. H. Potter? Only I got about an \rquote undred of these at the front desk.\rdblquote\par
She held up a letter so they could read the green ink address:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li567\ri567\qj\i Mr. H. Potter\par
Room 17\par
Railview Hotel\par
Cokeworth\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i0\par
Harry made a grab for the letter but Uncle Vernon knocked his hand out of the way. The woman stared.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll take them,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, standing up quickly and fol\-lowing her from the dining room.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc *   *   *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj  \ldblquote Wouldn\rquote t it be better just to go home, dear?\rdblquote  Aunt Petunia suggested timidly, hours later, but Uncle Vernon didn\rquote t seem to hear her. Exactly what he was looking for, none of them knew. He drove them into the middle of a forest, got out, looked around, shook his head, got back in the car, and off they went again. The same thing happened in the middle of a plowed field, halfway across a suspension bridge, and at the top of a multilevel parking garage.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Daddy\rquote s gone mad, hasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  Dudley asked Aunt Petunia dully late that afternoon. Uncle Vernon had parked at the coast, locked them all inside the car, and disappeared.\par
It started to rain. Great drops beat on the roof of the car. Dud\-ley sniveled.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s Monday,\rdblquote  he told his mother. \ldblquote The Great Humberto\rquote s on tonight. I want to stay somewhere with a \i television.\rdblquote\i0\par
Monday. This reminded Harry of something. If it \i was \i0 Mon\-day \emdash  and you could usually count on Dudley to know the days of the week, because of television \emdash  then tomorrow, Tuesday, was Harry\rquote s eleventh birthday. Of course, his birthdays were never ex\-actly fun \emdash  last year, the Dursleys had given him a coat hanger and a pair of Uncle Vernon\rquote s old socks. Still, you weren\rquote t eleven every day.\par
Uncle Vernon was back and he was smiling. He was also carry\-ing a long, thin package and didn\rquote t answer Aunt Petunia when she asked what he\rquote d bought.\par
\ldblquote Found the perfect place!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Come on! Everyone out!\rdblquote\par
It was very cold outside the car. Uncle Vernon was pointing at what looked like a large rock way out at sea. Perched on top of the rock was the most miserable little shack you could imagine. One thing was certain, there was no television in there.\par
\ldblquote Storm forecast for tonight!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon gleefully, clap\-ping his hands together. \ldblquote And this gentleman\rquote s kindly agreed to lend us his boat!\rdblquote\par
A toothless old man came ambling up to them, pointing, with a rather wicked grin, at an old rowboat bobbing in the iron-gray water below them.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve already got us some rations,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, \ldblquote so all aboard!\rdblquote\par
It was freezing in the boat. Icy sea spray and rain crept down their necks and a chilly wind whipped their faces. After what seemed like hours they reached the rock, where Uncle Vernon, slip\-ping and sliding, led the way to the broken-down house.\par
The inside was horrible; it smelled strongly of seaweed, the wind whistled through the gaps in the wooden walls, and the fireplace was damp and empty. There were only two rooms.\par
Uncle Vernon\rquote s rations turned out to be a bag of chips each and four bananas. He tried to start a fire but the empty chip bags just smoked and shriveled up.\par
\ldblquote Could do with some of those letters now, eh?\rdblquote  he said cheer\-fully.\par
He was in a very good mood. Obviously he thought nobody stood a chance of reaching them here in a storm to deliver mail. Harry privately agreed, though the thought didn\rquote t cheer him up at all.\par
As night fell, the promised storm blew up around them. Spray from the high waves splattered the walls of the hut and a fierce wind rattled the filthy windows. Aunt Petunia found a few moldy blankets in the second room and made up a bed for Dudley on the moth-eaten sofa. She and Uncle Vernon went off to the lumpy bed next door, and Harry was left to find the softest bit of floor he could and to curl up under the thinnest, most ragged blanket.\par
The storm raged more and more ferociously as the night went on. Harry couldn\rquote t sleep. He shivered and turned over, trying to get comfortable, his stomach rumbling with hunger. Dudley\rquote s snores were drowned by the low rolls of thunder that started near mid\-night. The lighted dial of Dudley\rquote s watch, which was dangling over the edge of the sofa on his fat wrist, told Harry he\rquote d be eleven in ten minutes\rquote  time. He lay and watched his birthday tick nearer, won\-dering if the Dursleys would remember at all, wondering where the letter writer was now.\par
Five minutes to go. Harry heard something creak outside. He hoped the roof wasn\rquote t going to fall in, although he might be warmer if it did. Four minutes to go. Maybe the house in Privet Drive would be so full of letters when they got back that he\rquote d be able to steal one somehow.\par
Three minutes to go. Was that the sea, slapping hard on the rock like that? And (two minutes to go) what was that funny crunching noise? Was the rock crumbling into the sea?\par
One minute to go and he\rquote d be eleven. Thirty seconds \'85 twenty \'85 ten \'85 nine \emdash  maybe he\rquote d wake Dudley up, just to annoy him \emdash  three \'85 two \'85 one \'85\par
BOOM.\par
The whole shack shivered and Harry sat bolt upright, staring at the door. Someone was outside, knocking to come in.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\lang3081\page\fs36 Chapter 4\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Keeper Of The Keys\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj BOOM. They knocked again. Dudley jerked awake.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Where\rquote s the cannon?\rdblquote  he said stupidly.\par
There was a crash behind them and Uncle Vernon came skid\-ding into the room. He was holding a rifle in his hands \emdash  now they knew what had been in the long, thin package he had brought with them.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  he shouted. \ldblquote I warn you \emdash  I\rquote m armed!\rdblquote\par
There was a pause. Then \emdash\par
SMASH!\par
The door was hit with such force that it swung clean off its hinges and with a deafening crash landed flat on the floor.\par
A giant of a man was standing in the doorway. His face was al\-most completely hidden by a long, shaggy mane of hair and a wild, tangled beard, but you could make out his eyes, glinting like black beetles under all the hair.\par
The giant squeezed his way into the hut, stooping so that his head just brushed the ceiling. He bent down, picked up the door, and fitted it easily back into its frame. The noise of the storm out\-side dropped a little. He turned to look at them all.\par
\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t make us a cup o\rquote  tea, could yeh? It\rquote s not been an easy journey. \'85\rdblquote\par
He strode over to the sofa where Dudley sat frozen with fear.\par
\ldblquote Budge up, yeh great lump,\rdblquote  said the stranger.\par
Dudley squeaked and ran to hide behind his mother, who was crouching, terrified, behind Uncle Vernon.\par
\ldblquote An\rquote  here\rquote s Harry!\rdblquote  said the giant.\par
Harry looked up into the fierce, wild, shadowy face and saw that the beetle eyes were crinkled in a smile.\par
\ldblquote Las\rquote  time I saw you, you was only a baby,\rdblquote  said the giant. \ldblquote Yeh look a lot like yer dad, but yeh\rquote ve got yer mom\rquote s eyes.\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon made a funny rasping noise.\par
\ldblquote I demand that you leave at once, sir!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You are break\-ing and entering!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ah, shut up, Dursley, yeh great prune,\rdblquote  said the giant; he reached over the back of the sofa, jerked the gun out of Uncle Ver\-non\rquote s hands, bent it into a knot as easily as if it had been made of rubber, and threw it into a corner of the room.\par
Uncle Vernon made another funny noise, like a mouse being trodden on.\par
\ldblquote Anyway \emdash  Harry,\rdblquote  said the giant, turning his back on the Dursleys, \ldblquote a very happy birthday to yeh. Got summat fer yeh here \emdash  I mighta sat on it at some point, but it\rquote ll taste all right.\rdblquote\par
From an inside pocket of his black overcoat he pulled a slightly squashed box. Harry opened it with trembling fingers. Inside was a large, sticky chocolate cake with \i Happy Birthday Harry\i0  written on it in green icing.\par
Harry looked up at the giant. He meant to say thank you, but the words got lost on the way to his mouth, and what he said in\-stead was, \ldblquote Who are you?\rdblquote\par
The giant chuckled.\par
\ldblquote True, I haven\rquote t introduced meself. Rubeus Hagrid, Keeper of Keys and Grounds at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\par
He held out an enormous hand and shook Harry\rquote s whole arm.\par
\ldblquote What about that tea then, eh?\rdblquote  he said, rubbing his hands to\-gether. \ldblquote I\rquote d not say no ter summat stronger if yeh\rquote ve got it, mind.\rdblquote\par
His eyes fell on the empty grate with the shriveled chip bags in it and he snorted. He bent down over the fireplace; they couldn\rquote t see what he was doing but when he drew back a second later, there was a roaring fire there. It filled the whole damp hut with flickering light and Harry felt the warmth wash over him as though he\rquote d sunk into a hot bath.\par
The giant sat back down on the sofa, which sagged under his weight, and began taking all sorts of things out of the pockets of his coat: a copper kettle, a squashy package of sausages, a poker, a teapot, several chipped mugs, and a bottle of some amber liquid that he took a swig from before starting to make tea. Soon the hut was full of the sound and smell of sizzling sausage. Nobody said a thing while the giant was working, but as he slid the first six fat, juicy, slightly burnt sausages from the poker, Dudley fidgeted a lit\-tle. Uncle Vernon said sharply, \ldblquote Don\rquote t touch anything he gives you, Dudley.\rdblquote\par
The giant chuckled darkly.\par
\ldblquote Yer great puddin\rquote  of a son don\rquote  need fattenin\rquote  anymore, Durs\-ley, don\rquote  worry.\rdblquote\par
He passed the sausages to Harry, who was so hungry he had never tasted anything so wonderful, but he still couldn\rquote t take his eyes off the giant. Finally, as nobody seemed about to explain any\-thing, he said, \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, but I still don\rquote t really know who you are.\rdblquote\par
The giant took a gulp of tea and wiped his mouth with the back of his hand.\par
\ldblquote Call me Hagrid,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote everyone does. An\rquote  like I told yeh, I\rquote m Keeper of Keys at Hogwarts \emdash  yeh\rquote ll know all about Hog\-warts, o\rquote  course.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  no,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Hagrid looked shocked.\par
\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  Harry said quickly.\par
\i\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote\i0  barked Hagrid, turning to stare at the Dursleys, who shrank back into the shadows. \ldblquote It\rquote s them as should be sorry! I knew yeh weren\rquote t gettin\rquote  yer letters but I never thought yeh wouldn\rquote t even know abou\rquote  Hogwarts, fer cryin\rquote  out loud! Did yeh never wonder where yer parents learned it all?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All what?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\par
\ldblquote ALL WHAT?\rdblquote  Hagrid thundered. \ldblquote Now wait jus\rquote  one second!\rdblquote\par
He had leapt to his feet. In his anger he seemed to fill the whole hut. The Dursleys were cowering against the wall.\par
\ldblquote Do you mean ter tell me,\rdblquote  he growled at the Dursleys, \ldblquote that this boy \emdash  this boy! \emdash  knows nothin\rquote  abou\rquote  \emdash  about ANYTHING?\rdblquote\par
Harry thought this was going a bit far. He had been to school, after all, and his marks weren\rquote t bad.\par
\ldblquote I know \i some\i0  things,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I can, you know, do math and stuff.\rdblquote\par
