\ldblquote Well, their main job is to keep it from the Muggles that there\rquote s still witches an\rquote  wizards up an\rquote  down the country.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\i\ldblquote Why? \i0 Blimey, Harry, everyone\rquote d be wantin\rquote  magic solutions to their problems. Nah, we\rquote re best left alone.\rdblquote\par
At this moment the boat bumped gently into the harbor wall. Hagrid folded up his newspaper, and they clambered up the stone steps onto the street.\par
Passersby stared a lot at Hagrid as they walked through the little town to the station. Harry couldn\rquote t blame them. Not only was Ha\-grid twice as tall as anyone else, he kept pointing at perfectly ordi\-nary things like parking meters and saying loudly, \ldblquote See that, Harry? Things these Muggles dream up, eh?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Harry, panting a bit as he ran to keep up, \ldblquote did you say there are \i dragons\i0  at Gringotts?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, so they say,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Crikey, I\rquote d like a dragon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote d \i like\i0  one?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wanted one ever since I was a kid \emdash  here we go.\rdblquote\par
They had reached the station. There was a train to London in five minutes\rquote  time. Hagrid, who didn\rquote t understand \ldblquote Muggle money,\rdblquote  as he called it, gave the bills to Harry so he could buy their tickets.\par
People stared more than ever on the train. Hagrid took up two seats and sat knitting what looked like a canary-yellow circus tent.\par
\ldblquote Still got yer letter, Harry?\rdblquote  he asked as he counted stitches.\par
Harry took the parchment envelope out of his pocket.\par
\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote There\rquote s a list there of everything yeh need.\rdblquote\par
Harry unfolded a second piece of paper he hadn\rquote t noticed the night before, and read:\par
