\pard\nowidctlpar\qj\ldblquote Can we buy all this in London?\rdblquote  Harry wondered aloud.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote If yeh know where to go,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry had never been to London before. Although Hagrid seemed to know where he was going, he was obviously not used to getting there in an ordinary way. He got stuck in the ticket barrier on the Underground, and complained loudly that the seats were too small and the trains too slow.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote I don\rquote t know how the Muggles manage without magic,\rdblquote  he said as they climbed a broken-down escalator that led up to a bustling road lined with shops.\par
Hagrid was so huge that he parted the crowd easily; all Harry had to do was keep close behind him. They passed book shops and music stores, hamburger restaurants and cinemas, but nowhere that looked as if it could sell you a magic wand. This was just an ordinary street full of ordinary people. Could there really be piles of wizard gold buried miles beneath them? Were there really shops that sold spell books and broomsticks? Might this not all be some huge joke that the Dursleys had cooked up? If Harry hadn\rquote t known that the Dursleys had no sense of humor, he might have thought so; yet somehow, even though everything Hagrid had told him so far was unbelievable, Harry couldn\rquote t help trusting him.\par
\ldblquote This is it,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, coming to a halt, \ldblquote the Leaky Cauldron. It\rquote s a famous place.\rdblquote\par
It was a tiny, grubby-looking pub. If Hagrid hadn\rquote t pointed it out, Harry wouldn\rquote t have noticed it was there. The people hurrying by didn\rquote t glance at it. Their eyes slid from the big book shop on one side to the record shop on the other as if they couldn\rquote t see the Leaky Cauldron at all. In fact, Harry had the most peculiar feeling that only he and Hagrid could see it. Before he could mention this, Ha\-grid had steered him inside.\par
For a famous place, it was very dark and shabby. A few old women were sitting in a corner, drinking tiny glasses of sherry. One of them was smoking a long pipe. A little man in a top hat was talk\-ing to the old bartender, who was quite bald and looked like a toothless walnut. The low buzz of chatter stopped when they walked in. Everyone seemed to know Hagrid; they waved and smiled at him, and the bartender reached for a glass, saying, \ldblquote The usual, Hagrid?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t, Tom, I\rquote m on Hogwarts business,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, clapping his great hand on Harry\rquote s shoulder and making Harry\rquote s knees buckle.\par
\ldblquote Good Lord,\rdblquote  said the bartender, peering at Harry, \ldblquote is this \emdash  can this be \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
The Leaky Cauldron had suddenly gone completely still and silent.\par
\ldblquote Bless my soul,\rdblquote  whispered the old bartender, \ldblquote Harry Potter \'85 what an honor.\rdblquote\par
He hurried out from behind the bar, rushed toward Harry and seized his hand, tears in his eyes.\par
\ldblquote Welcome back, Mr. Potter, welcome back.\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t know what to say. Everyone was looking at him. The old woman with the pipe was puffing on it without realizing it had gone out. Hagrid was beaming.\par
Then there was a great scraping of chairs and the next moment, Harry found himself shaking hands with everyone in the Leaky Cauldron.\par
\ldblquote Doris Crockford, Mr. Potter, can\rquote t believe I\rquote m meeting you at last.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So proud, Mr. Potter, I\rquote m just so proud.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Always wanted to shake your hand \emdash  I\rquote m all of a flutter.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Delighted, Mr. Potter, just can\rquote t tell you, Diggle\rquote s the name, Dedalus Diggle.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve seen you before!\rdblquote  said Harry, as Dedalus Diggle\rquote s top hat fell off in his excitement. \ldblquote You bowed to me once in a shop.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He remembers!\rdblquote  cried Dedalus Diggle, looking around at everyone. \ldblquote Did you hear that? He remembers me!\rdblquote\par
Harry shook hands again and again \emdash  Doris Crockford kept coming back for more.\par
A pale young man made his way forward, very nervously. One of his eyes was twitching.\par
\ldblquote Professor Quirrell!\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Harry, Professor Quirrell will be one of your teachers at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote P-P-Potter,\rdblquote  stammered Professor Quirrell, grasping Harry\rquote s hand, \ldblquote c-can\rquote t t-tell you how p-pleased I am to meet you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What sort of magic do you teach, Professor Quirrell?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote D-Defense Against the D-D-Dark Arts,\rdblquote  muttered Professor Quirrell, as though he\rquote d rather not think about it. \ldblquote N-not that you n-need it, eh, P-P-Potter?\rdblquote  He laughed nervously. \ldblquote You\rquote ll be g-getting all your equipment, I suppose? I\rquote ve g-got to p-pick up a new b-book on vampires, m-myself.\rdblquote  He looked terrified at the very thought.\par
But the others wouldn\rquote t let Professor Quirrell keep Harry to himself. It took almost ten minutes to get away from them all. At last, Hagrid managed to make himself heard over the babble.\par
\ldblquote Must get on \emdash  lots ter buy. Come on, Harry.\rdblquote\par
Doris Crockford shook Harry\rquote s hand one last time, and Hagrid led them through the bar and out into a small, walled courtyard, where there was nothing but a trash can and a few weeds.\par
Hagrid grinned at Harry.\par
\ldblquote Told yeh, didn\rquote t I? Told yeh you was famous. Even Professor Quirrell was tremblin\rquote  ter meet yeh \emdash  mind you, he\rquote s usually trem\-blin\rquote .\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is he always that nervous?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, yeah. Poor bloke. Brilliant mind. He was fine while he was studyin\rquote  outta books but then he took a year off ter get some first\-hand experience. \'85 They say he met vampires in the Black Forest, and there was a nasty bit o\rquote  trouble with a hag \emdash  never been the same since. Scared of the students, scared of his own subject \emdash  now, where\rquote s me umbrella?\rdblquote\par
Vampires? Hags? Harry\rquote s head was swimming. Hagrid, mean\-while, was counting bricks in the wall above the trash can.\par
\ldblquote Three up \'85 two across \'85\rdblquote  he muttered. \ldblquote Right, stand back, Harry.\rdblquote\par
He tapped the wall three times with the point of his umbrella.\par
The brick he had touched quivered \emdash  it wriggled \emdash  in the middle, a small hole appeared \emdash  it grew wider and wider \emdash  a sec\-ond later they were facing an archway large enough even for Ha\-grid, an archway onto a cobbled street that twisted and turned out of sight.\par
\ldblquote Welcome,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote to Diagon Alley.\rdblquote\par
He grinned at Harry\rquote s amazement. They stepped through the archway. Harry looked quickly over his shoulder and saw the arch\-way shrink instantly back into solid wall.\par
The sun shone brightly on a stack of cauldrons outside the near\-est shop. Cauldrons \emdash  All Sizes \emdash  Copper, Brass, Pewter, Sil\-ver \emdash  Self-Stirring \emdash  Collapsible, said a sign hanging over them.\par
\ldblquote Yeah, you\rquote ll be needin\rquote  one,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote but we gotta get yer money first.\rdblquote\par
Harry wished he had about eight more eyes. He turned his head in every direction as they walked up the street, trying to look at everything at once: the shops, the things outside them, the people doing their shopping. A plump woman outside an Apothecary was shaking her head as they passed, saying, \ldblquote Dragon liver, sixteen Sickles an ounce, they\rquote re mad.\par
A low, soft hooting came from a dark shop with a sign saying Eeylops Owl Emporium \emdash  Tawny, Screech, Barn, Brown, and Snowy. Several boys of about Harry\rquote s age had their noses pressed against a window with broomsticks in it. \ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  Harry heard one of them say, \ldblquote the new Nimbus Two Thousand \emdash  fastest ever \emdash\rdblquote  There were shops selling robes, shops selling telescopes and strange silver instruments Harry had never seen before, windows stacked with barrels of bat spleens and eels\rquote  eyes, tottering piles of spell books, quills, and rolls of parchment, potion bottles, globes of the moon. \'85\par
\ldblquote Gringotts,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
They had reached a snowy white building that towered over the other little shops. Standing beside its burnished bronze doors, wearing a uniform of scarlet and gold, was \emdash\par
\ldblquote Yeah, that\rquote s a goblin,\rdblquote  said Hagrid quietly as they walked up the white stone steps toward him. The goblin was about a head shorter than Harry. He had a swarthy, clever face, a pointed beard and, Harry noticed, very long fingers and feet. He bowed as they walked inside. Now they were facing a second pair of doors, silver this time, with words engraved upon them:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li567\ri567\i Enter, stranger, but take heed\par
Of what awaits the sin of greed,\par
For those who take, but do not earn,\par
Must pay most dearly in their turn.\par
So if you seek beneath our floors\par
A treasure that was never yours,\i0\par
\i Thief, you have been warned, beware\par
Of finding more than treasure there.\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj\ldblquote Like I said, yeh\rquote d be mad ter try an\rquote  rob it,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj A pair of goblins bowed them through the silver doors and they were in a vast marble hall. About a hundred more goblins were sit\-ting on high stools behind a long counter, scribbling in large ledgers, weighing coins in brass scales, examining precious stones through eyeglasses. There were too many doors to count leading off the hall, and yet more goblins were showing people in and out of these. Hagrid and Harry made for the counter.\par
\ldblquote Morning,\rdblquote  said Hagrid to a free goblin. \ldblquote We\rquote ve come ter take some money outta Mr. Harry Potter\rquote s safe.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You have his key, sir?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Got it here somewhere,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, and he started emptying his pockets onto the counter, scattering a handful of moldy dog biscuits over the goblins book of numbers. The goblin wrinkled his nose. Harry watched the goblin on their right weighing a pile of ru\-bies as big as glowing coals.\par
\ldblquote Got it,\rdblquote  said Hagrid at last, holding up a tiny golden key.\par
The goblin looked at it closely.\par
\ldblquote That seems to be in order.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote An\rquote  I\rquote ve also got a letter here from Professor Dumbledore,\rdblquote  said Hagrid importantly, throwing out his chest. \ldblquote It\rquote s about the You-Know-What in vault seven hundred and thirteen.\rdblquote\par
The goblin read the letter carefully.\par
\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  he said, handing it back to Hagrid, \ldblquote I will have someone take you down to both vaults. Griphook!\rdblquote\par
Griphook was yet another goblin. Once Hagrid had crammed all the dog biscuits back inside his pockets, he and Harry followed Griphook toward one of the doors leading off the hall.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s the You-Know-What in vault seven hundred and thir\-teen?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t tell yeh that,\rdblquote  said Hagrid mysteriously. \ldblquote Very secret. Hogwarts business. Dumbledore\rquote s trusted me. More\rquote n my job\rquote s worth ter tell yeh that.\rdblquote\par
Griphook held the door open for them. Harry, who had ex\-pected more marble, was surprised. They were in a narrow stone passageway lit with flaming torches. It sloped steeply down\-ward and there were little railway tracks on the floor. Griphook whistled and a small cart came hurtling up the tracks toward them. They climbed in \emdash  Hagrid with some difficulty \emdash  and were off.\par
At first they just hurtled through a maze of twisting passages. Harry tried to remember, left, right, right, left, middle fork, right, left, but it was impossible. The rattling cart seemed to know its own way, because Griphook wasn\rquote t steering.\par
Harry\rquote s eyes stung as the cold air rushed past them, but he kept them wide open. Once, he thought he saw a burst of fire at the end of a passage and twisted around to see if it was a dragon, but too late \emdash  they plunged even deeper, passing an underground lake where huge stalactites and stalagmites grew from the ceiling and floor.\par
\ldblquote I never know,\rdblquote  Harry called to Hagrid over the noise of the cart, \ldblquote what\rquote s the difference between a stalagmite and a stalactite?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Stalagmite\rquote s got an \lquote m\rquote  in it,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote An\rquote  don\rquote  ask me questions just now, I think I\rquote m gonna be sick.\rdblquote\par
He did look very green, and when the cart stopped at last beside a small door in the passage wall, Hagrid got out and had to lean against the wall to stop his knees from trembling.\par
Griphook unlocked the door. A lot of green smoke came billow\-ing out, and as it cleared, Harry gasped. Inside were mounds of gold coins. Columns of silver. Heaps of little bronze Knuts.\par
\ldblquote All yours,\rdblquote  smiled Hagrid.\par
All Harry\rquote s \emdash  it was incredible. The Dursleys couldn\rquote t have known about this or they\rquote d have had it from him faster than blink\-ing. How often had they complained how much Harry cost them to keep? And all the time there had been a small fortune belonging to him, buried deep under London.\par
Hagrid helped Harry pile some of it into a bag.\par
\ldblquote The gold ones are Galleons,\rdblquote  he explained. \ldblquote Seventeen silver Sickles to a Galleon and twenty-nine Knuts to a Sickle, it\rquote s easy enough. Right, that should be enough fer a couple o\rquote  terms, we\rquote ll keep the rest safe for yeh.\rdblquote  He turned to Griphook. \ldblquote Vault seven hundred and thirteen now, please, and can we go more slowly?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote One speed only,\rdblquote  said Griphook.\par
They were going even deeper now and gathering speed. The air became colder and colder as they hurtled round tight corners. They went rattling over an underground ravine, and Harry leaned over the side to try to see what was down at the dark bottom, but Ha\-grid groaned and pulled him back by the scruff of his neck.\par
Vault seven hundred and thirteen had no keyhole.\par
\ldblquote Stand back,\rdblquote  said Griphook importantly. He stroked the door gently with one of his long fingers and it simply melted away.\par
\ldblquote If anyone but a Gringotts goblin tried that, they\rquote d be sucked through the door and trapped in there,\rdblquote  said Griphook.\par
\ldblquote How often do you check to see if anyone\rquote s inside?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
\ldblquote About once every ten years,\rdblquote  said Griphook with a rather nasty grin.\par
Something really extraordinary had to be inside this top security vault, Harry was sure, and he leaned forward eagerly, expecting to see fabulous jewels at the very least \emdash  but at first he thought it was empty. Then he noticed a grubby little package wrapped up in brown paper lying on the floor. Hagrid picked it up and tucked it deep inside his coat. Harry longed to know what it was, but knew better than to ask.\par
\ldblquote Come on, back in this infernal cart, and don\rquote t talk to me on the way back, it\rquote s best if I keep me mouth shut,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj One wild cart ride later they stood blinking in the sunlight outside Gringotts. Harry didn\rquote t know where to run first now that he had a bag full of money. He didn\rquote t have to know how many Galleons there were to a pound to know that he was holding more money than he\rquote d had in his whole life \emdash  more money than even Dudley had ever had.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Might as well get yer uniform,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, nodding toward Madam Malkin\rquote s Robes for All Occasions. \ldblquote Listen, Harry, would yeh mind if I slipped off fer a pick-me-up in the Leaky Cauldron? I hate them Gringotts carts.\rdblquote  He did still look a bit sick, so Harry entered Madam Malkin\rquote s shop alone, feeling nervous.\par
Madam Malkin was a squat, smiling witch dressed all in mauve.\par
\ldblquote Hogwarts, dear?\rdblquote  she said, when Harry started to speak. \ldblquote Got the lot here \emdash  another young man being fitted up just now, in fact.\rdblquote\par
In the back of the shop, a boy with a pale, pointed face was standing on a footstool while a second witch pinned up his long black robes. Madam Malkin stood Harry on a stool next to him, slipped a long robe over his head, and began to pin it to the right length.\par
\ldblquote Hello,\rdblquote  said the boy, \ldblquote Hogwarts, too?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote My father\rquote s next door buying my books and mother\rquote s up the street looking at wands,\rdblquote  said the boy. He had a bored, drawling voice. \ldblquote Then I\rquote m going to drag them off to look at racing brooms. I don\rquote t see why first years can\rquote t have their own. I think I\rquote ll bully fa\-ther into getting me one and I\rquote ll smuggle it in somehow.\rdblquote\par
Harry was strongly reminded of Dudley.\par
\ldblquote Have \i you\i0  got your own broom?\rdblquote  the boy went on.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Play Quidditch at all?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Harry said again, wondering what on earth Quidditch could be.\par
\i\ldblquote I\i0  do \emdash  Father says it\rquote s a crime if I\rquote m not picked to play for my House, and I must say, I agree. Know what House you\rquote ll be in yet?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, feeling more stupid by the minute.\par
\ldblquote Well, no one really knows until they get there, do they, but I know I\rquote ll be in Slytherin, all our family have been \emdash  imagine be\-ing in Hufflepuff, I think I\rquote d leave, wouldn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mmm,\rdblquote  said Harry, wishing he could say something a bit more interesting.\par
\ldblquote I say, look at that man!\rdblquote  said the boy suddenly, nodding toward the front window. Hagrid was standing there, grinning at Harry and pointing at two large ice creams to show he couldn\rquote t come in.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Harry, pleased to know something the boy didn\rquote t. \ldblquote He works at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said the boy, \ldblquote I\rquote ve heard of him. He\rquote s a sort of servant, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s the gamekeeper,\rdblquote  said Harry. He was liking the boy less and less every second.\par
\ldblquote Yes, exactly. I heard he\rquote s a sort of \i savage\i0  \emdash  lives in a hut on the school grounds and every now and then he gets drunk, tries to do magic, and ends up setting fire to his bed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I think he\rquote s brilliant,\rdblquote  said Harry coldly.\par
\i\ldblquote Do\i0  you?\rdblquote  said the boy, with a slight sneer. \ldblquote Why is he with you? Where are your parents?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re dead,\rdblquote  said Harry shortly. He didn\rquote t feel much like go\-ing into the matter with this boy.\par
\ldblquote Oh, sorry,\rdblquote  said the other, not sounding sorry at all. \ldblquote But they were \i our\i0  kind, weren\rquote t they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They were a witch and wizard, if that\rquote s what you mean.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I really don\rquote t think they should let the other sort in, do you? They\rquote re just not the same, they\rquote ve never been brought up to know our ways. Some of them have never even heard of Hogwarts until they get the letter, imagine. I think they should keep it in the old wizarding families. What\rquote s your surname, anyway?\rdblquote\par
But before Harry could answer, Madam Malkin said, \ldblquote That\rquote s you done, my dear,\rdblquote  and Harry, not sorry for an excuse to stop talk\-ing to the boy, hopped down from the footstool.\par
\ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll see you at Hogwarts, I suppose,\rdblquote  said the drawling boy.\par
Harry was rather quiet as he ate the ice cream Hagrid had bought him (chocolate and raspberry with chopped nuts).\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s up?\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  Harry lied. They stopped to buy parchment and quills. Harry cheered up a bit when he found a bottle of ink that changed color as you wrote. When they had left the shop, he said, \ldblquote Hagrid, what\rquote s Quidditch?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Blimey, Harry, I keep forgettin\rquote  how little yeh know \emdash  not knowin\rquote  about Quidditch!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t make me feel worse,\rdblquote  said Harry. He told Hagrid about the pale boy in Madam Malkin\rquote s.\par
\ldblquote\emdash  and he said people from Muggle families shouldn\rquote t even be allowed in \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yer not \i from\i0  a Muggle family. If he\rquote d known who yeh \i were\i0  \emdash  he\rquote s grown up knowin\rquote  yer name if his parents are wizardin\rquote  folk. You saw what everyone in the Leaky Cauldron was like when they saw yeh. Anyway, what does he know about it, some o\rquote  the best I ever saw were the only ones with magic in \rquote em in a long line o\rquote  Muggles \emdash  look at yer mum! Look what she had fer a sister!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So what \i is\i0  Quidditch?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s our sport. Wizard sport. It\rquote s like \emdash  like soccer in the Muggle world \emdash  everyone follows Quidditch \emdash  played up in the air on broomsticks and there\rquote s four balls \emdash  sorta hard ter explain the rules.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what are Slytherin and Hufflepuff?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote School Houses. There\rquote s four. Everyone says Hufflepuff are a lot o\rquote  duffers, but \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I bet I\rquote m in Hufflepuff,\rdblquote  said Harry gloomily.\par
\ldblquote Better Hufflepuff than Slytherin,\rdblquote  said Hagrid darkly. \ldblquote There\rquote s not a single witch or wizard who went bad who wasn\rquote t in Slytherin. You-Know-Who was one.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Vol-, sorry \emdash  You-Know-Who was at Hogwarts?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Years an\rquote  years ago,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
They bought Harry\rquote s school books in a shop called Flourish and Blotts where the shelves were stacked to the ceiling with books as large as paving stones bound in leather; books the size of postage stamps in covers of silk; books full of peculiar symbols and a few books with nothing in them at all. Even Dudley, who never read anything, would have been wild to get his hands on some of these. Hagrid almost had to drag Harry away from \i Curses and Counter-curses (Bewitch Your Friends and Befuddle Your Enemies with the Latest Revenges: Hair Loss, Jelly-Legs, Tongue-Tying and Much, Much More)\i0  by Professor Vindictus Viridian.\par
\ldblquote I was trying to find out how to curse Dudley.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not sayin\rquote  that\rquote s not a good idea, but yer not ter use magic in the Muggle world except in very special circumstances,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote An\rquote  anyway, yeh couldn\rquote  work any of them curses yet, yeh\rquote ll need a lot more study before yeh get ter that level.\rdblquote\par
Hagrid wouldn\rquote t let Harry buy a solid gold cauldron, either (\ldblquote It says pewter on yer list\rdblquote ), but they got a nice set of scales for weigh\-ing potion ingredients and a collapsible brass telescope. Then they visited the Apothecary, which was fascinating enough to make up for its horrible smell, a mixture of bad eggs and rotted cabbages. Barrels of slimy stuff stood on the floor; jars of herbs, dried roots, and bright powders lined the walls; bundles of feathers, strings of fangs, and snarled claws hung from the ceiling. While Hagrid asked the man behind the counter for a supply of some basic po\-tion ingredients for Harry, Harry himself examined silver unicorn horns at twenty-one Galleons each and minuscule, glittery-black beetle eyes (five Knuts a scoop).\par
Outside the Apothecary, Hagrid checked Harry\rquote s list again.\par
\ldblquote Just yer wand left \emdash  oh yeah, an\rquote  I still haven\rquote t got yeh a birth\-day present.\rdblquote\par
Harry felt himself go red.\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t have to \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know I don\rquote t have to. Tell yeh what, I\rquote ll get yer animal. Not a toad, toads went outta fashion years ago, yeh\rquote d be laughed at \emdash  an\rquote  I don\rquote  like cats, they make me sneeze. I\rquote ll get yer an owl. All the kids want owls, they\rquote re dead useful, carry yer mail an\rquote  everythin\rquote .\rdblquote\par
Twenty minutes later, they left Eeylops Owl Emporium, which had been dark and full of rustling and flickering, jewel-bright eyes. Harry now carried a large cage that held a beautiful snowy owl, fast asleep with her head under her wing. He couldn\rquote t stop stammering his thanks, sounding just like Professor Quirrell.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote  mention it,\rdblquote  said Hagrid gruffly. \ldblquote Don\rquote  expect you\rquote ve had a lotta presents from them Dursleys. Just Ollivanders left now \emdash  only place fer wands, Ollivanders, and yeh gotta have the best wand.\rdblquote\par
A magic wand \'85 this was what Harry had been really looking forward to.\par
The last shop was narrow and shabby. Peeling gold letters over the door read Ollivanders: Makers of Fine Wands since 382b.c. A single wand lay on a faded purple cushion in the dusty window.\par
A tinkling bell rang somewhere in the depths of the shop as they stepped inside. It was a tiny place, empty except for a single, spindly chair that Hagrid sat on to wait. Harry felt strangely as though he had entered a very strict library; he swallowed a lot of new questions that had just occurred to him and looked instead at the thousands of narrow boxes piled neatly right up to the ceiling. For some reason, the back of his neck prickled. The very dust and silence in here seemed to tingle with some secret magic.\par
\ldblquote Good afternoon,\rdblquote  said a soft voice. Harry jumped. Hagrid must have jumped, too, because there was a loud crunching noise and he got quickly off the spindly chair.\par
An old man was standing before them, his wide, pale eyes shin\-ing like moons through the gloom of the shop.\par
\ldblquote Hello,\rdblquote  said Harry awkwardly.\par
\ldblquote Ah yes,\rdblquote  said the man. \ldblquote Yes, yes. I thought I\rquote d be seeing you soon. Harry Potter.\rdblquote  It wasn\rquote t a question. \ldblquote You have your mother\rquote s eyes. It seems only yesterday she was in here herself, buying her first wand. Ten and a quarter inches long, swishy, made of willow. Nice wand for charm work.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Ollivander moved closer to Harry. Harry wished he would blink. Those silvery eyes were a bit creepy.\par
\ldblquote Your father, on the other hand, favored a mahogany wand. Eleven inches. Pliable. A little more power and excellent for trans\-figuration. Well, I say your father favored it \emdash  it\rquote s really the wand that chooses the wizard, of course.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Ollivander had come so close that he and Harry were almost nose to nose. Harry could see himself reflected in those misty eyes.\par
\ldblquote And that\rquote s where \'85\rdblquote\par
Mr. Ollivander touched the lightning scar on Harry\rquote s forehead with a long, white finger.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry to say I sold the wand that did it,\rdblquote  he said softly. \ldblquote Thirteen-and-a-half inches. Yew. Powerful wand, very powerful, and in the wrong hands \'85 well, if I\rquote d known what that wand was going out into the world to do. \'85\rdblquote\par
He shook his head and then, to Harry\rquote s relief, spotted Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote Rubeus! Rubeus Hagrid! How nice to see you again. \'85 Oak, sixteen inches, rather bendy, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was, sir, yes,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote Good wand, that one. But I suppose they snapped it in half when you got expelled?\rdblquote  said Mr. Ollivander, suddenly stern.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  yes, they did, yes,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, shuffling his feet. \ldblquote I\rquote ve still got the pieces, though,\rdblquote  he added brightly.\par
\ldblquote But you don\rquote t \i use\i0  them?\rdblquote  said Mr. Ollivander sharply.\par
\ldblquote Oh, no, sir,\rdblquote  said Hagrid quickly. Harry noticed he gripped his pink umbrella very tightly as he spoke.\par
\ldblquote Hmmm,\rdblquote  said Mr. Ollivander, giving Hagrid a piercing look. \ldblquote Well, now \emdash  Mr. Potter. Let me see.\rdblquote  He pulled a long tape mea\-sure with silver markings out of his pocket. \ldblquote Which is your wand arm?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  well, I\rquote m right-handed,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Hold out your arm. That\rquote s it.\rdblquote  He measured Harry from shoul\-der to finger, then wrist to elbow, shoulder to floor, knee to armpit and round his head. As he measured, he said, \ldblquote Every Ollivander wand has a core of a powerful magical substance, Mr. Potter. We use unicorn hairs, phoenix tail feathers, and the heartstrings of dragons. No two Ollivander wands are the same, just as no two unicorns, dragons, or phoenixes are quite the same. And of course, you will never get such good results with another wizard\rquote s wand.\rdblquote\par
Harry suddenly realized that the tape measure, which was mea\-suring between his nostrils, was doing this on its own. Mr. Olli\-vander was flitting around the shelves, taking down boxes.\par
\ldblquote That will do,\rdblquote  he said, and the tape measure crumpled into a heap on the floor. \ldblquote Right then, Mr. Potter. Try this one. Beech-wood and dragon heartstring. Nine inches. Nice and flexible. Just take it and give it a wave.\rdblquote\par
Harry took the wand and (feeling foolish) waved it around a bit, but Mr. Ollivander snatched it out of his hand almost at once.\par
\ldblquote Maple and phoenix feather.  Seven inches.  Quite whippy. Try \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry tried \emdash  but he had hardly raised the wand when it, too, was snatched back by Mr. Ollivander.\par
\ldblquote No, no \emdash  here, ebony and unicorn hair, eight and a half inches, springy. Go on, go on, try it out.\rdblquote\par
Harry tried. And tried. He had no idea what Mr. Ollivander was waiting for. The pile of tried wands was mounting higher and higher on the spindly chair, but the more wands Mr. Ollivander pulled from the shelves, the happier he seemed to become.\par
\ldblquote Tricky customer, eh? Not to worry, we\rquote ll find the perfect match here somewhere \emdash  I wonder, now \emdash  yes, why not \emdash  unusual combination \emdash  holly and phoenix feather, eleven inches, nice and supple.\rdblquote\par
Harry took the wand. He felt a sudden warmth in his fingers. He raised the wand above his head, brought it swishing down through the dusty air and a stream of red and gold sparks shot from the end like a firework, throwing dancing spots of light on to the walls. Hagrid whooped and clapped and Mr. Ollivander cried, \ldblquote Oh, bravo! Yes, indeed, oh, very good. Well, well, well \'85 how curious \'85 how very curious \'85\rdblquote\par
He put Harry\rquote s wand back into its box and wrapped it in brown paper, still muttering, \ldblquote Curious \'85 curious \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but \i what\rquote s\i0  curious?\rdblquote\par
Mr. Ollivander fixed Harry with his pale stare.\par
\ldblquote I remember every wand I\rquote ve ever sold, Mr. Potter. Every single wand. It so happens that the phoenix whose tail feather is in your wand, gave another feather \emdash  just one other. It is very curious in\-deed that you should be destined for this wand when its brother \emdash  why, its brother gave you that scar.\rdblquote\par
Harry swallowed.\par
\ldblquote Yes, thirteen-and-a-half inches. Yew. Curious indeed how these things happen. The wand chooses the wizard, remember. \'85 I think we must expect great things from you, Mr. Potter. \'85 After all, He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named did great things \emdash  terrible, yes, but great.\rdblquote\par
Harry shivered. He wasn\rquote t sure he liked Mr. Ollivander too much. He paid seven gold Galleons for his wand, and Mr. Olli\-vander bowed them from his shop.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The late afternoon sun hung low in the sky as Harry and Hagrid made their way back down Diagon Alley, back through the wall, back through the Leaky Cauldron, now empty. Harry didn\rquote t speak at all as they walked down the road; he didn\rquote t even notice how much people were gawking at them on the Underground, laden as they were with all their funny-shaped packages, with the snowy owl asleep in its cage on Harry\rquote s lap. Up another escalator, out into Paddington station; Harry only realized where they were when Ha\-grid tapped him on the shoulder.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Got time fer a bite to eat before yer train leaves,\rdblquote  he said.\par
He bought Harry a hamburger and they sat down on plastic seats to eat them. Harry kept looking around. Everything looked so strange, somehow.\par
\ldblquote You all right, Harry? Yer very quiet,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
Harry wasn\rquote t sure he could explain. He\rquote d just had the best birth\-day of his life \emdash  and yet \emdash  he chewed his hamburger, trying to find the words.\par
\ldblquote Everyone thinks I\rquote m special,\rdblquote  he said at last. \ldblquote All those people in the Leaky Cauldron, Professor Quirrell, Mr. Ollivander \'85 but I don\rquote t know anything about magic at all. How can they expect great things? I\rquote m famous and I can\rquote t even remember what I\rquote m famous for. I don\rquote t know what happened when Vol-, sorry \emdash  I mean, the night my parents died.\rdblquote\par
Hagrid leaned across the table. Behind the wild beard and eye\-brows he wore a very kind smile.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote  you worry, Harry. You\rquote ll learn fast enough. Everyone starts at the beginning at Hogwarts, you\rquote ll be just fine. Just be yer\-self. I know it\rquote s hard. Yeh\rquote ve been singled out, an\rquote  that\rquote s always hard. But yeh\rquote ll have a great time at Hogwarts \emdash  I did \emdash  still do, \rquote smat\-ter of fact.\rdblquote\par
Hagrid helped Harry on to the train that would take him back to the Dursleys, then handed him an envelope.\par
\ldblquote Yer ticket fer Hogwarts,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote First o\rquote  September \emdash  King\rquote s Cross \emdash  it\rquote s all on yer ticket. Any problems with the Dursleys, send me a letter with yer owl, she\rquote ll know where to find me. \'85 See yeh soon, Harry.\rdblquote\par
The train pulled out of the station. Harry wanted to watch Ha\-grid until he was out of sight; he rose in his seat and pressed his nose against the window, but he blinked and Hagrid had gone.\par
