\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 6\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Journey from Platform Nine and Three-Quarters\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry\rquote s last month with the Dursleys wasn\rquote t fun. True, Dudley was now so scared of Harry he wouldn\rquote t stay in the same room, while Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon didn\rquote t shut Harry in his cupboard, force him to do anything, or shout at him \emdash  in fact, they didn\rquote t speak to him at all. Half terrified, half furious, they acted as though any chair with Harry in it were empty. Although this was an improvement in many ways, it did be\-come a bit depressing after a while.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Harry kept to his room, with his new owl for company. He had decided to call her Hedwig, a name he had found in \i A History of Magic.\i0  His school books were very interesting. He lay on his bed reading late into the night, Hedwig swooping in and out of the open window as she pleased. It was lucky that Aunt Petunia didn\rquote t come in to vacuum anymore, because Hedwig kept bringing back dead mice. Every night before he went to sleep, Harry ticked off another day on the piece of paper he had pinned to the wall, count\-ing down to September the first.\par
On the last day of August he thought he\rquote d better speak to his aunt and uncle about getting to King\rquote s Cross station the next day, so he went down to the living room where they were watching a quiz show on television. He cleared his throat to let them know he was there, and Dudley screamed and ran from the room.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  Uncle Vernon?\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon grunted to show he was listening.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  I need to be at King\rquote s Cross tomorrow to \emdash  to go to Hogwarts.\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon grunted again.\par
\ldblquote Would it be all right if you gave me a lift?\rdblquote\par
Grunt. Harry supposed that meant yes.\par
\ldblquote Thank you.\rdblquote\par
He was about to go back upstairs when Uncle Vernon actually spoke.\par
\ldblquote Funny way to get to a wizards\rquote  school, the train. Magic carpets all got punctures, have they?\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t say anything.\par
\ldblquote Where is this school, anyway?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Harry, realizing this for the first time. He pulled the ticket Hagrid had given him out of his pocket.\par
\ldblquote I just take the train from platform nine and three-quarters at eleven o\rquote clock,\rdblquote  he read.\par
His aunt and uncle stared.\par
\ldblquote Platform what?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nine and three-quarters.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t talk rubbish,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote There is no platform nine and three-quarters.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s on my ticket.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Barking,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, \ldblquote howling mad, the lot of them. You\rquote ll see. You just wait. All right, we\rquote ll take you to King\rquote s Cross. We\rquote re going up to London tomorrow anyway, or I wouldn\rquote t bother.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why are you going to London?\rdblquote  Harry asked, trying to keep things friendly.\par
\ldblquote Taking Dudley to the hospital,\rdblquote  growled Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote Got to have that ruddy tail removed before he goes to Smeltings.\rdblquote\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry woke at five o\rquote clock the next morning and was too excited and nervous to go back to sleep. He got up and pulled on his jeans because he didn\rquote t want to walk into the station in his wizard\rquote s robes \emdash  he\rquote d change on the train. He checked his Hogwarts list yet again to make sure he had everything he needed, saw that Hedwig was shut safely in her cage, and then paced the room, waiting for the Dursleys to get up. Two hours later, Harry\rquote s huge, heavy trunk had been loaded into the Dursleys\rquote  car, Aunt Petunia had talked Dudley into sitting next to Harry, and they had set off.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj They reached King\rquote s Cross at half past ten. Uncle Vernon dumped Harry\rquote s trunk onto a cart and wheeled it into the station for him. Harry thought this was strangely kind until Uncle Vernon stopped dead, facing the platforms with a nasty grin on his face.\par
\ldblquote Well, there you are, boy. Platform nine \emdash  platform ten. Your platform should be somewhere in the middle, but they don\rquote t seem to have built it yet, do they?\rdblquote\par
He was quite right, of course. There was a big plastic number nine over one platform and a big plastic number ten over the one next to it, and in the middle, nothing at all.\par
\ldblquote Have a good term,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon with an even nastier smile. He left without another word. Harry turned and saw the Dursleys drive away. All three of them were laughing. Harry\rquote s mouth went rather dry. What on earth was he going to do? He was starting to attract a lot of funny looks, because of Hedwig. He\rquote d have to ask someone.\par
He stopped a passing guard, but didn\rquote t dare mention platform nine and three-quarters. The guard had never heard of Hogwarts and when Harry couldn\rquote t even tell him what part of the country it was in, he started to get annoyed, as though Harry was being stu\-pid on purpose. Getting desperate, Harry asked for the train that left at eleven o\rquote clock, but the guard said there wasn\rquote t one. In the end the guard strode away, muttering about time wasters. Harry was now trying hard not to panic. According to the large clock over the arrivals board, he had ten minutes left to get on the train to Hog\-warts and he had no idea how to do it; he was stranded in the mid\-dle of a station with a trunk he could hardly lift, a pocket full of wizard money, and a large owl.\par
Hagrid must have forgotten to tell him something you had to do, like tapping the third brick on the left to get into Diagon Alley. He wondered if he should get out his wand and start tapping the ticket inspector\rquote s stand between platforms nine and ten.\par
At that moment a group of people passed just behind him and he caught a few words of what they were saying.\par
\ldblquote\emdash  packed with Muggles, of course \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry swung round. The speaker was a plump woman who was talking to four boys, all with flaming red hair. Each of them was pushing a trunk like Harry\rquote s in front of him \emdash  and they had an \i owl.\i0\par
Heart hammering, Harry pushed his cart after them. They stopped and so did he, just near enough to hear what they were say\-ing.\par
\ldblquote Now, what\rquote s the platform number?\rdblquote  said the boys\rquote  mother.\par
\ldblquote Nine and three-quarters!\rdblquote  piped a small girl, also red-headed, who was holding her hand, \ldblquote Mom, can\rquote t I go \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re not old enough, Ginny, now be quiet. All right, Percy, you go first.\rdblquote\par
What looked like the oldest boy marched toward platforms nine and ten. Harry watched, careful not to blink in case he missed it \emdash  but just as the boy reached the dividing barrier between the two platforms, a large crowd of tourists came swarming in front of him and by the time the last backpack had cleared away, the boy had vanished.\par
\ldblquote Fred, you next,\rdblquote  the plump woman said.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not Fred, I\rquote m George,\rdblquote  said the boy. \ldblquote Honestly, woman, you call yourself our mother? Can\rquote t you \i tell\i0  I\rquote m George?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sorry, George, dear.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Only joking, I am Fred,\rdblquote  said the boy, and off he went. His twin called after him to hurry up, and he must have done so, be\-cause a second later, he had gone \emdash  but how had he done it?\par
Now the third brother was walking briskly toward the barrier \emdash  he was almost there \emdash  and then, quite suddenly, he wasn\rquote t any\-where.\par
There was nothing else for it.\par
\ldblquote Excuse me,\rdblquote  Harry said to the plump woman.\par
\ldblquote Hello, dear,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote First time at Hogwarts? Ron\rquote s new, too.\rdblquote\par
She pointed at the last and youngest of her sons. He was tall, thin, and gangling, with freckles, big hands and feet, and a long nose.\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote The thing is \emdash  the thing is, I don\rquote t know how to \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How to get onto the platform?\rdblquote  she said kindly, and Harry nodded.\par
\ldblquote Not to worry,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote All you have to do is walk straight at the barrier between platforms nine and ten. Don\rquote t stop and don\rquote t be scared you\rquote ll crash into it, that\rquote s very important. Best do it at a bit of a run if you\rquote re nervous. Go on, go now before Ron.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  okay,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
He pushed his trolley around and stared at the barrier. It looked very solid.\par
He started to walk toward it. People jostled him on their way to platforms nine and ten. Harry walked more quickly. He was going to smash right into that barrier and then he\rquote d be in trouble \emdash  lean\-ing forward on his cart, he broke into a heavy run \emdash  the barrier was coming nearer and nearer \emdash  he wouldn\rquote t be able to stop \emdash  the cart was out of control \emdash  he was a foot away \emdash  he closed his eyes ready for the crash \emdash\par
It didn\rquote t come \'85 he kept on running \'85 he opened his eyes.\par
A scarlet steam engine was waiting next to a platform packed with people. A sign overhead said Hogwarts Express, eleven o\rquote clock. Harry looked behind him and saw a wrought-iron archway where the barrier had been, with the words \i Platform Nine and Three-Quarters\i0  on it. He had done it.\par
Smoke from the engine drifted over the heads of the chattering crowd, while cats of every color wound here and there between their legs. Owls hooted to one another in a disgruntled sort of way over the babble and the scraping of heavy trunks.\par
The first few carriages were already packed with students, some hanging out of the window to talk to their families, some fighting over seats. Harry pushed his cart off down the platform in search of an empty seat. He passed a round-faced boy who was saying, \ldblquote Gran, I\rquote ve lost my toad again.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, \i Neville,\rdblquote\i0  he heard the old woman sigh.\par
A boy with dreadlocks was surrounded by a small crowd.\par
\ldblquote Give us a look, Lee, go on.\rdblquote\par
The boy lifted the lid of a box in his arms, and the people around him shrieked and yelled as something inside poked out a long, hairy leg.\par
Harry pressed on through the crowd until he found an empty compartment near the end of the train. He put Hedwig inside first and then started to shove and heave his trunk toward the train door. He tried to lift it up the steps but could hardly raise one end and twice he dropped it painfully on his foot.\par
\ldblquote Want a hand?\rdblquote  It was one of the red-haired twins he\rquote d followed through the barrier.\par
\ldblquote Yes, please,\rdblquote  Harry panted.\par
\ldblquote Oy, Fred! C\rquote mere and help!\rdblquote\par
With the twins\rquote  help, Harry\rquote s trunk was at last tucked away in a corner of the compartment.\par
\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, pushing his sweaty hair out of his eyes.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote  said one of the twins suddenly, pointing at Harry\rquote s lightning scar.\par
\ldblquote Blimey,\rdblquote  said the other twin. \ldblquote Are you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He \i is,\i0\rdblquote\i  \i0 said the first twin. \ldblquote Aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote  he added to Harry.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\i\ldblquote Harry Potter,\rdblquote\i0  chorused the twins.\par
\ldblquote Oh, him,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I mean, yes, I am.\rdblquote\par
The two boys gawked at him, and Harry felt himself turning red. Then, to his relief, a voice came floating in through the train\rquote s open door.\par
\ldblquote Fred? George? Are you there?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Coming, Mom.\rdblquote\par
With a last look at Harry, the twins hopped off the train.\par
Harry sat down next to the window where, half hidden, he could watch the red-haired family on the platform and hear what they were saying. Their mother had just taken out her handker\-chief.\par
\ldblquote Ron, you\rquote ve got something on your nose.\rdblquote\par
The youngest boy tried to jerk out of the way, but she grabbed him and began rubbing the end of his nose.\par
\i\ldblquote Mom\i0  \emdash  geroff.\rdblquote  He wriggled free.\par
\ldblquote Aaah, has ickle Ronnie got somefink on his nosie?\rdblquote  said one of the twins.\par
\ldblquote Shut up,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote s Percy?\rdblquote  said their mother.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s coming now.\rdblquote\par
The oldest boy came striding into sight. He had already changed into his billowing black Hogwarts robes, and Harry noticed a shiny red and gold badge on his chest with the letter \i P\i0  on it.\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t stay long, Mother,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I\rquote m up front, the prefects have got two compartments to themselves \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, are you a \i prefect,\i0  Percy?\rdblquote  said one of the twins, with an air of great surprise. \ldblquote You should have said something, we had no idea.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hang on, I think I remember him saying something about it,\rdblquote  said the other twin. \ldblquote Once \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Or twice \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A minute \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All summer \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, shut up,\rdblquote  said Percy the Prefect.\par
\ldblquote How come Percy gets new robes, anyway?\rdblquote  said one of the twins.\par
\ldblquote Because he\rquote s a \i prefect,\rdblquote  \i0 said their mother fondly. \ldblquote All right, dear, well, have a good term \emdash  send me an owl when you get there.\rdblquote\par
She kissed Percy on the cheek and he left. Then she turned to the twins.\par
\ldblquote Now, you two \emdash  this year, you behave yourselves. If I get one more owl telling me you\rquote ve \emdash  you\rquote ve blown up a toilet or \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Blown up a toilet? We\rquote ve never blown up a toilet.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Great idea though, thanks, Mom.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s \i not funny. \i0 And look after Ron.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry, ickle Ronniekins is safe with us.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Shut up,\rdblquote  said Ron again. He was almost as tall as the twins al\-ready and his nose was still pink where his mother had rubbed it.\par
\ldblquote Hey, Mom, guess what? Guess who we just met on the train?\rdblquote\par
Harry leaned back quickly so they couldn\rquote t see him looking.\par
\ldblquote You know that black-haired boy who was near us in the station? Know who he is?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Who?\rdblquote\par
\i\ldblquote Harry Potter!\rdblquote\par
\i0 Harry heard the little girl\rquote s voice.\par
\ldblquote Oh, Mom, can I go on the train and see him, Mom, oh please. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve already seen him, Ginny, and the poor boy isn\rquote t some\-thing you goggle at in a zoo. Is he really, Fred? How do you know?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Asked him. Saw his scar. It\rquote s really there \emdash  like lightning.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Poor \i dear\i0  \emdash  no wonder he was alone, I wondered. He was ever so polite when he asked how to get onto the platform.\rdblquote\par
