\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The door swung open at once. A tall, black-haired witch in emerald-green robes stood there. She had a very stern face and Harry\rquote s first thought was that this was not someone to cross.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote The firs\rquote  years, Professor McGonagall,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote Thank you, Hagrid. I will take them from here.\rdblquote\par
She pulled the door wide. The entrance hall was so big you could have fit the whole of the Dursleys\rquote  house in it. The stone walls were lit with flaming torches like the ones at Gringotts, the ceiling was too high to make out, and a magnificent marble stair\-case facing them led to the upper floors.\par
They followed Professor McGonagall across the flagged stone floor. Harry could hear the drone of hundreds of voices from a doorway to the right \emdash  the rest of the school must already be here \emdash  but Professor McGonagall showed the first years into a small, empty chamber off the hall. They crowded in, standing rather closer together than they would usually have done, peering about nervously.\par
\ldblquote Welcome to Hogwarts,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote The start-of-term banquet will begin shortly, but before you take your seats in the Great Hall, you will be sorted into your Houses. The Sorting is a very important ceremony because, while you are here, your House will be something like your family within Hogwarts. You will have classes with the rest of your House, sleep in your House dormitory, and spend free time in your House common room.\par
\ldblquote The four Houses are called Gryffindor, Hufflepuff, Ravenclaw, and Slytherin. Each House has its own noble history and each has produced outstanding witches and wizards. While you are at Hog\-warts, your triumphs will earn your House points, while any rule-breaking will lose House points. At the end of the year, the House with the most points is awarded the House cup, a great honor. I hope each of you will be a credit to whichever House becomes yours.\par
\ldblquote The Sorting Ceremony will take place in a few minutes in front of the rest of the school. I suggest you all smarten yourselves up as much as you can while you are waiting.\rdblquote\par
Her eyes lingered for a moment on Neville\rquote s cloak, which was fastened under his left ear, and on Ron\rquote s smudged nose. Harry ner\-vously tried to flatten his hair.\par
\ldblquote I shall return when we are ready for you,\rdblquote  said Professor Mc\-Gonagall. \ldblquote Please wait quietly.\rdblquote\par
She left the chamber. Harry swallowed.\par
\ldblquote How exactly do they sort us into Houses?\rdblquote  he asked Ron.\par
\ldblquote Some sort of test, I think. Fred said it hurts a lot, but I think he was joking.\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s heart gave a horrible jolt. A test? In front of the whole school? But he didn\rquote t know any magic yet \emdash  what on earth would he have to do? He hadn\rquote t expected something like this the moment they arrived. He looked around anxiously and saw that everyone else looked terrified, too. No one was talking much except Hermione Granger, who was whispering very fast about all the spells she\rquote d learned and wondering which one she\rquote d need. Harry tried hard not to listen to her. He\rquote d never been more nervous, never, not even when he\rquote d had to take a school report home to the Dursleys saying that he\rquote d somehow turned his teachers wig blue. He kept his eyes fixed on the door. Any second now, Professor McGonagall would come back and lead him to his doom.\par
Then something happened that made him jump about a foot in the air \emdash  several people behind him screamed.\par
\ldblquote What the \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
He gasped. So did the people around him. About twenty ghosts had just streamed through the back wall. Pearly-white and slightly transparent, they glided across the room talking to one another and hardly glancing at the first years. They seemed to be arguing. What looked like a fat little monk was saying: \ldblquote Forgive and forget, I say, we ought to give him a second chance \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My dear Friar, haven\rquote t we given Peeves all the chances he de\-serves? He gives us all a bad name and you know, he\rquote s not really even a ghost \emdash  I say, what are you all doing here?\rdblquote\par
A ghost wearing a ruff and tights had suddenly noticed the first years.\par
Nobody answered.\par
\ldblquote New students!\rdblquote  said the Fat Friar, smiling around at them. \ldblquote About to be Sorted, I suppose?\rdblquote\par
A few people nodded mutely.\par
\ldblquote Hope to see you in Hufflepuff!\rdblquote  said the Friar. \ldblquote My old House, you know.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Move along now,\rdblquote  said a sharp voice. \ldblquote The Sorting Ceremony\rquote s about to start.\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall had returned. One by one, the ghosts floated away through the opposite wall.\par
\ldblquote Now, form a line,\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall told the first years, \ldblquote and follow me.\rdblquote\par
Feeling oddly as though his legs had turned to lead, Harry got into line behind a boy with sandy hair, with Ron behind him, and they walked out of the chamber, back across the hall, and through a pair of double doors into the Great Hall.\par
Harry had never even imagined such a strange and splendid place. It was lit by thousands and thousands of candles that were floating in midair over four long tables, where the rest of the stu\-dents were sitting. These tables were laid with glittering golden plates and goblets. At the top of the hall was another long table where the teachers were sitting. Professor McGonagall led the first years up here, so that they came to a halt in a line facing the other students, with the teachers behind them. The hundreds of faces staring at them looked like pale lanterns in the flickering candle\-light. Dotted here and there among the students, the ghosts shone misty silver. Mainly to avoid all the staring eyes, Harry looked up\-ward and saw a velvety black ceiling dotted with stars. He heard Hermione whisper, \ldblquote It\rquote s bewitched to look like the sky outside. I read about it in \i Hogwarts, A History.\rdblquote\i0\par
It was hard to believe there was a ceiling there at all, and that the Great Hall didn\rquote t simply open on to the heavens.\par
Harry quickly looked down again as Professor McGonagall silently placed a four-legged stool in front of the first years. On top of the stool she put a pointed wizard\rquote s hat. This hat was patched and frayed and extremely dirty. Aunt Petunia wouldn\rquote t have let it in the house.\par
\i Maybe they had to try and get a rabbit out of it,\i0  Harry thought wildly, that seemed the sort of thing \emdash  noticing that everyone in the hall was now staring at the hat, he stared at it, too. For a few seconds, there was complete silence. Then the hat twitched. A rip near the brim opened wide like a mouth \emdash  and the hat began to sing:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li851\qj\i\ldblquote Oh, you may not think I\rquote m pretty,\par
But don\rquote t judge on what you see,\par
I\rquote ll eat myself if you can find\par
A smarter hat than me.\par
You can keep your bowlers black,\par
Your top hats sleek and tall,\par
For I\rquote m the Hogwarts Sorting Hat\par
And I can cap them all.\par
There\rquote s nothing hidden in your head\par
The Sorting Hat can\rquote t see,\par
So try me on and I will tell you\par
Where you ought to be.\par
You might belong in Gryffindor,\par
Where dwell the brave at heart,\par
Their daring, nerve, and chivalry\par
Set Gryffindors apart;\par
You might belong in Hufflepuff,\par
Where they are just and loyal,\par
Those patient Hufflepuffs are true\par
And unafraid of toil;\par
Or yet in wise old Ravenclaw,\par
If you\rquote ve a ready mind,\par
Where those of wit and learning,\par
Will always find their kind;\par
Or perhaps in Slytherin\par
You\rquote ll make your real friends,\par
Those cunning folk use any means\par
To achieve their ends.\par
So put me on! Don\rquote t be afraid!\par
And don\rquote t get in a flap!\par
You\rquote re in safe hands (though I have none)\par
For I\rquote m a Thinking Cap!\rdblquote\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The whole hall burst into applause as the hat finished its song. It bowed to each of the four tables and then became quite still again.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote So we\rquote ve just got to try on the hat!\rdblquote  Ron whispered to Harry. \ldblquote I\rquote ll kill Fred, he was going on about wrestling a troll.\rdblquote\par
Harry smiled weakly. Yes, trying on the hat was a lot better than having to do a spell, but he did wish they could have tried it on without everyone watching. The hat seemed to be asking rather a lot; Harry didn\rquote t feel brave or quick-witted or any of it at the mo\-ment. If only the hat had mentioned a House for people who felt a bit queasy, that would have been the one for him.\par
Professor McGonagall now stepped forward holding a long roll of parchment.\par
\ldblquote When I call your name, you will put on the hat and sit on the stool to be sorted,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Abbott, Hannah!\rdblquote\par
A pink-faced girl with blonde pigtails stumbled out of line, put on the hat, which fell right down over her eyes, and sat down. A moment\rquote s pause \emdash\par
\ldblquote HUFFLEPUFF!\rdblquote  shouted the hat.\par
The table on the right cheered and clapped as Hannah went to sit down at the Hufflepuff table. Harry saw the ghost of the Fat Friar waving merrily at her.\par
\ldblquote Bones, Susan!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote HUFFLEPUFF!\rdblquote  shouted the hat again, and Susan scuttled off to sit next to Hannah.\par
\ldblquote Boot, Terry!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote RAVENCLAW!\rdblquote\par
The table second from the left clapped this time; several Raven\-claws stood up to shake hands with Terry as he joined them.\par
\ldblquote Brocklehurst, Mandy\rdblquote  went to Ravenclaw too, but \ldblquote Brown, Lavender\rdblquote  became the first new Gryffindor, and the table on the far left exploded with cheers; Harry could see Ron\rquote s twin brothers cat\-calling.\par
\ldblquote Bulstrode, Millicent\rdblquote  then became a Slytherin. Perhaps it was Harry\rquote s imagination, after all he\rquote d heard about Slytherin, but he thought they looked like an unpleasant lot.\par
He was starting to feel definitely sick now. He remembered be\-ing picked for teams during gym at his old school. He had always been last to be chosen, not because he was no good, but because no one wanted Dudley to think they liked him.\par
\ldblquote Finch-Fletchley, Justin!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote HUFFLEPUFF!\rdblquote\par
Sometimes, Harry noticed, the hat shouted out the House at once, but at others it took a little while to decide. \ldblquote Finnigan, Sea\-mus,\rdblquote  the sandy-haired boy next to Harry in the line, sat on the stool for almost a whole minute before the hat declared him a Gryffindor.\par
\ldblquote Granger, Hermione!\rdblquote\par
Hermione almost ran to the stool and jammed the hat eagerly on her head.\par
\ldblquote GRYFFINDOR!\rdblquote  shouted the hat. Ron groaned.\par
A horrible thought struck Harry, as horrible thoughts always do when you\rquote re very nervous. What if he wasn\rquote t chosen at all? What if he just sat there with the hat over his eyes for ages, until Professor McGonagall jerked it off his head and said there had obviously been a mistake and he\rquote d better get back on the train?\par
When Neville Longbottom, the boy who kept losing his toad, was called, he fell over on his way to the stool. The hat took a long time to decide with Neville. When it finally shouted, \ldblquote GRYFFINDOR,\rdblquote  Neville ran off still wearing it, and had to jog back amid gales of laughter to give it to \ldblquote MacDougal, Morag.\rdblquote\par
Malfoy swaggered forward when his name was called and got his wish at once: the hat had barely touched his head when it screamed, \ldblquote SLYTHERIN!\rdblquote\par
Malfoy went to join his friends Crabbe and Goyle, looking pleased with himself.\par
There weren\rquote t many people left now.\par
\ldblquote Moon\rdblquote  \'85 , \ldblquote Nott\rdblquote  \'85 , \ldblquote Parkinson\rdblquote  \'85 , then a pair of twin girls, \ldblquote Patil\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Patil\rdblquote  \'85 , then \ldblquote Perks, Sally-Anne\rdblquote  \'85 , and then, at last \emdash\par
\ldblquote Potter, Harry!\rdblquote\par
As Harry stepped forward, whispers suddenly broke out like lit\-tle hissing fires all over the hall.\par
\i\ldblquote Potter,\i0  did she say?\rdblquote\par
\i\ldblquote The\i0  Harry Potter?\rdblquote\par
The last thing Harry saw before the hat dropped over his eyes was the hall full of people craning to get a good look at him. Next second he was looking at the black inside of the hat. He waited.\par
\ldblquote Hmm,\rdblquote  said a small voice in his ear. \ldblquote Difficult. Very difficult. Plenty of courage, I see. Not a bad mind either. There\rquote s talent, oh my goodness, yes \emdash  and a nice thirst to prove yourself, now that\rquote s interesting. \'85 So where shall I put you?\rdblquote\par
Harry gripped the edges of the stool and thought, \i Not Slytherin, not Slytherin.\i0\par
\ldblquote Not Slytherin, eh?\rdblquote  said the small voice. \ldblquote Are you sure? You could be great, you know, it\rquote s all here in your head, and Slytherin will help you on the way to greatness, no doubt about that \emdash  no? Well, if you\rquote re sure \emdash  better be GRYFFINDOR!\rdblquote\par
Harry heard the hat shout the last word to the whole hall. He took off the hat and walked shakily toward the Gryffindor table. He was so relieved to have been chosen and not put in Slytherin, he hardly noticed that he was getting the loudest cheer yet. Percy the Prefect got up and shook his hand vigorously, while the Weasley twins yelled, \ldblquote We got Potter! We got Potter!\rdblquote  Harry sat down op\-posite the ghost in the ruff he\rquote d seen earlier. The ghost patted his arm, giving Harry the sudden, horrible feeling he\rquote d just plunged it into a bucket of ice-cold water.\par
He could see the High Table properly now. At the end nearest him sat Hagrid, who caught his eye and gave him the thumbs up. Harry grinned back. And there, in the center of the High Table, in a large gold chair, sat Albus Dumbledore. Harry recognized him at once from the card he\rquote d gotten out of the Chocolate Frog on the train. Dumbledore\rquote s silver hair was the only thing in the whole hall that shone as brightly as the ghosts. Harry spotted Professor Quir\-rell, too, the nervous young man from the Leaky Cauldron. He was looking very peculiar in a large purple turban.\par
And now there were only four people left to be sorted. \ldblquote Thomas, Dean,\rdblquote  a Black boy even taller than Ron, joined Harry at the Gryffindor table. \ldblquote Turpin, Lisa,\rdblquote  became a Ravenclaw and then it was Ron\rquote s turn. He was pale green by now. Harry crossed his fin\-gers under the table and a second later the hat had shouted, \ldblquote GRYFFINDOR!\rdblquote\par
Harry clapped loudly with the rest as Ron collapsed into the chair next to him.\par
\ldblquote Well done, Ron, excellent,\rdblquote  said Percy Weasley pompously across Harry as \ldblquote Zabini, Blaise,\rdblquote  was made a Slytherin. Professor McGonagall rolled up her scroll and took the Sorting Hat away.\par
Harry looked down at his empty gold plate. He had only just realized how hungry he was. The pumpkin pasties seemed ages ago.\par
Albus Dumbledore had gotten to his feet. He was beaming at the students, his arms opened wide, as if nothing could have pleased him more than to see them all there.\par
\ldblquote Welcome!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Welcome to a new year at Hogwarts! Be\-fore we begin our banquet, I would like to say a few words. And here they are: Nitwit! Blubber! Oddment! Tweak!\par
\ldblquote Thank you!\rdblquote\par
He sat back down. Everybody clapped and cheered. Harry didn\rquote t know whether to laugh or not.\par
\ldblquote Is he \emdash  a bit mad?\rdblquote  he asked Percy uncertainly.\par
\ldblquote Mad?\rdblquote  said Percy airily. \ldblquote He\rquote s a genius! Best wizard in the world! But he is a bit mad, yes. Potatoes, Harry?\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s mouth fell open. The dishes in front of him were now piled with food. He had never seen so many things he liked to eat on one table: roast beef, roast chicken, pork chops and lamb chops, sausages, bacon and steak, boiled potatoes, roast potatoes, fries, Yorkshire pudding, peas, carrots, gravy, ketchup, and, for some strange reason, peppermint humbugs.\par
The Dursleys had never exactly starved Harry, but he\rquote d never been allowed to eat as much as he liked. Dudley had always taken anything that Harry really wanted, even if it made him sick. Harry piled his plate with a bit of everything except the peppermints and began to eat. It was all delicious.\par
\ldblquote That does look good,\rdblquote  said the ghost in the ruff sadly, watching Harry cut up his steak.\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I haven\rquote t eaten for nearly five hundred years,\rdblquote  said the ghost. \ldblquote I don\rquote t need to, of course, but one does miss it. I don\rquote t think I\rquote ve introduced myself? Sir Nicholas de Mimsy-Porpington at your ser\-vice. Resident ghost of Gryffindor Tower.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know who you are!\rdblquote  said Ron suddenly. \ldblquote My brothers told me about you \emdash  you\rquote re Nearly Headless Nick!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I would \i prefer\i0  you to call me Sir Nicholas de Mimsy \emdash\rdblquote  the ghost began stiffly, but sandy-haired Seamus Finnigan interrupted.\par
\i\ldblquote Nearly\i0  Headless? How can you be \i nearly\i0  headless?\rdblquote\par
Sir Nicholas looked extremely miffed, as if their little chat wasn\rquote t going at all the way he wanted.\par
\ldblquote Like \i this,\rdblquote\i0  he said irritably. He seized his left ear and pulled. His whole head swung off his neck and fell onto his shoulder as if it was on a hinge. Someone had obviously tried to behead him, but not done it properly. Looking pleased at the stunned looks on their faces, Nearly Headless Nick flipped his head back onto his neck, coughed, and said, \ldblquote So \emdash  new Gryffindors! I hope you\rquote re going to help us win the House Championship this year? Gryffindors have never gone so long without winning. Slytherins have got the cup six years in a row! The Bloody Baron\rquote s becoming almost unbear\-able \emdash  he\rquote s the Slytherin ghost.\rdblquote\par
Harry looked over at the Slytherin table and saw a horrible ghost sitting there, with blank staring eyes, a gaunt face, and robes stained with silver blood. He was right next to Malfoy who, Harry was pleased to see, didn\rquote t look too pleased with the seating arrangements.\par
\ldblquote How did he get covered in blood?\rdblquote  asked Seamus with great in\-terest.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve never asked,\rdblquote  said Nearly Headless Nick delicately.\par
When everyone had eaten as much as they could, the remains of the food faded from the plates, leaving them sparkling clean as before. A moment later the desserts appeared. Blocks of ice cream in every flavor you could think of, apple pies, treacle tarts, chocolate \'e9clairs and jam doughnuts, trifle, strawberries, Jell-O, rice pud\-ding \'85\par
As Harry helped himself to a treacle tart, the talk turned to their families.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m half-and-half,\rdblquote  said Seamus. \ldblquote Me dad\rquote s a Muggle. Mom didn\rquote t tell him she was a witch \rquote til after they were married. Bit of a nasty shock for him.\rdblquote\par
The others laughed.\par
\ldblquote What about you, Neville?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Well, my gran brought me up and she\rquote s a witch,\rdblquote  said Neville, \ldblquote but the family thought I was all-Muggle for ages. My Great Uncle Algie kept trying to catch me off my guard and force some magic out of me \emdash  he pushed me off the end of Blackpool pier once, I nearly drowned \emdash  but nothing happened until I was eight. Great Uncle Algie came round for dinner, and he was hanging me out of an upstairs window by the ankles when my Great Auntie Enid of\-fered him a meringue and he accidentally let go. But I bounced \emdash  all the way down the garden and into the road. They were all really pleased, Gran was crying, she was so happy. And you should have seen their faces when I got in here \emdash  they thought I might not be magic enough to come, you see. Great Uncle Algie was so pleased he bought me my toad.\rdblquote\par
On Harry\rquote s other side, Percy Weasley and Hermione were talk\-ing about lessons (\ldblquote I \i do\i0  hope they start right away, there\rquote s so much to learn, I\rquote m particularly interested in Transfiguration, you know, turning something into something else, of course, it\rquote s supposed to be very difficult \emdash\rdblquote ; \ldblquote You\rquote ll be starting small, just matches into needles and that sort of thing \emdash\rdblquote ).\par
Harry, who was starting to feel warm and sleepy, looked up at the High Table again. Hagrid was drinking deeply from his goblet. Professor McGonagall was talking to Professor Dumbledore. Pro\-fessor Quirrell, in his absurd turban, was talking to a teacher with greasy black hair, a hooked nose, and sallow skin.\par
It happened very suddenly. The hook-nosed teacher looked past Quirrell\rquote s turban straight into Harry\rquote s eyes \emdash  and a sharp, hot pain shot across the scar on Harry\rquote s forehead.\par
\ldblquote Ouch!\rdblquote  Harry clapped a hand to his head.\par
\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  asked Percy.\par
\ldblquote N-nothing.\rdblquote\par
The pain had gone as quickly as it had come. Harder to shake off was the feeling Harry had gotten from the teachers look \emdash  a feel\-ing that he didn\rquote t like Harry at all.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s that teacher talking to Professor Quirrell?\rdblquote  he asked Percy.\par
\ldblquote Oh, you know Quirrell already, do you? No wonder he\rquote s look\-ing so nervous, that\rquote s Professor Snape. He teaches Potions, but he doesn\rquote t want to \emdash  everyone knows he\rquote s after Quirrell\rquote s job. Knows an awful lot about the Dark Arts, Snape.\rdblquote\par
Harry watched Snape for a while, but Snape didn\rquote t look at him again.\par
At last, the desserts too disappeared, and Professor Dumbledore got to his feet again. The hall fell silent.\par
\ldblquote Ahem \emdash  just a few more words now that we are all fed and wa\-tered. I have a few start-of-term notices to give you.\par
\ldblquote First years should note that the forest on the grounds is forbid\-den to all pupils. And a few of our older students would do well to remember that as well.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore\rquote s twinkling eyes flashed in the direction of the Weasley twins.\par
\ldblquote I have also been asked by Mr. Filch, the caretaker, to remind you all that no magic should be used between classes in the corri\-dors.\par
\ldblquote Quidditch trials will be held in the second week of the term. Anyone interested in playing for their House teams should contact Madam Hooch.\par
\ldblquote And finally, I must tell you that this year, the third-floor corri\-dor on the right-hand side is out of bounds to everyone who does not wish to die a very painful death.\rdblquote\par
Harry laughed, but he was one of the few who did.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s not serious?\rdblquote  he muttered to Percy.\par
\ldblquote Must be,\rdblquote  said Percy, frowning at Dumbledore. \ldblquote It\rquote s odd, because he usually gives us a reason why we\rquote re not allowed to go somewhere \emdash  the forest\rquote s full of dangerous beasts, everyone knows that. I do think he might have told us prefects, at least.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And now, before we go to bed, let us sing the school song!\rdblquote  cried Dumbledore. Harry noticed that the other teachers\rquote  smiles had become rather fixed.\par
Dumbledore gave his wand a little flick, as if he was trying to get a fly off the end, and a long golden ribbon flew out of it, which rose high above the tables and twisted itself, snakelike, into words.\par
\ldblquote Everyone pick their favorite tune,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote and off we go!\rdblquote\par
And the school bellowed:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li851\qj\i\ldblquote Hogwarts, Hogwarts, Hoggy Warty Hogwarts,\par
Teach us something please,\par
Whether we be old and bald\par
Or young with scabby knees,\par
Our heads could do with filling\par
With some interesting stuff,\par
For now they\rquote re bare and full of air,\par
Dead flies and bits of fluff,\par
So teach us things worth knowing,\par
Bring back what we\rquote ve forgot,\par
Just do your best, we\rquote ll do the rest,\par
And learn until our brains all rot.\rdblquote\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Everybody finished the song at different times. At last, only the Weasley twins were left singing along to a very slow funeral march. Dumbledore conducted their last few lines with his wand and when they had finished, he was one of those who clapped loudest.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Ah, music,\rdblquote  he said, wiping his eyes. \ldblquote A magic beyond all we do here! And now, bedtime. Off you trot!\rdblquote\par
The Gryffindor first years followed Percy through the chattering crowds, out of the Great Hall, and up the marble staircase. Harry\rquote s legs were like lead again, but only because he was so tired and full of food. He was too sleepy even to be surprised that the people in the portraits along the corridors whispered and pointed as they passed, or that twice Percy led them through doorways hidden be\-hind sliding panels and hanging tapestries. They climbed more staircases, yawning and dragging their feet, and Harry was just wondering how much farther they had to go when they came to a sudden halt.\par
A bundle of walking sticks was floating in midair ahead of them, and as Percy took a step toward them they started throwing them\-selves at him.\par
\ldblquote Peeves,\rdblquote  Percy whispered to the first years. \ldblquote A poltergeist.\rdblquote  He raised his voice, \ldblquote Peeves \emdash  show yourself.\rdblquote\par
A loud, rude sound, like the air being let out of a balloon, an\-swered.\par
\ldblquote Do you want me to go to the Bloody Baron?\rdblquote\par
There was a pop, and a little man with wicked, dark eyes and a wide mouth appeared, floating cross-legged in the air, clutching the walking sticks.\par
\ldblquote Oooooooh!\rdblquote  he said, with an evil cackle. \ldblquote Ickle Firsties! What fun!\rdblquote\par
He swooped suddenly at them. They all ducked.\par
\ldblquote Go away, Peeves, or the Baron\rquote ll hear about this, I mean it!\rdblquote  barked Percy.\par
Peeves stuck out his tongue and vanished, dropping the walking sticks on Neville\rquote s head. They heard him zooming away, rattling coats of armor as he passed.\par
\ldblquote You want to watch out for Peeves,\rdblquote  said Percy, as they set off again. \ldblquote The Bloody Baron\rquote s the only one who can control him, he won\rquote t even listen to us prefects. Here we are.\rdblquote\par
At the very end of the corridor hung a portrait of a very fat woman in a pink silk dress.\par
\ldblquote Password?\rdblquote  she said.\par
\ldblquote Caput Draconis,\rdblquote  said Percy, and the portrait swung forward to reveal a round hole in the wall. They all scrambled through it \emdash  Neville needed a leg up \emdash  and found themselves in the Gryffindor common room, a cozy, round room full of squashy armchairs.\par
Percy directed the girls through one door to their dormitory and the boys through another. At the top of a spiral staircase \emdash  they were obviously in one of the towers \emdash  they found their beds at last: five four-posters hung with deep red, velvet curtains. Their trunks had already been brought up. Too tired to talk much, they pulled on their pajamas and fell into bed.\par
\ldblquote Great food, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  Ron muttered to Harry through the hang\-ings. \ldblquote Get \i off,\i0  Scabbers! He\rquote s chewing my sheets.\rdblquote\par
Harry was going to ask Ron if he\rquote d had any of the treacle tart, but he fell asleep almost at once.\par
Perhaps Harry had eaten a bit too much, because he had a very strange dream. He was wearing Professor Quirrell\rquote s turban, which kept talking to him, telling him he must transfer to Slytherin at once, because it was his destiny. Harry told the turban he didn\rquote t want to be in Slytherin; it got heavier and heavier; he tried to pull it off but it tightened painfully \emdash  and there was Malfoy, laughing at him as he struggled with it \emdash  then Malfoy turned into the hook-nosed teacher, Snape, whose laugh became high and cold \emdash  there was a burst of green light and Harry woke, sweating and shaking.\par
He rolled over and fell asleep again, and when he woke next day, he didn\rquote t remember the dream at all.\par
