\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 8\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Potions Master\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj  \ldblquote There, look.\rdblquote\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Where?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Next to the tall kid with the red hair.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wearing the glasses?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Did you see his face?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Did you see his scar?\rdblquote\par
Whispers followed Harry from the moment he left his dormi\-tory the next day. People lining up outside classrooms stood on tip\-toe to get a look at him, or doubled back to pass him in the corridors again, staring. Harry wished they wouldn\rquote t, because he was trying to concentrate on finding his way to classes.\par
There were a hundred and forty-two staircases at Hogwarts: wide, sweeping ones; narrow, rickety ones; some that led some\-where different on a Friday; some with a vanishing step halfway up that you had to remember to jump. Then there were doors that wouldn\rquote t open unless you asked politely, or tickled them in exactly the right place, and doors that weren\rquote t really doors at all, but solid walls just pretending. It was also very hard to remember where any\-thing was, because it all seemed to move around a lot. The people in the portraits kept going to visit each other, and Harry was sure the coats of armor could walk.\par
The ghosts didn\rquote t help, either. It was always a nasty shock when one of them glided suddenly through a door you were trying to open. Nearly Headless Nick was always happy to point new Gryffindors in the right direction, but Peeves the Poltergeist was worth two locked doors and a trick staircase if you met him when you were late for class. He would drop wastepaper baskets on your head, pull rugs from under your feet, pelt you with bits of chalk, or sneak up behind you, invisible, grab your nose, and screech, \ldblquote GOT YOUR CONK!\rdblquote\par
Even worse than Peeves, if that was possible, was the caretaker, Argus Filch. Harry and Ron managed to get on the wrong side of him on their very first morning. Filch found them trying to force their way through a door that unluckily turned out to be the en\-trance to the out-of-bounds corridor on the third floor. He wouldn\rquote t believe they were lost, was sure they were trying to break into it on purpose, and was threatening to lock them in the dungeons when they were rescued by Professor Quirrell, who was passing.\par
Filch owned a cat called Mrs. Norris, a scrawny, dust-colored creature with bulging, lamplike eyes just like Filch\rquote s. She patrolled the corridors alone. Break a rule in front of her, put just one toe out of line, and she\rquote d whisk off for Filch, who\rquote d appear, wheezing, two seconds later. Filch knew the secret passageways of the school bet\-ter than anyone (except perhaps the Weasley twins) and could pop up as suddenly as any of the ghosts. The students all hated him, and it was the dearest ambition of many to give Mrs. Norris a good kick.\par
And then, once you had managed to find them, there were the classes themselves. There was a lot more to magic, as Harry quickly found out, than waving your wand and saying a few funny words.\par
They had to study the night skies through their telescopes every Wednesday at midnight and learn the names of different stars and the movements of the planets. Three times a week they went out to the greenhouses behind the castle to study Herbology, with a dumpy little witch called Professor Sprout, where they learned how to take care of all the strange plants and fungi, and found out what they were used for.\par
Easily the most boring class was History of Magic, which was the only one taught by a ghost. Professor Binns had been very old indeed when he had fallen asleep in front of the staff room fire and got up next morning to teach, leaving his body behind him. Binns droned on and on while they scribbled down names and dates, and got Emeric the Evil and Uric the Oddball mixed up.\par
Professor Flitwick, the Charms teacher, was a tiny little wizard who had to stand on a pile of books to see over his desk. At the start of their first class he took the roll call, and when he reached Harry\rquote s name he gave an excited squeak and toppled out of sight.\par
Professor McGonagall was again different. Harry had been quite right to think she wasn\rquote t a teacher to cross. Strict and clever, she gave them a talking-to the moment they sat down in her first class.\par
\ldblquote Transfiguration is some of the most complex and dangerous magic you will learn at Hogwarts,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Anyone messing around in my class will leave and not come back. You have been warned.\rdblquote\par
Then she changed her desk into a pig and back again. They were all very impressed and couldn\rquote t wait to get started, but soon realized they weren\rquote t going to be changing the furniture into animals for a long time. After taking a lot of complicated notes, they were each given a match and started trying to turn it into a needle. By the end of the lesson, only Hermione Granger had made any difference to her match; Professor McGonagall showed the class how it had gone all silver and pointy and gave Hermione a rare smile.\par
The class everyone had really been looking forward to was De\-fense Against the Dark Arts, but Quirrell\rquote s lessons turned out to be a bit of a joke. His classroom smelled strongly of garlic, which everyone said was to ward off a vampire he\rquote d met in Romania and was afraid would be coming back to get him one of these days. His turban, he told them, had been given to him by an African prince as a thank-you for getting rid of a troublesome zombie, but they weren\rquote t sure they believed this story. For one thing, when Seamus Finnigan asked eagerly to hear how Quirrell had fought off the zombie, Quirrell went pink and started talking about the weather; for another, they had noticed that a funny smell hung around the turban, and the Weasley twins insisted that it was stuffed full of garlic as well, so that Quirrell was protected wherever he went.\par
Harry was very relieved to find out that he wasn\rquote t miles behind everyone else. Lots of people had come from Muggle families and, like him, hadn\rquote t had any idea that they were witches and wizards. There was so much to learn that even people like Ron didn\rquote t have much of a head start.\par
Friday was an important day for Harry and Ron. They finally managed to find their way down to the Great Hall for breakfast without getting lost once.\par
\ldblquote What have we got today?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron as he poured sugar on his porridge.\par
\ldblquote Double Potions with the Slytherins,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Snape\rquote s Head of Slytherin House. They say he always favors them \emdash  we\rquote ll be able to see if it\rquote s true.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wish McGonagall favored us,\rdblquote  said Harry. Professor McGona\-gall was head of Gryffindor House, but it hadn\rquote t stopped her from giving them a huge pile of homework the day before.\par
Just then, the mail arrived. Harry had gotten used to this by now, but it had given him a bit of a shock on the first morning, when about a hundred owls had suddenly streamed into the Great Hall during breakfast, circling the tables until they saw their own\-ers, and dropping letters and packages onto their laps.\par
Hedwig hadn\rquote t brought Harry anything so far. She sometimes flew in to nibble his ear and have a bit of toast before going off to sleep in the owlery with the other school owls. This morning, how\-ever, she fluttered down between the marmalade and the sugar bowl and dropped a note onto Harry\rquote s plate. Harry tore it open at once. It said, in a very untidy scrawl:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li284\ri284\qj\i Dear Harry,\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\li284\ri284\qj I know you get Friday afternoons off so would you like to come and have a  cup of tea with me  around three?\par
I want to hear all about your first week. Send us an answer back with Hedwig.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li284\ri284\qj Hagrid\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry borrowed Ron\rquote s quill, scribbled \i Yes, please, see you later\i0  on the back of the note, and sent Hedwig off again.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj It was lucky that Harry had tea with Hagrid to look forward to, because the Potions lesson turned out to be the worst thing that had happened to him so far.\par
At the start-of-term banquet, Harry had gotten the idea that Professor Snape disliked him. By the end of the first Potions lesson, he knew he\rquote d been wrong. Snape didn\rquote t dislike Harry \emdash  he \i hated \i0 him.\par
Potions lessons took place down in one of the dungeons. It was colder here than up in the main castle, and would have been quite creepy enough without the pickled animals floating in glass jars all around the walls.\par
Snape, like Flitwick, started the class by taking the roll call, and like Flitwick, he paused at Harry\rquote s name.\par
\ldblquote Ah, \i yes,\i0\rdblquote  he said softly, \ldblquote Harry Potter. Our new \emdash  \i celebrity.\rdblquote\i0\par
Draco Malfoy and his friends Crabbe and Goyle sniggered be\-hind their hands. Snape finished calling the names and looked up at the class. His eyes were black like Hagrid\rquote s, but they had none of Hagrid\rquote s warmth. They were cold and empty and made you think of dark tunnels.\par
\ldblquote You are here to learn the subtle science and exact art of potion-making,\rdblquote  he began. He spoke in barely more than a whisper, but they caught every word \emdash  like Professor McGonagall, Snape had the gift of keeping a class silent without effort. \ldblquote As there is little foolish wand-waving here, many of you will hardly believe this is magic. I don\rquote t expect you will really understand the beauty of the softly simmering cauldron with its shimmering fumes, the delicate power of liquids that creep through human veins, bewitching the mind, ensnaring the senses. \'85 I can teach you how to bottle fame, brew glory, even stopper death \emdash  if you aren\rquote t as big a bunch of dunderheads as I usually have to teach.\rdblquote\par
More silence followed this little speech. Harry and Ron ex\-changed looks with raised eyebrows. Hermione Granger was on the edge of her seat and looked desperate to start proving that she wasn\rquote t a dunderhead.\par
\ldblquote Potter!\rdblquote  said Snape suddenly. \ldblquote What would I get if I added powdered root of asphodel to an infusion of wormwood?\rdblquote\par
\i Powdered root of what to an infusion of what?\i0  Harry glanced at Ron, who looked as stumped as he was; Hermione\rquote s hand had shot into the air.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Snape\rquote s lips curled into a sneer.\par
\ldblquote Tut, tut \emdash  fame clearly isn\rquote t everything.\rdblquote\par
He ignored Hermione\rquote s hand.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s try again. Potter, where would you look if I told you to find me a bezoar?\rdblquote\par
Hermione stretched her hand as high into the air as it would go without her leaving her seat, but Harry didn\rquote t have the faintest idea what a bezoar was. He tried not to look at Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle, who were shaking with laughter.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know, sir.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thought you wouldn\rquote t open a book before coming, eh, Potter?\rdblquote\par
Harry forced himself to keep looking straight into those cold eyes. He \i had\i0  looked through his books at the Dursleys\rquote , but did Snape expect him to remember everything in \i One Thousand Mag\-ical Herbs and Fungi?\i0\par
Snape was still ignoring Hermione\rquote s quivering hand.\par
\ldblquote What is the difference, Potter, between monkshood and wolfs\-bane?\rdblquote\par
At this, Hermione stood up, her hand stretching toward the dungeon ceiling.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Harry quietly. \ldblquote I think Hermione does, though, why don\rquote t you try her?\rdblquote\par
A few people laughed; Harry caught Seamus\rquote s eye, and Seamus winked. Snape, however, was not pleased.\par
\ldblquote Sit down,\rdblquote  he snapped at Hermione. \ldblquote For your information, Potter, asphodel and wormwood make a sleeping potion so power\-ful it is known as the Draught of Living Death. A bezoar is a stone taken from the stomach of a goat and it will save you from most poisons. As for monkshood and wolfsbane, they are the same plant, which also goes by the name of aconite. Well? Why aren\rquote t you all copying that down?\rdblquote\par
There was a sudden rummaging for quills and parchment. Over the noise, Snape said, \ldblquote And a point will be taken from Gryffindor House for your cheek, Potter.\rdblquote\par
Things didn\rquote t improve for the Gryffindors as the Potions lesson continued. Snape put them all into pairs and set them to mixing up a simple potion to cure boils. He swept around in his long black cloak, watching them weigh dried nettles and crush snake fangs, criticizing almost everyone except Malfoy, whom he seemed to like. He was just telling everyone to look at the perfect way Malfoy had stewed his horned slugs when clouds of acid green smoke and a loud hissing filled the dungeon. Neville had somehow managed to melt Seamus\rquote s cauldron into a twisted blob, and their potion was seeping across the stone floor, burning holes in people\rquote s shoes. Within seconds, the whole class was standing on their stools while Neville, who had been drenched in the potion when the cauldron collapsed, moaned in pain as angry red boils sprang up all over his arms and legs.\par
\ldblquote Idiot boy!\rdblquote  snarled Snape, clearing the spilled potion away with one wave of his wand. \ldblquote I suppose you added the porcupine quills before taking the cauldron off the fire?\rdblquote\par
Neville whimpered as boils started to pop up all over his nose.\par
\ldblquote Take him up to the hospital wing,\rdblquote  Snape spat at Seamus. Then he rounded on Harry and Ron, who had been working next to Neville.\par
\ldblquote You \emdash  Potter \emdash  why didn\rquote t you tell him not to add the quills? Thought he\rquote d make you look good if he got it wrong, did you? That\rquote s another point you\rquote ve lost for Gryffindor.\rdblquote\par
This was so unfair that Harry opened his mouth to argue, but Ron kicked him behind their cauldron.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t push it,\rdblquote  he muttered, \ldblquote I\rquote ve heard Snape can turn very nasty.\rdblquote\par
As they climbed the steps out of the dungeon an hour later, Harry\rquote s mind was racing and his spirits were low. He\rquote d lost two points for Gryffindor in his very first week \emdash  \i why\i0  did Snape hate him so much?\par
\ldblquote Cheer up,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote Snape\rquote s always taking points off Fred and George. Can I come and meet Hagrid with you?\rdblquote\par
At five to three they left the castle and made their way across the grounds. Hagrid lived in a small wooden house on the edge of the forbidden forest. A crossbow and a pair of galoshes were outside the front door.\par
When Harry knocked they heard a frantic scrabbling from in\-side and several booming barks. Then Hagrid\rquote s voice rang out, say\-ing, \i\ldblquote Back\i0 , Fang \emdash  \i back.\rdblquote\i0\par
Hagrid\rquote s big, hairy face appeared in the crack as he pulled the door open.\par
\ldblquote Hang on,\rdblquote  he said. \i\ldblquote Back,\i0  Fang.\rdblquote\par
He let them in, struggling to keep a hold on the collar of an enormous black boarhound.\par
There was only one room inside. Hams and pheasants were hanging from the ceiling, a copper kettle was boiling on the open fire, and in the corner stood a massive bed with a patchwork quilt over it.\par
\ldblquote Make yerselves at home,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, letting go of Fang, who bounded straight at Ron and started licking his ears. Like Hagrid, Fang was clearly not as fierce as he looked.\par
\ldblquote This is Ron,\rdblquote  Harry told Hagrid, who was pouring boiling wa\-ter into a large teapot and putting rock cakes onto a plate.\par
\ldblquote Another Weasley, eh?\rdblquote  said Hagrid, glancing at Ron\rquote s freckles. \ldblquote I spent half me life chasin\rquote  yer twin brothers away from the forest.\rdblquote\par
The rock cakes were shapeless lumps with raisins that almost broke their teeth, but Harry and Ron pretended to be enjoying them as they told Hagrid all about their first lessons. Fang rested his head on Harry\rquote s knee and drooled all over his robes.\par
Harry and Ron were delighted to hear Hagrid call Filch \ldblquote that old git\rquote\rquote\par
\ldblquote An\rquote  as fer that cat, Mrs. Norris, I\rquote d like ter introduce her to Fang sometime. D\rquote yeh know, every time I go up ter the school, she follows me everywhere? Can\rquote t get rid of her \emdash  Filch puts her up to it.\rdblquote\par
Harry told Hagrid about Snape\rquote s lesson. Hagrid, like Ron, told Harry not to worry about it, that Snape liked hardly any of the stu\-dents.\par
\ldblquote But he seemed to really \i hate\i0  me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Rubbish!\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Why should he?\rdblquote\par
Yet Harry couldn\rquote t help thinking that Hagrid didn\rquote t quite meet his eyes when he said that.\par
\ldblquote How\rquote s yer brother Charlie?\rdblquote  Hagrid asked Ron. \ldblquote I liked him a lot \emdash  great with animals.\rdblquote\par
Harry wondered if Hagrid had changed the subject on purpose. While Ron told Hagrid all about Charlie\rquote s work with dragons, Harry picked up a piece of paper that was lying on the table under the tea cozy. It was a cutting from the \i Daily Prophet\i0 :\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\b GRINGOTTS BREAK-IN LATEST\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li284\ri284\qj\b0 Investigations continue into the break-in at Gringotts on 31 July, widely believed to be the work of Dark wizards or witches unknown.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\li284\ri284\qj Gringotts goblins today insisted that nothing had been taken. The vault that was searched had in fact been emptied the same day.\par
\ldblquote But we\rquote re not telling you what was in there, so keep your noses out if you know what\rquote s good for you,\rdblquote  said a Gringotts spokesgoblin this after\-noon.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry remembered Ron telling him on the train that someone had tried to rob Gringotts, but Ron hadn\rquote t mentioned the date.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Hagrid!\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote that Gringotts break-in happened on my birthday! It might\rquote ve been happening while we were there!\rdblquote\par
There was no doubt about it, Hagrid definitely didn\rquote t meet Harry\rquote s eyes this time. He grunted and offered him another rock cake. Harry read the story again. \i The vault that was searched had in fact been emptied earlier that same day.\i0  Hagrid had emptied vault seven hundred and thirteen, if you could call it emptying, taking out that grubby little package. Had that been what the thieves were looking for?\par
As Harry and Ron walked back to the castle for dinner, their pockets weighed down with rock cakes they\rquote d been too polite to refuse, Harry thought that none of the lessons he\rquote d had so far had given him as much to think about as tea with Hagrid. Had Hagrid collected that package just in time? Where was it now? And did Hagrid know something about Snape that he didn\rquote t want to tell Harry?\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 9\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Midnight Duel\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry had never believed he would meet a boy he hated more than Dudley, but that was before he met Draco Malfoy. Still, first-year Gryffindors only had Potions with the Slytherins, so they didn\rquote t have to put up with Malfoy much. Or at least, they didn\rquote t until they spotted a notice pinned up in the Gryffindor common room that made them all groan. Flying lessons would be starting on Thursday \emdash  and Gryffindor and Slytherin would be learning together.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote Typical,\rdblquote  said Harry darkly. \ldblquote Just what I always wanted. To make a fool of myself on a broomstick in front of Malfoy.\rdblquote\par
He had been looking forward to learning to fly more than any\-thing else.\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t know that you\rquote ll make a fool of yourself,\rdblquote  said Ron reasonably. \ldblquote Anyway, I know Malfoy\rquote s always going on about how good he is at Quidditch, but I bet that\rquote s all talk.\rdblquote\par
Malfoy certainly did talk about flying a lot. He complained loudly about first years never getting on the House Quidditch teams and told long, boastful stories that always seemed to end with him narrowly escaping Muggles in helicopters. He wasn\rquote t the only one, though: the way Seamus Finnigan told it, he\rquote d spent most of his childhood zooming around the countryside on his broom\-stick. Even Ron would tell anyone who\rquote d listen about the time he\rquote d almost hit a hang glider on Charlie\rquote s old broom. Everyone from wizarding families talked about Quidditch constantly. Ron had al\-ready had a big argument with Dean Thomas, who shared their dormitory, about soccer. Ron couldn\rquote t see what was exciting about a game with only one ball where no one was allowed to fly. Harry had caught Ron prodding Dean\rquote s poster of West Ham soccer team, trying to make the players move.\par
Neville had never been on a broomstick in his life, because his grandmother had never let him near one. Privately, Harry felt she\rquote d had good reason, because Neville managed to have an extraordi\-nary number of accidents even with both feet on the ground.\par
Hermione Granger was almost as nervous about flying as Neville was. This was something you couldn\rquote t learn by heart out of a book \emdash  not that she hadn\rquote t tried. At breakfast on Thursday she bored them all stupid with flying tips she\rquote d gotten out of a library book called \i Quidditch Through the Ages.\i0  Neville was hanging on to her every word, desperate for anything that might help him hang on to his broomstick later, but everybody else was very pleased when Hermione\rquote s lecture was interrupted by the arrival of the mail.\par
Harry hadn\rquote t had a single letter since Hagrid\rquote s note, something that Malfoy had been quick to notice, of course. Malfoy\rquote s eagle owl was always bringing him packages of sweets from home, which he opened gloatingly at the Slytherin table.\par
A barn owl brought Neville a small package from his grand\-mother. He opened it excitedly and showed them a glass ball the size of a large marble, which seemed to be full of white smoke.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s a Remembrall!\rdblquote  he explained. \ldblquote Gran knows I forget things \emdash  this tells you if there\rquote s something you\rquote ve forgotten to do. Look, you hold it tight like this and if it turns red \emdash  oh \'85\rdblquote  His face fell, because the Remembrall had suddenly glowed scarlet, \ldblquote\'85 you\rquote ve forgotten something \'85\rdblquote\par
Neville was trying to remember what he\rquote d forgotten when Draco Malfoy, who was passing the Gryffindor table, snatched the Re\-membrall out of his hand.\par
Harry and Ron jumped to their feet. They were half hoping for a reason to fight Malfoy, but Professor McGonagall, who could spot trouble quicker than any teacher in the school, was there in a flash.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Malfoy\rquote s got my Remembrall, Professor.\rdblquote\par
Scowling, Malfoy quickly dropped the Remembrall back on the table.\par
\ldblquote Just looking,\rdblquote  he said, and he sloped away with Crabbe and Goyle behind him.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj At three-thirty that afternoon, Harry, Ron, and the other Gryffin\-dors hurried down the front steps onto the grounds for their first flying lesson. It was a clear, breezy day, and the grass rippled under their feet as they marched down the sloping lawns toward a smooth, flat lawn on the opposite side of the grounds to the for\-bidden forest, whose trees were swaying darkly in the distance.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj The Slytherins were already there, and so were twenty broom\-sticks lying in neat lines on the ground. Harry had heard Fred and George Weasley complain about the school brooms, saying that some of them started to vibrate if you flew too high, or always flew slightly to the left.\par
Their teacher, Madam Hooch, arrived. She had short, gray hair, and yellow eyes like a hawk.\par
\ldblquote Well, what are you all waiting for?\rdblquote  she barked. \ldblquote Everyone stand by a broomstick. Come on, hurry up.\rdblquote\par
Harry glanced down at his broom. It was old and some of the twigs stuck out at odd angles.\par
\ldblquote Stick out your right hand over your broom,\rdblquote  called Madam Hooch at the front, \ldblquote and say \lquote Up!\rquote  \rdblquote\par
\ldblquote UP!\rdblquote  everyone shouted.\par
Harry\rquote s broom jumped into his hand at once, but it was one of the few that did. Hermione Granger\rquote s had simply rolled over on the ground, and Neville\rquote s hadn\rquote t moved at all. Perhaps brooms, like horses, could tell when you were afraid, thought Harry; there was a quaver in Neville\rquote s voice that said only too clearly that he wanted to keep his feet on the ground.\par
Madam Hooch then showed them how to mount their brooms without sliding off the end, and walked up and down the rows cor\-recting their grips. Harry and Ron were delighted when she told Malfoy he\rquote d been doing it wrong for years.\par
