\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Malfoy couldn\rquote t believe his eyes when he saw that Harry and Ron were still at Hogwarts the next day, looking tired but perfectly cheerful. Indeed, by the next morning Harry and Ron thought that meeting the three-headed dog had been an excellent adventure, and they were quite keen to have another one. In the meantime, Harry filled Ron in about the package that seemed to have been moved from Gringotts to Hogwarts, and they spent a lot of time wondering what could possibly need such heavy protection.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote It\rquote s either really valuable or really dangerous,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Or both,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
But as all they knew for sure about the mysterious object was that it was about two inches long, they didn\rquote t have much chance of guessing what it was without further clues.\par
Neither Neville nor Hermione showed the slightest interest in what lay underneath the dog and the trapdoor. All Neville cared about was never going near the dog again.\par
Hermione was now refusing to speak to Harry and Ron, but she was such a bossy know-it-all that they saw this as an added bonus. All they really wanted now was a way of getting back at Malfoy, and to their great delight, just such a thing arrived in the mail about a week later.\par
As the owls flooded into the Great Hall as usual, everyone\rquote s at\-tention was caught at once by a long, thin package carried by six large screech owls. Harry was just as interested as everyone else to see what was in this large parcel, and was amazed when the owls soared down and dropped it right in front of him, knocking his ba\-con to the floor. They had hardly fluttered out of the way when an\-other owl dropped a letter on top of the parcel.\par
Harry ripped open the letter first, which was lucky, because it said:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li567\ri567\qj DO NOT OPEN THE PARCEL AT THE TABLE.\par
It contains your new Nimbus Two Thousand, but I don\rquote t want everybody knowing you\rquote ve got a broomstick or they\rquote ll all want one. Oliver Wood will meet you tonight on the Quidditch field at seven o\rquote clock for your first training ses\-sion.\par
Professor M. McGonagall\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry had difficulty hiding his glee as he handed the note to Ron to read.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote A Nimbus Two Thousand!\rdblquote  Ron moaned enviously. \ldblquote I\rquote ve never even \i touched\i0  one.\rdblquote\par
They left the hall quickly, wanting to unwrap the broomstick in private before their first class, but halfway across the entrance hall they found the way upstairs barred by Crabbe and Goyle. Malfoy seized the package from Harry and felt it.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s a broomstick,\rdblquote  he said, throwing it back to Harry with a mixture of jealousy and spite on his face. \ldblquote You\rquote ll be in for it this time, Potter, first years aren\rquote t allowed them.\rdblquote\par
Ron couldn\rquote t resist it.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not any old broomstick,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote it\rquote s a Nimbus Two Thou\-sand. What did you say you\rquote ve got at home, Malfoy, a Comet Two Sixty?\rdblquote  Ron grinned at Harry. \ldblquote Comets look flashy, but they\rquote re not in the same league as the Nimbus.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What would you know about it, Weasley, you couldn\rquote t afford half the handle,\rdblquote  Malfoy snapped back. \ldblquote I suppose you and your brothers have to save up twig by twig.\rdblquote\par
Before Ron could answer, Professor Flitwick appeared at Mal\-foy\rquote s elbow.\par
\ldblquote Not arguing, I hope, boys?\rdblquote  he squeaked.\par
\ldblquote Potter\rquote s been sent a broomstick, Professor,\rdblquote  said Malfoy quickly.\par
\ldblquote Yes, yes, that\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Professor Flitwick, beaming at Harry. \ldblquote Professor McGonagall told me all about the special circumstances, Potter. And what model is it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A Nimbus Two Thousand, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, fighting not to laugh at the look of horror on Malfoy\rquote s face. \ldblquote And it\rquote s really thanks to Malfoy here that I\rquote ve got it,\rdblquote  he added.\par
Harry and Ron headed upstairs, smothering their laughter at Malfoy\rquote s obvious rage and confusion.\par
\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s true,\rdblquote  Harry chortled as they reached the top of the marble staircase, \ldblquote If he hadn\rquote t stolen Neville\rquote s Remembrall I wouldn\rquote t be on the team. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So I suppose you think that\rquote s a reward for breaking rules?\rdblquote  came an angry voice from just behind them. Hermione was stomping up the stairs, looking disapprovingly at the package in Harry\rquote s hand.\par
\ldblquote I thought you weren\rquote t speaking to us?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Yes, don\rquote t stop now,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote it\rquote s doing us so much good.\rdblquote\par
Hermione marched away with her nose in the air.\par
Harry had a lot of trouble keeping his mind on his lessons that day. It kept wandering up to the dormitory where his new broom\-stick was lying under his bed, or straying off to the Quidditch field where he\rquote d be learning to play that night. He bolted his din\-ner that evening without noticing what he was eating, and then rushed upstairs with Ron to unwrap the Nimbus Two Thousand at last.\par
\ldblquote Wow,\rdblquote  Ron sighed, as the broomstick rolled onto Harry\rquote s bed\-spread.\par
Even Harry, who knew nothing about the different brooms, thought it looked wonderful. Sleek and shiny, with a mahogany handle, it had a long tail of neat, straight twigs and Nimbus Two Thousand written in gold near the top.\par
As seven o\rquote clock drew nearer, Harry left the castle and set off in the dusk toward the Quidditch field. He\rquote d never been inside the stadium before. Hundreds of seats were raised in stands around the field so that the spectators were high enough to see what was going on. At either end of the field were three golden poles with hoops on the end. They reminded Harry of the little plastic sticks Muggle children blew bubbles through, except that they were fifty feet high.\par
Too eager to fly again to wait for Wood, Harry mounted his broomstick and kicked off from the ground. What a feeling \emdash  he swooped in and out of the goal posts and then sped up and down the field. The Nimbus Two Thousand turned wherever he wanted at his lightest touch.\par
\ldblquote Hey, Potter, come down!\rdblquote\par
Oliver Wood had arrived. He was carrying a large wooden crate under his arm. Harry landed next to him.\par
\ldblquote Very nice,\rdblquote  said Wood, his eyes glinting. \ldblquote I see what McGona\-gall meant \'85 you really are a natural. I\rquote m just going to teach you the rules this evening, then you\rquote ll be joining team practice three times a week.\rdblquote\par
He opened the crate. Inside were four different-sized balls.\par
\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote Now, Quidditch is easy enough to under\-stand, even if it\rquote s not too easy to play. There are seven players on each side. Three of them are called Chasers.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Three Chasers,\rdblquote  Harry repeated, as Wood took out a bright red ball about the size of a soccer ball.\par
\ldblquote This ball\rquote s called the Quaffle,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote The Chasers throw the Quaffle to each other and try and get it through one of the hoops to score a goal. Ten points every time the Quaffle goes through one of the hoops. Follow me?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The Chasers throw the Quaffle and put it through the hoops to score,\rdblquote  Harry recited. \ldblquote So \emdash  that\rquote s sort of like basketball on broomsticks with six hoops, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s basketball?\rdblquote  said Wood curiously.\par
\ldblquote Never mind,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly.\par
\ldblquote Now, there\rquote s another player on each side who\rquote s called the Keeper \emdash  I\rquote m Keeper for Gryffindor. I have to fly around our hoops and stop the other team from scoring.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Three Chasers, one Keeper,\rdblquote  said Harry, who was determined to remember it all. \ldblquote And they play with the Quaffle. Okay, got that. So what are they for?\rdblquote  He pointed at the three balls left inside the box.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll show you now,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote Take this.\rdblquote\par
He handed Harry a small club, a bit like a short baseball bat.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m going to show you what the Bludgers do,\rdblquote  Wood said. \ldblquote These two are the Bludgers.\rdblquote\par
He showed Harry two identical balls, jet black and slightly smaller than the red Quaffle. Harry noticed that they seemed to be straining to escape the straps holding them inside the box.\par
\ldblquote Stand back,\rdblquote  Wood warned Harry. He bent down and freed one of the Bludgers.\par
At once, the black ball rose high in the air and then pelted straight at Harry\rquote s face. Harry swung at it with the bat to stop it from breaking his nose, and sent it zigzagging away into the air \emdash  it zoomed around their heads and then shot at Wood, who dived on top of it and managed to pin it to the ground.\par
\ldblquote See?\rdblquote  Wood panted, forcing the struggling Bludger back into the crate and strapping it down safely. \ldblquote The Bludgers rocket around, trying to knock players off their brooms. That\rquote s why you have two Beaters on each team \emdash  the Weasley twins are ours \emdash  it\rquote s their job to protect their side from the Bludgers and try and knock them toward the other team. So \emdash  think you\rquote ve got all that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Three Chasers try and score with the Quaffle; the Keeper guards the goal posts; the Beaters keep the Bludgers away from their team,\rdblquote  Harry reeled off.\par
\ldblquote Very good,\rdblquote  said Wood.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  have the Bludgers ever killed anyone?\rdblquote  Harry asked, hop\-ing he sounded offhand.\par
\ldblquote Never at Hogwarts. We\rquote ve had a couple of broken jaws but nothing worse than that. Now, the last member of the team is the Seeker. That\rquote s you. And you don\rquote t have to worry about the Quaffle or the Bludgers \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\emdash  unless they crack my head open.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry, the Weasleys are more than a match for the Bludgers \emdash  I mean, they\rquote re like a pair of human Bludgers them\-selves.\rdblquote\par
Wood reached into the crate and took out the fourth and last ball. Compared with the Quaffle and the Bludgers, it was tiny, about the size of a large walnut. It was bright gold and had little fluttering silver wings.\par
\i\ldblquote This,\rdblquote\i0  said Wood, \ldblquote is the Golden Snitch, and it\rquote s the most im\-portant ball of the lot. It\rquote s very hard to catch because it\rquote s so fast and difficult to see. It\rquote s the Seeker\rquote s job to catch it. You\rquote ve got to weave in and out of the Chasers, Beaters, Bludgers, and Quaffle to get it before the other team\rquote s Seeker, because whichever Seeker catches the Snitch wins his team an extra hundred and fifty points, so they nearly always win. That\rquote s why Seekers get fouled so much. A game of Quidditch only ends when the Snitch is caught, so it can go on for ages \emdash  I think the record is three months, they had to keep bringing on substitutes so the players could get some sleep.\par
\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s it \emdash  any questions?\rdblquote\par
Harry shook his head. He understood what he had to do all right, it was doing it that was going to be the problem.\par
\ldblquote We won\rquote t practice with the Snitch yet,\rdblquote  said Wood, carefully shutting it back inside the crate, \ldblquote it\rquote s too dark, we might lose it. Let\rquote s try you out with a few of these.\rdblquote\par
He pulled a bag of ordinary golf balls out of his pocket and a few minutes later, he and Harry were up in the air, Wood throwing the golf balls as hard as he could in every direction for Harry to catch.\par
Harry didn\rquote t miss a single one, and Wood was delighted. After half an hour, night had really fallen and they couldn\rquote t carry on.\par
\ldblquote That Quidditch Cup\rquote ll have our name on it this year,\rdblquote  said Wood happily as they trudged back up to the castle. \ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t be surprised if you turn out better than Charlie Weasley, and he could have played for England if he hadn\rquote t gone off chasing dragons.\rdblquote\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Perhaps it was because he was now so busy, what with Quidditch practice three evenings a week on top of all his homework, but Harry could hardly believe it when he realized that he\rquote d already been at Hogwarts two months. The castle felt more like home than Privet Drive ever had. His lessons, too, were becoming more and more interesting now that they had mastered the basics.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj On Halloween morning they woke to the delicious smell of bak\-ing pumpkin wafting through the corridors. Even better, Professor Flitwick announced in Charms that he thought they were ready to start making objects fly, something they had all been dying to try since they\rquote d seen him make Neville\rquote s toad zoom around the class\-room. Professor Flitwick put the class into pairs to practice. Harry\rquote s partner was Seamus Finnigan (which was a relief, because Neville had been trying to catch his eye). Ron, however, was to be working with Hermione Granger. It was hard to tell whether Ron or Hermione was angrier about this. She hadn\rquote t spoken to either of them since the day Harry\rquote s broomstick had arrived.\par
\ldblquote Now, don\rquote t forget that nice wrist movement we\rquote ve been practic\-ing!\rdblquote  squeaked Professor Flitwick, perched on top of his pile of books as usual. \ldblquote Swish and flick, remember, swish and flick. And saying the magic words properly is very important, too \emdash  never forget Wizard Baruffio, who said \lquote s\rquote  instead of \lquote f\rquote  and found himself on the floor with a buffalo on his chest.\rdblquote\par
It was very difficult. Harry and Seamus swished and flicked, but the feather they were supposed to be sending skyward just lay on the desktop. Seamus got so impatient that he prodded it with his wand and set fire to it \emdash  Harry had to put it out with his hat.\par
Ron, at the next table, wasn\rquote t having much more luck.\par
\i\ldblquote Wingardium Leviosa!\rdblquote  \i0 he shouted, waving his long arms like a windmill.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re saying it wrong,\rdblquote  Harry heard Hermione snap. \ldblquote It\rquote s Wing-\i gar\i0 -dium Levi-\i o\i0 -sa, make the \lquote gar\rquote  nice and long.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You do it, then, if you\rquote re so clever,\rdblquote  Ron snarled.\par
Hermione rolled up the sleeves of her gown, flicked her wand, and said, \i\ldblquote Wingardium Leviosa!\rdblquote\i0\par
Their feather rose off the desk and hovered about four feet above their heads.\par
\ldblquote Oh, well done!\rdblquote  cried Professor Flitwick, clapping. \ldblquote Everyone see here, Miss Granger\rquote s done it!\rdblquote\par
Ron was in a very bad mood by the end of the class.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s no wonder no one can stand her,\rdblquote  he said to Harry as they pushed their way into the crowded corridor, \ldblquote she\rquote s a nightmare, honestly.\rdblquote\par
Someone knocked into Harry as they hurried past him. It was Hermione. Harry caught a glimpse of her face \emdash  and was startled to see that she was in tears.\par
\ldblquote I think she heard you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So?\rdblquote  said Ron, but he looked a bit uncomfortable. \ldblquote She must\rquote ve noticed she\rquote s got no friends.\rdblquote\par
Hermione didn\rquote t turn up for the next class and wasn\rquote t seen all af\-ternoon. On their way down to the Great Hall for the Halloween feast, Harry and Ron overheard Parvati Patil telling her friend Lavender that Hermione was crying in the girls\rquote  bathroom and wanted to be left alone. Ron looked still more awkward at this, but a moment later they had entered the Great Hall, where the Hal\-loween decorations put Hermione out of their minds.\par
A thousand live bats fluttered from the walls and ceiling while a thousand more swooped over the tables in low black clouds, mak\-ing the candles in the pumpkins stutter. The feast appeared sud\-denly on the golden plates, as it had at the start-of-term banquet.\par
Harry was just helping himself to a baked potato when Professor Quirrell came sprinting into the hall, his turban askew and terror on his face. Everyone stared as he reached Professor Dumbledore\rquote s chair, slumped against the table, and gasped, \ldblquote Troll \emdash  in the dun\-geons \emdash  thought you ought to know.\rdblquote\par
He then sank to the floor in a dead faint.\par
There was an uproar. It took several purple firecrackers explod\-ing from the end of Professor Dumbledore\rquote s wand to bring silence.\par
\ldblquote Prefects,\rdblquote  he rumbled, \ldblquote lead your Houses back to the dormito\-ries immediately!\rdblquote\par
Percy was in his element.\par
\ldblquote Follow me! Stick together, first years! No need to fear the troll if you follow my orders! Stay close behind me, now. Make way, first years coming through! Excuse me, I\rquote m a prefect!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How could a troll get in?\rdblquote  Harry asked as they climbed the stairs.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t ask me, they\rquote re supposed to be really stupid,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Maybe Peeves let it in for a Halloween joke.\rdblquote\par
They passed different groups of people hurrying in different di\-rections. As they jostled their way through a crowd of confused Hufflepuffs, Harry suddenly grabbed Ron\rquote s arm.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve just thought \emdash  Hermione.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about her?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She doesn\rquote t know about the troll.\rdblquote\par
Ron bit his lip.\par
\ldblquote Oh, all right,\rdblquote  he snapped. \ldblquote But Percy\rquote d better not see us.\rdblquote\par
Ducking down, they joined the Hufflepuffs going the other way, slipped down a deserted side corridor, and hurried off toward the girls\rquote  bathroom. They had just turned the corner when they heard quick footsteps behind them.\par
\ldblquote Percy!\rdblquote  hissed Ron, pulling Harry behind a large stone griffin.\par
Peering around it, however, they saw not Percy but Snape. He crossed the corridor and disappeared from view.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s he doing?\rdblquote  Harry whispered. \ldblquote Why isn\rquote t he down in the dungeons with the rest of the teachers?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Search me.\rdblquote\par
Quietly as possible, they crept along the next corridor after Snape\rquote s fading footsteps.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s heading for the third floor,\rdblquote  Harry said, but Ron held up his hand.\par
\ldblquote Can you smell something?\rdblquote\par
Harry sniffed and a foul stench reached his nostrils, a mixture of old socks and the kind of public toilet no one seems to clean.\par
And then they heard it \emdash  a low grunting, and the shuffling footfalls of gigantic feet. Ron pointed \emdash  at the end of a passage to the left, something huge was moving toward them. They shrank into the shadows and watched as it emerged into a patch of moon\-light.\par
It was a horrible sight. Twelve feet tall, its skin was a dull, gran\-ite gray, its great lumpy body like a boulder with its small bald head perched on top like a coconut. It had short legs thick as tree trunks with flat, horny feet. The smell coming from it was incredible. It was holding a huge wooden club, which dragged along the floor because its arms were so long.\par
The troll stopped next to a doorway and peered inside. It wag\-gled its long ears, making up its tiny mind, then slouched slowly into the room.\par
\ldblquote The key\rquote s in the lock,\rdblquote  Harry muttered. \ldblquote We could lock it in.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good idea,\rdblquote  said Ron nervously.\par
They edged toward the open door, mouths dry, praying the troll wasn\rquote t about to come out of it. With one great leap, Harry man\-aged to grab the key, slam the door, and lock it.\par
\i\ldblquote Yes!\rdblquote\par
\i0 Flushed with their victory, they started to run back up the passage, but as they reached the corner they heard something that made their hearts stop \emdash  a high, petrified scream \emdash  and it was coming from the chamber they\rquote d just chained up.\par
\ldblquote Oh, no,\rdblquote  said Ron, pale as the Bloody Baron.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s the girls\rquote  bathroom!\rdblquote  Harry gasped.\par
\i\ldblquote Hermione!\rdblquote\i0  they said together.\par
It was the last thing they wanted to do, but what choice did they have? Wheeling around, they sprinted back to the door and turned the key, fumbling in their panic. Harry pulled the door open and they ran inside.\par
Hermione Granger was shrinking against the wall opposite, looking as if she was about to faint. The troll was advancing on her, knocking the sinks off the walls as it went.\par
\ldblquote Confuse it!\rdblquote  Harry said desperately to Ron, and, seizing a tap, he threw it as hard as he could against the wall.\par
The troll stopped a few feet from Hermione. It lumbered around, blinking stupidly, to see what had made the noise. Its mean little eyes saw Harry. It hesitated, then made for him instead, lifting its club as it went.\par
\ldblquote Oy, pea-brain!\rdblquote  yelled Ron from the other side of the chamber, and he threw a metal pipe at it. The troll didn\rquote t even seem to notice the pipe hitting its shoulder, but it heard the yell and paused again, turning its ugly snout toward Ron instead, giving Harry time to run around it.\par
\ldblquote Come on, run, \i run!\rdblquote\i0  Harry yelled at Hermione, trying to pull her toward the door, but she couldn\rquote t move, she was still flat against the wall, her mouth open with terror.\par
The shouting and the echoes seemed to be driving the troll berserk. It roared again and started toward Ron, who was nearest and had no way to escape.\par
Harry then did something that was both very brave and very stu\-pid: He took a great running jump and managed to fasten his arms around the troll\rquote s neck from behind. The troll couldn\rquote t feel Harry hanging there, but even a troll will notice if you stick a long bit of wood up its nose, and Harry\rquote s wand had still been in his hand when he\rquote d jumped \emdash  it had gone straight up one of the troll\rquote s nostrils.\par
Howling with pain, the troll twisted and flailed its club, with Harry clinging on for dear life; any second, the troll was going to rip him off or catch him a terrible blow with the club.\par
Hermione had sunk to the floor in fright; Ron pulled out his own wand \emdash  not knowing what he was going to do he heard him\-self cry the first spell that came into his head: \i\ldblquote Wingardium Leviosa!\rdblquote\i0\par
The club flew suddenly out of the troll\rquote s hand, rose high, high up into the air, turned slowly over \emdash  and dropped, with a sicken\-ing crack, onto its owner\rquote s head. The troll swayed on the spot and then fell flat on its face, with a thud that made the whole room tremble.\par
Harry got to his feet. He was shaking and out of breath. Ron was standing there with his wand still raised, staring at what he had done.\par
It was Hermione who spoke first.\par
\ldblquote Is it \emdash  dead?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t think so,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote I think it\rquote s just been knocked out.\rdblquote\par
He bent down and pulled his wand out of the troll\rquote s nose. It was covered in what looked like lumpy gray glue.\par
\ldblquote Urgh \lang3081\emdash\lang1033  troll boogers.\rdblquote\par
He wiped it on the troll\rquote s trousers.\par
A sudden slamming and loud footsteps made the three of them look up. They hadn\rquote t realized what a racket they had been making, but of course, someone downstairs must have heard the crashes and the troll\rquote s roars. A moment later, Professor McGonagall had come bursting into the room, closely followed by Snape, with Quirrell bringing up the rear. Quirrell took one look at the troll, let out a faint whimper, and sat quickly down on a toilet, clutching his heart.\par
Snape bent over the troll. Professor McGonagall was looking at Ron and Harry. Harry had never seen her look so angry. Her lips were white. Hopes of winning fifty points for Gryffindor faded quickly from Harry\rquote s mind.\par
\ldblquote What on earth were you thinking of?\rdblquote  said Professor McGona\-gall, with cold fury in her voice. Harry looked at Ron, who was still standing with his wand in the air. \ldblquote You\rquote re lucky you weren\rquote t killed. Why aren\rquote t you in your dormitory?\rdblquote\par
Snape gave Harry a swift, piercing look. Harry looked at the floor. He wished Ron would put his wand down.\par
Then a small voice came out of the shadows.\par
\ldblquote Please, Professor McGonagall \emdash  they were looking for me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Miss Granger!\rdblquote\par
Hermione had managed to get to her feet at last.\par
\ldblquote I went looking for the troll because I \emdash  I thought I could deal with it on my own \emdash  you know, because I\rquote ve read all about them.\rdblquote\par
Ron dropped his wand. Hermione Granger, telling a downright lie to a teacher?\par
\ldblquote If they hadn\rquote t found me, I\rquote d be dead now. Harry stuck his wand up its nose and Ron knocked it out with its own club. They didn\rquote t have time to come and fetch anyone. It was about to finish me off when they arrived.\rdblquote\par
Harry and Ron tried to look as though this story wasn\rquote t new to them.\par
\ldblquote Well \emdash  in that case \'85\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, staring at the three of them, \ldblquote Miss Granger, you foolish girl, how could you think of tackling a mountain troll on your own?\rdblquote\par
Hermione hung her head. Harry was speechless. Hermione was the last person to do anything against the rules, and here she was, pretending she had, to get them out of trouble. It was as if Snape had started handing out sweets.\par
\ldblquote Miss Granger, five points will be taken from Gryffindor for this,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote I\rquote m very disappointed in you. If you\rquote re not hurt at all, you\rquote d better get off to Gryffindor Tower. Stu\-dents are finishing the feast in their Houses.\rdblquote\par
Hermione left.\par
Professor McGonagall turned to Harry and Ron.\par
\ldblquote Well, I still say you were lucky, but not many first years could have taken on a full-grown mountain troll. You each win Gryffindor five points. Professor Dumbledore will be informed of this. You may go.\rdblquote\par
They hurried out of the chamber and didn\rquote t speak at all until they had climbed two floors up. It was a relief to be away from the smell of the troll, quite apart from anything else.\par
\ldblquote We should have gotten more than ten points,\rdblquote  Ron grumbled.\par
\ldblquote Five, you mean, once she\rquote s taken off Hermione\rquote s.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good of her to get us out of trouble like that,\rdblquote  Ron admitted. \ldblquote Mind you, we \i did\i0  save her.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She might not have needed saving if we hadn\rquote t locked the thing in with her,\rdblquote  Harry reminded him.\par
They had reached the portrait of the Fat Lady.\par
\ldblquote Pig snout,\rdblquote  they said and entered.\par
The common room was packed and noisy. Everyone was eating the food that had been sent up. Hermione, however, stood alone by the door, waiting for them. There was a very embarrassed pause. Then, none of them looking at each other, they all said \ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  and hurried off to get plates.\par
But from that moment on, Hermione Granger became their friend. There are some things you can\rquote t share without ending up liking each other, and knocking out a twelve-foot mountain troll is one of them.\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 11\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Quidditch\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj As they entered November, the weather turned very cold. The mountains around the school became icy gray and the lake like chilled steel. Every morning the ground was covered in frost. Hagrid could be seen from the upstairs windows defrost\-ing broomsticks on the Quidditch field, bundled up in a long moleskin overcoat, rabbit fur gloves, and enormous beaverskin boots.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj The Quidditch season had begun. On Saturday, Harry would be playing in his first match after weeks of training: Gryffindor versus Slytherin. If Gryffindor won, they would move up into second place in the House Championship.\par
Hardly anyone had seen Harry play because Wood had decided that, as their secret weapon, Harry should be kept, well, secret. But the news that he was playing Seeker had leaked out somehow, and Harry didn\rquote t know which was worse \emdash  people telling him he\rquote d be brilliant or people telling him they\rquote d be running around under\-neath him holding a mattress.\par
It was really lucky that Harry now had Hermione as a friend. He didn\rquote t know how he\rquote d have gotten through all his homework with\-out her, what with all the last-minute Quidditch practice Wood was making them do. She had also lent him \i Quidditch Through the Ages,\i0  which turned out to be a very interesting read.\par
Harry learned that there were seven hundred ways of commit\-ting a Quidditch foul and that all of them had happened during a World Cup match in 1473; that Seekers were usually the smallest and fastest players, and that most serious Quidditch accidents seemed to happen to them; that although people rarely died play\-ing Quidditch, referees had been known to vanish and turn up months later in the Sahara Desert.\par
Hermione had become a bit more relaxed about breaking rules since Harry and Ron had saved her from the mountain troll, and she was much nicer for it. The day before Harry\rquote s first Quidditch match the three of them were out in the freezing courtyard during break, and she had conjured them up a bright blue fire that could be carried around in a jam jar. They were standing with their backs to it, getting warm, when Snape crossed the yard. Harry noticed at once that Snape was limping. Harry, Ron, and Hermione moved closer together to block the fire from view; they were sure it wouldn\rquote t be allowed. Unfortunately, something about their guilty faces caught Snape\rquote s eye. He limped over. He hadn\rquote t seen the fire, but he seemed to be looking for a reason to tell them off anyway.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s that you\rquote ve got there, Potter?\rdblquote\par
It was \i Quidditch Through the Ages.\i0  Harry showed him.\par
\ldblquote Library books are not to be taken outside the school,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote Give it to me. Five points from Gryffindor.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s just made that rule up,\rdblquote  Harry muttered angrily as Snape limped away. \ldblquote Wonder what\rquote s wrong with his leg?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Dunno, but I hope it\rquote s really hurting him,\rdblquote  said Ron bitterly.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The Gryffindor common room was very noisy that evening. Harry, Ron, and Hermione sat together next to a window. Hermione was checking Harry and Ron\rquote s Charms homework for them. She would never let them copy (\ldblquote How will you learn?\rdblquote ), but by asking her to read it through, they got the right answers anyway.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Harry felt restless. He wanted \i Quidditch Through the Ages\i0  back, to take his mind off his nerves about tomorrow. Why should he be afraid of Snape? Getting up, he told Ron and Hermione he was go\-ing to ask Snape if he could have it.\par
\ldblquote Better you than me,\rdblquote  they said together, but Harry had an idea that Snape wouldn\rquote t refuse if there were other teachers listening.\par
He made his way down to the staffroom and knocked. There was no answer. He knocked again. Nothing.\par
Perhaps Snape had left the book in there? It was worth a try. He pushed the door ajar and peered inside \emdash  and a horrible scene met his eyes.\par
Snape and Filch were inside, alone. Snape was holding his robes above his knees. One of his legs was bloody and mangled. Filch was handing Snape bandages.\par
\ldblquote Blasted thing,\rdblquote  Snape was saying. \ldblquote How are you supposed to keep your eyes on all three heads at once?\rdblquote\par
Harry tried to shut the door quietly, but \emdash\par
\ldblquote POTTER!\rdblquote\par
Snape\rquote s face was twisted with fury as he dropped his robes quickly to hide his leg. Harry gulped.\par
\ldblquote I just wondered if I could have my book back.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote GET OUT! \i OUT!\rdblquote\i0\par
Harry left, before Snape could take any more points from Gryffindor. He sprinted back upstairs.\par
\ldblquote Did you get it?\rdblquote  Ron asked as Harry joined them. \ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote\par
In a low whisper, Harry told them what he\rquote d seen.\par
\ldblquote You know what this means?\rdblquote  he finished breathlessly. \ldblquote He tried to get past that three-headed dog at Halloween! That\rquote s where he was going when we saw him \emdash  he\rquote s after whatever it\rquote s guarding! And I\rquote d bet my broomstick \i he\i0  let that troll in, to make a diversion!\rdblquote\par
Hermione\rquote s eyes were wide.\par
\ldblquote No \emdash  he wouldn\rquote t,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote I know he\rquote s not very nice, but he wouldn\rquote t try and steal something Dumbledore was keeping safe.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Honestly, Hermione, you think all teachers are saints or some\-thing,\rdblquote  snapped Ron. \ldblquote I\rquote m with Harry. I wouldn\rquote t put anything past Snape. But what\rquote s he after? What\rquote s that dog guarding?\rdblquote\par
Harry went to bed with his head buzzing with the same ques\-tion. Neville was snoring loudly, but Harry couldn\rquote t sleep. He tried to empty his mind \emdash  he needed to sleep, he had to, he had his first Quidditch match in a few hours \emdash  but the expression on Snape\rquote s face when Harry had seen his leg wasn\rquote t easy to forget.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The next morning dawned very bright and cold. The Great Hall was full of the delicious smell of fried sausages and the cheerful chatter of everyone looking forward to a good Quidditch match.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote You\rquote ve got to eat some breakfast.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t want anything.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Just a bit of toast,\rdblquote  wheedled Hermione.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not hungry.\rdblquote\par
Harry felt terrible. In an hour\rquote s time he\rquote d be walking onto the field.\par
\ldblquote Harry, you need your strength,\rdblquote  said Seamus Finnigan. \ldblquote Seek\-ers are always the ones who get clobbered by the other team.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks, Seamus,\rdblquote  said Harry, watching Seamus pile ketchup on his sausages.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj By eleven o\rquote clock the whole school seemed to be out in the stands around the Quidditch pitch. Many students had binoculars. The seats might be raised high in the air, but it was still difficult to see what was going on sometimes.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Ron and Hermione joined Neville, Seamus, and Dean the West Ham fan up in the top row. As a surprise for Harry, they had painted a large banner on one of the sheets Scabbers had ruined. It said \i Potter for President,\i0  and Dean, who was good at drawing, had done a large Gryffindor lion underneath. Then Hermione had performed a tricky little charm so that the paint flashed different colors.\par
Meanwhile, in the locker room, Harry and the rest of the team were changing into their scarlet Quidditch robes (Slytherin would be playing in green).\par
Wood cleared his throat for silence.\par
\ldblquote Okay, men,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote And women,\rdblquote  said Chaser Angelina Johnson.\par
\ldblquote And women,\rdblquote  Wood agreed. \ldblquote This is it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The big one,\rdblquote  said Fred Weasley.\par
\ldblquote The one we\rquote ve all been waiting for,\rdblquote  said George.\par
\ldblquote We know Oliver\rquote s speech by heart,\rdblquote  Fred told Harry, \ldblquote we were on the team last year.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Shut up, you two,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote This is the best team Gryf\-findor\rquote s had in years. We\rquote re going to win. I know it.\rdblquote\par
He glared at them all as if to say, \ldblquote Or else.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right. It\rquote s time. Good luck, all of you.\rdblquote\par
Harry followed Fred and George out of the locker room and, hoping his knees weren\rquote t going to give way, walked onto the field to loud cheers.\par
Madam Hooch was refereeing. She stood in the middle of the field waiting for the two teams, her broom in her hand.\par
\ldblquote Now, I want a nice fair game, all of you,\rdblquote  she said, once they were all gathered around her. Harry noticed that she seemed to be speaking particularly to the Slytherin Captain, Marcus Flint, a fifth year. Harry thought Flint looked as if he had some troll blood in him. Out of the corner of his eye he saw the fluttering banner high above, flashing \i Potter for President\i0  over the crowd. His heart skipped. He felt braver.\par
\ldblquote Mount your brooms, please.\rdblquote\par
Harry clambered onto his Nimbus Two Thousand.\par
Madam Hooch gave a loud blast on her silver whistle.\par
Fifteen brooms rose up, high, high into the air. They were off.\par
\ldblquote And the Quaffle is taken immediately by Angelina Johnson of Gryffindor \emdash  what an excellent Chaser that girl is, and rather at\-tractive, too \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote JORDAN!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sorry, Professor.\rdblquote\par
The Weasley twins\rquote  friend, Lee Jordan, was doing the commen\-tary for the match, closely watched by Professor McGonagall.\par
\ldblquote And she\rquote s really belting along up there, a neat pass to Alicia Spinnet, a good find of Oliver Wood\rquote s, last year only a reserve \emdash  back to Johnson and \emdash  no, the Slytherins have taken the Quaffle, Slytherin Captain Marcus Flint gains the Quaffle and off he goes \emdash  Flint flying like an eagle up there \emdash  he\rquote s going to sc- no, stopped by an excellent move by Gryffindor Keeper Wood and the Gryffindors take the Quaffle \emdash  that\rquote s Chaser Katie Bell of Gryffindor there, nice dive around Flint, off up the field and \emdash  OUCH \emdash  that must have hurt, hit in the back of the head by a Bludger \emdash  Quaffle taken by the Slytherins \emdash  that\rquote s Adrian Pucey speeding off toward the goal posts, but he\rquote s blocked by a second Bludger \emdash  sent his way by Fred or George Weasley, can\rquote t tell which \emdash  nice play by the Gryffindor Beater, anyway, and Johnson back in possession of the Quaffle, a clear field ahead and off she goes \emdash  she\rquote s really flying \emdash  dodges a speeding Bludger \emdash  the goal posts are ahead \emdash  come on, now, Angelina \emdash  Keeper Bletch\-ley dives \emdash  misses \emdash  GRYFFINDORS SCORE!\rdblquote\par
Gryffindor cheers filled the cold air, with howls and moans from the Slytherins.\par
\ldblquote Budge up there, move along.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hagrid!\rdblquote\par
Ron and Hermione squeezed together to give Hagrid enough space to join them.\par
\ldblquote Bin watchin\rquote  from me hut,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, patting a large pair of binoculars around his neck, \ldblquote But it isn\rquote t the same as bein\rquote  in the crowd. No sign of the Snitch yet, eh?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nope,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Harry hasn\rquote t had much to do yet.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Kept outta trouble, though, that\rquote s somethin\rquote ,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, rais\-ing his binoculars and peering skyward at the speck that was Harry.\par
Way up above them, Harry was gliding over the game, squinting about for some sign of the Snitch. This was part of his and Wood\rquote s game plan.\par
\ldblquote Keep out of the way until you catch sight of the Snitch,\rdblquote  Wood had said. \ldblquote We don\rquote t want you attacked before you have to be.\rdblquote\par
When Angelina had scored, Harry had done a couple of loop-the-loops to let off his feelings. Now he was back to staring around for the Snitch. Once he caught sight of a flash of gold, but it was just a reflection from one of the Weasleys\rquote  wristwatches, and once a Bludger decided to come pelting his way, more like a cannonball than anything, but Harry dodged it and Fred Weasley came chas\-ing after it.\par
\ldblquote All right there, Harry?\rdblquote  he had time to yell, as he beat the Bludger furiously toward Marcus Flint.\par
\ldblquote Slytherin in possession,\rdblquote  Lee Jordan was saying, \ldblquote Chaser Pucey ducks two Bludgers, two Weasleys, and Chaser Bell, and speeds toward the \emdash  wait a moment \emdash  was that the Snitch?\rdblquote\par
A murmur ran through the crowd as Adrian Pucey dropped the Quaffle, too busy looking over his shoulder at the flash of gold that had passed his left ear.\par
Harry saw it. In a great rush of excitement he dived downward after the streak of gold. Slytherin Seeker Terence Higgs had seen it, too. Neck and neck they hurtled toward the Snitch \emdash  all the Chasers seemed to have forgotten what they were supposed to be doing as they hung in midair to watch.\par
Harry was faster than Higgs \emdash  he could see the little round ball, wings fluttering, darting up ahead \emdash  he put on an extra spurt of speed \emdash\par
WHAM! A roar of rage echoed from the Gryffindors below \emdash  Marcus Flint had blocked Harry on purpose, and Harry\rquote s broom spun off course, Harry holding on for dear life.\par
\ldblquote Foul!\rdblquote  screamed the Gryffindors.\par
Madam Hooch spoke angrily to Flint and then ordered a free shot at the goal posts for Gryffindor. But in all the confusion, of course, the Golden Snitch had disappeared from sight again.\par
Down in the stands, Dean Thomas was yelling, \ldblquote Send him off, ref! Red card!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What are you talking about, Dean?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Red card!\rdblquote  said Dean furiously. \ldblquote In soccer you get shown the red card and you\rquote re out of the game!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But this isn\rquote t soccer, Dean,\rdblquote  Ron reminded him.\par
Hagrid, however, was on Dean\rquote s side.\par
\ldblquote They oughta change the rules. Flint coulda knocked Harry outta the air.\rdblquote\par
Lee Jordan was finding it difficult not to take sides.\par
\ldblquote So \emdash  after that obvious and disgusting bit of cheating \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jordan!\rdblquote  growled Professor McGonagall.\par
\ldblquote I mean, after that open and revolting foul \emdash\rdblquote\par
\i\ldblquote Jordan, I\rquote m warning you \emdash\rdblquote\par
\i0\ldblquote All right, all right. Flint nearly kills the Gryffindor Seeker, which could happen to anyone, I\rquote m sure, so a penalty to Gryffindor, taken by Spinnet, who puts it away, no trouble, and we continue play, Gryffindor still in possession.\rdblquote\par
It was as Harry dodged another Bludger, which went spinning dangerously past his head, that it happened. His broom gave a sud\-den, frightening lurch. For a split second, he thought he was going to fall. He gripped the broom tightly with both his hands and knees. He\rquote d never felt anything like that.\par
It happened again. It was as though the broom was trying to buck him off. But Nimbus Two Thousands did not suddenly de\-cide to buck their riders off. Harry tried to turn back toward the Gryffindor goal posts \emdash  he had half a mind to ask Wood to call time-out \emdash  and then he realized that his broom was completely out of his control. He couldn\rquote t turn it. He couldn\rquote t direct it at all. It was zigzagging through the air, and every now and then making vi\-olent swishing movements that almost unseated him.\par
Lee was still commentating.\par
\ldblquote Slytherin in possession \emdash  Flint with the Quaffle \emdash  passes Spinnet \emdash  passes Bell \emdash  hit hard in the face by a Bludger, hope it broke his nose \emdash  only joking, Professor \emdash  Slytherins score \emdash  oh no \'85\rdblquote\par
The Slytherins were cheering. No one seemed to have noticed that Harry\rquote s broom was behaving strangely It was carrying him slowly higher, away from the game, jerking and twitching as it went.\par
\ldblquote Dunno what Harry thinks he\rquote s doing,\rdblquote  Hagrid mumbled. He stared through his binoculars. \ldblquote If I didn\rquote  know better, I\rquote d say he\rquote d lost control of his broom \'85 but he can\rquote t have. \'85\rdblquote\par
Suddenly, people were pointing up at Harry all over the stands. His broom had started to roll over and over, with him only just managing to hold on. Then the whole crowd gasped. Harry\rquote s broom had given a wild jerk and Harry swung off it. He was now dangling from it, holding on with only one hand.\par
\ldblquote Did something happen to it when Flint blocked him?\rdblquote  Seamus whispered.\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t have,\rdblquote  Hagrid said, his voice shaking. \ldblquote Can\rquote t nothing in\-terfere with a broomstick except powerful Dark magic \emdash  no kid could do that to a Nimbus Two Thousand.\rdblquote\par
At these words, Hermione seized Hagrid\rquote s binoculars, but in\-stead of looking up at Harry, she started looking frantically at the crowd.\par
\ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote  moaned Ron, gray-faced.\par
\ldblquote I knew it,\rdblquote  Hermione gasped, \ldblquote Snape \emdash  look.\rdblquote\par
Ron grabbed the binoculars. Snape was in the middle of the stands opposite them. He had his eyes fixed on Harry and was mut\-tering nonstop under his breath.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s doing something \emdash  jinxing the broom,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\par
\ldblquote What should we do?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Leave it to me.\rdblquote\par
Before Ron could say another word, Hermione had disappeared. Ron turned the binoculars back on Harry. His broom was vibrat\-ing so hard, it was almost impossible for him to hang on much longer. The whole crowd was on its feet, watching, terrified, as the Weasleys flew up to try and pull Harry safely onto one of their brooms, but it was no good \emdash  every time they got near him, the broom would jump higher still. They dropped lower and cir\-cled beneath him, obviously hoping to catch him if he fell. Marcus Flint seized the Quaffle and scored five times without anyone noticing.\par
\ldblquote Come on, Hermione,\rdblquote  Ron muttered desperately.\par
Hermione had fought her way across to the stand where Snape stood, and was now racing along the row behind him; she didn\rquote t even stop to say sorry as she knocked Professor Quirrell headfirst into the row in front. Reaching Snape, she crouched down, pulled out her wand, and whispered a few, well-chosen words. Bright blue flames shot from her wand onto the hem of Snape\rquote s robes.\par
It took perhaps thirty seconds for Snape to realize that he was on fire. A sudden yelp told her she had done her job. Scooping the fire off him into a little jar in her pocket, she scrambled back along the row \emdash  Snape would never know what had happened.\par
It was enough. Up in the air, Harry was suddenly able to clam\-ber back on to his broom.\par
\ldblquote Neville, you can look!\rdblquote  Ron said. Neville had been sobbing into Hagrid\rquote s jacket for the last five minutes.\par
Harry was speeding toward the ground when the crowd saw him clap his hand to his mouth as though he was about to be sick \emdash  he hit the field on all fours \emdash  coughed \emdash  and something gold fell into his hand.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve got the Snitch!\rdblquote  he shouted, waving it above his head, and the game ended in complete confusion.\par
\ldblquote He didn\rquote t \i catch\i0  it, he nearly \i swallowed\i0  it,\rdblquote  Flint was still howl\-ing twenty minutes later, but it made no difference \emdash  Harry hadn\rquote t broken any rules and Lee Jordan was still happily shouting the results \emdash  Gryffindor had won by one hundred and seventy points to sixty. Harry heard none of this, though. He was being made a cup of strong tea back in Hagrid\rquote s hut, with Ron and Hermione.\par
\ldblquote It was Snape,\rdblquote  Ron was explaining, \ldblquote Hermione and I saw him. He was cursing your broomstick, muttering, he wouldn\rquote t take his eyes off you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Rubbish,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, who hadn\rquote t heard a word of what had gone on next to him in the stands. \ldblquote Why would Snape do some\-thin\rquote  like that?\rdblquote\par
Harry, Ron, and Hermione looked at one another, wondering what to tell him. Harry decided on the truth.\par
\ldblquote I found out something about him,\rdblquote  he told Hagrid. \ldblquote He tried to get past that three-headed dog on Halloween. It bit him. We think he was trying to steal whatever it\rquote s guarding.\rdblquote\par
Hagrid dropped the teapot.\par
\ldblquote How do you know about Fluffy?\rdblquote  he said.\par
\i\ldblquote Fluffy?\rdblquote\par
\i0\ldblquote Yeah \emdash  he\rquote s mine \emdash  bought him off a Greek chappie I met in the pub las\rquote  year \emdash  I lent him to Dumbledore to guard the \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote  said Harry eagerly.\par
\ldblquote Now, don\rquote t ask me anymore,\rdblquote  said Hagrid gruffly. \ldblquote That\rquote s top secret, that is.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But Snape\rquote s trying to \i steal\i0  it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Rubbish,\rdblquote  said Hagrid again. \ldblquote Snape\rquote s a Hogwarts teacher, he\rquote d do nothin\rquote  of the sort.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So why did he just try and kill Harry?\rdblquote  cried Hermione.\par
The afternoon\rquote s events certainly seemed to have changed her mind about Snape.\par
\ldblquote I know a jinx when I see one, Hagrid, I\rquote ve read all about them! You\rquote ve got to keep eye contact, and Snape wasn\rquote t blinking at all, I saw him!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m tellin\rquote  yeh, yer wrong!\rdblquote  said Hagrid hotly. \ldblquote I don\rquote  know why Harry\rquote s broom acted like that, but Snape wouldn\rquote  try an\rquote  kill a stu\-dent! Now, listen to me, all three of yeh \emdash  yer meddlin\rquote  in things that don\rquote  concern yeh. It\rquote s dangerous. You forget that dog, an\rquote  you forget what it\rquote s guardin\rquote , that\rquote s between Professor Dumbledore an\rquote  Nicolas Flamel \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Aha!\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote so there\rquote s someone called Nicolas Flamel in\-volved, is there?\rdblquote\par
Hagrid looked furious with himself.\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 12\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Mirror Of Erised\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Christmas was coming. One morning in mid-December, Hogwarts woke to find itself covered in several feet of snow. The lake froze solid and the Weasley twins were punished for be\-witching several snowballs so that they followed Quirrell around, bouncing off the back of his turban. The few owls that managed to battle their way through the stormy sky to deliver mail had to be nursed back to health by Hagrid before they could fly off again.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj No one could wait for the holidays to start. While the Gryf\-findor common room and the Great Hall had roaring fires, the drafty corridors had become icy and a bitter wind rattled the windows in the classrooms. Worst of all were Professor Snape\rquote s classes down in the dungeons, where their breath rose in a mist before them and they kept as close as possible to their hot caul\-drons.\par
\ldblquote I do feel so sorry,\rdblquote  said Draco Malfoy, one Potions class, \ldblquote for all those people who have to stay at Hogwarts for Christmas because they\rquote re not wanted at home.\rdblquote\par
He was looking over at Harry as he spoke. Crabbe and Goyle chuckled. Harry, who was measuring out powdered spine of lion-fish, ignored them. Malfoy had been even more unpleasant than usual since the Quidditch match. Disgusted that the Slytherins had lost, he had tried to get everyone laughing at how a wide-mouthed tree frog would be replacing Harry as Seeker next. Then he\rquote d real\-ized that nobody found this funny, because they were all so im\-pressed at the way Harry had managed to stay on his bucking broomstick. So Malfoy, jealous and angry, had gone back to taunt\-ing Harry about having no proper family.\par
It was true that Harry wasn\rquote t going back to Privet Drive for Christmas. Professor McGonagall had come around the week be\-fore, making a list of students who would be staying for the holi\-days, and Harry had signed up at once. He didn\rquote t feel sorry for himself at all; this would probably be the best Christmas he\rquote d ever had. Ron and his brothers were staying, too, because Mr. and Mrs. Weasley were going to Romania to visit Charlie.\par
When they left the dungeons at the end of Potions, they found a large fir tree blocking the corridor ahead. Two enormous feet sticking out at the bottom and a loud puffing sound told them that Hagrid was behind it.\par
\ldblquote Hi, Hagrid, want any help?\rdblquote  Ron asked, sticking his head through the branches.\par
\ldblquote Nah, I\rquote m all right, thanks, Ron.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Would you mind moving out of the way?\rdblquote  came Malfoy\rquote s cold drawl from behind them. \ldblquote Are you trying to earn some extra money, Weasley? Hoping to be gamekeeper yourself when you leave Hogwarts, I suppose \emdash  that hut of Hagrid\rquote s must seem like a palace compared to what your family\rquote s used to.\rdblquote\par
Ron dived at Malfoy just as Snape came up the stairs.\par
\ldblquote WEASLEY!\rdblquote\par
Ron let go of the front of Malfoy\rquote s robes.\par
\ldblquote He was provoked, Professor Snape,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, sticking his huge hairy face out from behind the tree. \ldblquote Malfoy was insultin\rquote  his family.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Be that as it may, fighting is against Hogwarts rules, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Snape silkily. \ldblquote Five points from Gryffindor, Weasley, and be grateful it isn\rquote t more. Move along, all of you.\rdblquote\par
Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle pushed roughly past the tree, scat\-tering needles everywhere and smirking.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll get him,\rdblquote  said Ron, grinding his teeth at Malfoy\rquote s back, \ldblquote one of these days, I\rquote ll get him \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I hate them both,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote Malfoy and Snape.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come on, cheer up, it\rquote s nearly Christmas,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Tell yeh what, come with me an\rquote  see the Great Hall, looks a treat.\rdblquote\par
