\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry had never in all his life had such a Christmas dinner. A hun\-dred fat, roast turkeys; mountains of roast and boiled potatoes; platters of chipolatas; tureens of buttered peas, silver boats of thick, rich gravy and cranberry sauce \emdash  and stacks of wizard crackers every few feet along the table. These fantastic party favors were nothing like the feeble Muggle ones the Dursleys usually bought, with their little plastic toys and their flimsy paper hats inside. Harry pulled a wizard cracker with Fred and it didn\rquote t just bang, it went off with a blast like a cannon and engulfed them all in a cloud of blue smoke, while from the inside exploded a rear admiral\rquote s hat and several live, white mice. Up at the High Table, Dumbledore had swapped his pointed wizard\rquote s hat for a flowered bonnet, and was chuckling merrily at a joke Professor Flitwick had just read him.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Flaming Christmas puddings followed the turkey. Percy nearly broke his teeth on a silver Sickle embedded in his slice. Harry watched Hagrid getting redder and redder in the face as he called for more wine, finally kissing Professor McGonagall on the cheek, who, to Harry\rquote s amazement, giggled and blushed, her top hat lop\-sided.\par
When Harry finally left the table, he was laden down with a stack of things out of the crackers, including a pack of non-explodable, luminous balloons, a Grow-Your-Own-Warts kit, and his own new wizard chess set. The white mice had disappeared and Harry had a nasty feeling they were going to end up as Mrs. Nor\-ris\rquote s Christmas dinner.\par
Harry and the Weasleys spent a happy afternoon having a furi\-ous snowball fight on the grounds. Then, cold, wet, and gasping for breath, they returned to the fire in the Gryffindor common room, where Harry broke in his new chess set by losing spectacu\-larly to Ron. He suspected he wouldn\rquote t have lost so badly if Percy hadn\rquote t tried to help him so much.\par
After a meal of turkey sandwiches, crumpets, trifle, and Christ\-mas cake, everyone felt too full and sleepy to do much before bed except sit and watch Percy chase Fred and George all over Gryffindor Tower because they\rquote d stolen his prefect badge.\par
It had been Harry\rquote s best Christmas day ever. Yet something had been nagging at the back of his mind all day. Not until he climbed into bed was he free to think about it: the Invisibility Cloak and whoever had sent it.\par
Ron, full of turkey and cake and with nothing mysterious to bother him, fell asleep almost as soon as he\rquote d drawn the curtains of his four-poster. Harry leaned over the side of his own bed and pulled the cloak out from under it.\par
His father\rquote s \'85 this had been his father\rquote s. He let the material flow over his hands, smoother than silk, light as air. \i Use it well,\i0  the note had said.\par
He had to try it, now. He slipped out of bed and wrapped the cloak around himself. Looking down at his legs, he saw only moon\-light and shadows. It was a very funny feeling.\par
\i Use it well.\i0\par
Suddenly, Harry felt wide-awake. The whole of Hogwarts was open to him in this cloak. Excitement flooded through him as he stood there in the dark and silence. He could go anywhere in this, anywhere, and Filch would never know.\par
Ron grunted in his sleep. Should Harry wake him? Something held him back \emdash  his father\rquote s cloak \emdash  he felt that this time \emdash  the first time \emdash  he wanted to use it alone.\par
He crept out of the dormitory, down the stairs, across the com\-mon room, and climbed through the portrait hole.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  squawked the Fat Lady. Harry said nothing. He walked quickly down the corridor.\par
Where should he go? He stopped, his heart racing, and thought. And then it came to him. The Restricted Section in the library. He\rquote d be able to read as long as he liked, as long as it took to find out who Flamel was. He set off, drawing the Invisibility Cloak tight around him as he walked.\par
The library was pitch-black and very eerie. Harry lit a lamp to see his way along the rows of books. The lamp looked as if it was floating along in midair, and even though Harry could feel his arm supporting it, the sight gave him the creeps.\par
The Restricted Section was right at the back of the library. Stepping carefully over the rope that separated these books from the rest of the library, he held up his lamp to read the titles.\par
They didn\rquote t tell him much. Their peeling, faded gold letters spelled words in languages Harry couldn\rquote t understand. Some had no title at all. One book had a dark stain on it that looked horribly like blood. The hairs on the back of Harry\rquote s neck prickled. Maybe he was imagining it, maybe not, but he thought a faint whispering was coming from the books, as though they knew someone was there who shouldn\rquote t be.\par
He had to start somewhere. Setting the lamp down carefully on the floor, he looked along the bottom shelf for an interesting-looking book. A large black and silver volume caught his eye. He pulled it out with difficulty, because it was very heavy, and, balanc\-ing it on his knee, let it fall open.\par
A piercing, bloodcurdling shriek split the silence \emdash  the book was screaming! Harry snapped it shut, but the shriek went on and on, one high, unbroken, earsplitting note. He stumbled backward and knocked over his lamp, which went out at once. Panicking, he heard footsteps coming down the corridor outside \emdash  stuffing the shrieking book back on the shelf, he ran for it. He passed Filch in the doorway; Filch\rquote s pale, wild eyes looked straight through him, and Harry slipped under Filch\rquote s outstretched arm and streaked off up the corridor, the book\rquote s shrieks still ringing in his ears.\par
He came to a sudden halt in front of a tall suit of armor. He had been so busy getting away from the library, he hadn\rquote t paid attention to where he was going. Perhaps because it was dark, he didn\rquote t rec\-ognize where he was at all. There was a suit of armor near the kitchens, he knew, but he must be five floors above there.\par
\ldblquote You asked me to come directly to you, Professor, if anyone was wandering around at night, and somebody\rquote s been in the library \emdash  Restricted Section.\rdblquote\par
Harry felt the blood drain out of his face. Wherever he was, Filch must know a shortcut, because his soft, greasy voice was get\-ting nearer, and to his horror, it was Snape who replied, \ldblquote The Re\-stricted Section? Well, they can\rquote t be far, we\rquote ll catch them.\rdblquote\par
Harry stood rooted to the spot as Filch and Snape came around the corner ahead. They couldn\rquote t see him, of course, but it was a nar\-row corridor and if they came much nearer they\rquote d knock right into him \emdash  the cloak didn\rquote t stop him from being solid.\par
He backed away as quietly as he could. A door stood ajar to his left. It was his only hope. He squeezed through it, holding his breath, trying not to move it, and to his relief he managed to get in\-side the room without their noticing anything. They walked straight past, and Harry leaned against the wall, breathing deeply, listening to their footsteps dying away. That had been close, very close. It was a few seconds before he noticed anything about the room he had hidden in.\par
It looked like an unused classroom. The dark shapes of desks and chairs were piled against the walls, and there was an upturned wastepaper basket \emdash  but propped against the wall facing him was something that didn\rquote t look as if it belonged there, something that looked as if someone had just put it there to keep it out of the way.\par
It was a magnificent mirror, as high as the ceiling, with an ornate gold frame, standing on two clawed feet. There was an inscription carved around the top: \i Erised stra ehru oyt ube cafru oyt on wohsi.\i0\par
His panic fading now that there was no sound of Filch and Snape, Harry moved nearer to the mirror, wanting to look at him\-self but see no reflection again. He stepped in front of it.\par
He had to clap his hands to his mouth to stop himself from screaming. He whirled around. His heart was pounding far more furiously than when the book had screamed \emdash  for he had seen not only himself in the mirror, but a whole crowd of people standing right behind him.\par
But the room was empty. Breathing very fast, he turned slowly back to the mirror.\par
There he was, reflected in it, white and scared-looking, and there, reflected behind him, were at least ten others. Harry looked over his shoulder \emdash  but still, no one was there. Or were they all in\-visible, too? Was he in fact in a room full of invisible people and this mirrors trick was that it reflected them, invisible or not?\par
He looked in the mirror again. A woman standing right behind his reflection was smiling at him and waving. He reached out a hand and felt the air behind him. If she was really there, he\rquote d touch her, their reflections were so close together, but he felt only air \emdash  she and the others existed only in the mirror.\par
She was a very pretty woman. She had dark red hair and her eyes \emdash  \i her eyes are just like mine,\i0  Harry thought, edging a little closer to the glass. Bright green \emdash  exactly the same shape, but then he noticed that she was crying; smiling, but crying at the same time. The tall, thin, black-haired man standing next to her put his arm around her. He wore glasses, and his hair was very untidy. It stuck up at the back, just as Harry\rquote s did.\par
Harry was so close to the mirror now that his nose was nearly touching that of his reflection.\par
\ldblquote Mom?\rdblquote  he whispered. \ldblquote Dad?\rdblquote\par
They just looked at him, smiling. And slowly, Harry looked into the faces of the other people in the mirror, and saw other pairs of green eyes like his, other noses like his, even a little old man who looked as though he had Harry\rquote s knobbly knees \emdash  Harry was looking at his family, for the first time in his life.\par
The Potters smiled and waved at Harry and he stared hungrily back at them, his hands pressed flat against the glass as though he was hoping to fall right through it and reach them. He had a pow\-erful kind of ache inside him, half joy, half terrible sadness.\par
How long he stood there, he didn\rquote t know. The reflections did not fade and he looked and looked until a distant noise brought him back to his senses. He couldn\rquote t stay here, he had to find his way back to bed. He tore his eyes away from his mother\rquote s face, whis\-pered, \ldblquote I\rquote ll come back,\rdblquote  and hurried from the room.\par
