\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Nicholas Flamel\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Dumbledore had convinced Harry not to go looking for the Mirror of Erised again, and for the rest of the Christmas holidays the Invisibility Cloak stayed folded at the bottom of his trunk. Harry wished he could forget what he\rquote d seen in the mirror as easily, but he couldn\rquote t. He started having nightmares. Over and over again he dreamed about his parents disappearing in a flash of green light, while a high voice cackled with laughter.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote You see, Dumbledore was right, that mirror could drive you mad,\rdblquote  said Ron, when Harry told him about these dreams.\par
Hermione, who came back the day before term started, took a different view of things. She was torn between horror at the idea of Harry being out of bed, roaming the school three nights in a row (\ldblquote If Filch had caught you!\rdblquote ), and disappointment that he hadn\rquote t at least found out who Nicolas Flamel was.\par
They had almost given up hope of ever finding Flamel in a library book, even though Harry was still sure he\rquote d read the name somewhere. Once term had started, they were back to skimming through books for ten minutes during their breaks. Harry had even less time than the other two, because Quidditch practice had started again.\par
Wood was working the team harder than ever. Even the endless rain that had replaced the snow couldn\rquote t dampen his spirits. The Weasleys complained that Wood was becoming a fanatic, but Harry was on Wood\rquote s side. If they won their next match, against Hufflepuff, they would overtake Slytherin in the House Champi\-onship for the first time in seven years. Quite apart from wanting to win, Harry found that he had fewer nightmares when he was tired out after training.\par
Then, during one particularly wet and muddy practice session, Wood gave the team a bit of bad news. He\rquote d just gotten very angry with the Weasleys, who kept dive-bombing each other and pre\-tending to fall off their brooms.\par
\ldblquote Will you stop messing around!\rdblquote  he yelled. \ldblquote That\rquote s exactly the sort of thing that\rquote ll lose us the match! Snape\rquote s refereeing this time, and he\rquote ll be looking for any excuse to knock points off Gryffindor!\rdblquote\par
George Weasley really did fall off his broom at these words.\par
\i\ldblquote Snape\rquote s\i0  refereeing?\rdblquote  he spluttered through a mouthful of mud. \ldblquote When\rquote s he ever refereed a Quidditch match? He\rquote s not going to be fair if we might overtake Slytherin.\rdblquote\par
The rest of the team landed next to George to complain, too.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not \i my\i0  fault,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote We\rquote ve just got to make sure we play a clean game, so Snape hasn\rquote t got an excuse to pick on us.\rdblquote\par
Which was all very well, thought Harry, but he had another rea\-son for not wanting Snape near him while he was playing Quid\-ditch. \'85\par
The rest of the team hung back to talk to one another as usual at the end of practice, but Harry headed straight back to the Gryf\-findor common room, where he found Ron and Hermione playing chess. Chess was the only thing Hermione ever lost at, something Harry and Ron thought was very good for her.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t talk to me for a moment,\rdblquote  said Ron when Harry sat down next to him, \ldblquote I need to concen-\rdblquote  He caught sight of Harry\rquote s face. \ldblquote What\rquote s the matter with you? You look terrible.\rdblquote\par
Speaking quietly so that no one else would hear, Harry told the other two about Snape\rquote s sudden, sinister desire to be a Quidditch referee.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t play,\rdblquote  said Hermione at once.\par
\ldblquote Say you\rquote re ill,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Pretend to break your leg,\rdblquote  Hermione suggested.\par
\i\ldblquote Really\i0  break your leg,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote I can\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote There isn\rquote t a reserve Seeker. If I back out, Gryffindor can\rquote t play at all.\rdblquote\par
At that moment Neville toppled into the common room. How he had managed to climb through the portrait hole was anyone\rquote s guess, because his legs had been stuck together with what they recognized at once as the Leg-Locker Curse. He must have had to bunny hop all the way up to Gryffindor Tower.\par
Everyone fell over laughing except Hermione, who leapt up and performed the countercurse. Neville\rquote s legs sprang apart and he got to his feet, trembling.\par
\ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote  Hermione asked him, leading him over to sit with Harry and Ron.\par
\ldblquote Malfoy,\rdblquote  said Neville shakily. \ldblquote I met him outside the library. He said he\rquote d been looking for someone to practice that on.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Go to Professor McGonagall!\rdblquote  Hermione urged Neville. \ldblquote Re\-port him!\rdblquote\par
Neville shook his head.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t want more trouble,\rdblquote  he mumbled.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve got to stand up to him, Neville!\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote He\rquote s used to walking all over people, but that\rquote s no reason to lie down in front of him and make it easier.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s no need to tell me I\rquote m not brave enough to be in Gryffindor, Malfoy\rquote s already done that,\rdblquote  Neville choked out.\par
Harry felt in the pocket of his robes and pulled out a Chocolate Frog, the very last one from the box Hermione had given him for Christmas. He gave it to Neville, who looked as though he might cry.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re worth twelve of Malfoy,\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote The Sorting Hat chose you for Gryffindor, didn\rquote t it? And where\rquote s Malfoy? In stink\-ing Slytherin.\rdblquote\par
Neville\rquote s lips twitched in a weak smile as he unwrapped the frog.\par
\ldblquote Thanks, Harry \'85 I think I\rquote ll go to bed. \'85 D\rquote you want the card, you collect them, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
As Neville walked away, Harry looked at the Famous Wizard card.\par
\ldblquote Dumbledore again,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote He was the first one I ever \emdash\rdblquote\par
He gasped. He stared at the back of the card. Then he looked up at Ron and Hermione.\par
\i\ldblquote I\rquote ve found him!\rdblquote\i0  he whispered. \ldblquote I\rquote ve found Flamel! I \i told\i0  you I\rquote d read the name somewhere before, I read it on the train coming here \emdash  listen to this: \lquote Dumbledore is particularly famous for his defeat of the Dark wizard Grindelwald in 1945, for the discovery of the twelve uses of dragon\rquote s blood, \i and his work on alchemy with his partner, Nicolas Flamel\rquote !\rdblquote\i0\par
Hermione jumped to her feet. She hadn\rquote t looked so excited since they\rquote d gotten back the marks for their very first piece of homework.\par
\ldblquote Stay there!\rdblquote  she said, and she sprinted up the stairs to the girls\rquote  dormitories. Harry and Ron barely had time to exchange mystified looks before she was dashing back, an enormous old book in her arms.\par
\ldblquote I never thought to look in here!\rdblquote  she whispered excitedly. \ldblquote I got this out of the library weeks ago for a bit of light reading.\rdblquote\par
\i\ldblquote Light?\rdblquote\i0  said Ron, but Hermione told him to be quiet until she\rquote d looked something up, and started flicking frantically through the pages, muttering to herself.\par
At last she found what she was looking for.\par
\ldblquote I knew it! I \i knew\i0  it!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Are we allowed to speak yet?\rdblquote  said Ron grumpily. Hermione ig\-nored him.\par
\ldblquote Nicolas Flamel,\rdblquote  she whispered dramatically, \ldblquote is the \i only known maker of the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone!\rdblquote\i0\par
This didn\rquote t have quite the effect she\rquote d expected.\par
\ldblquote The what?\rdblquote  said Harry and Ron.\par
\ldblquote Oh, \i honestly,\i0  don\rquote t you two read? Look \emdash  read that, there.\rdblquote\par
She pushed the book toward them, and Harry and Ron read:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li567\ri567\qj\i The ancient study of alchemy is concerned with mak\-ing the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone, a legendary substance with as\-tonishing powers. The Stone will transform any metal into pure gold. It also produces the Elixir of Life, which will make the drinker immortal.\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\li567\ri567\qj\i There have been many reports of the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone over the centuries, but the only Stone currently in existence belongs to Mr. Nicolas Flamel, the noted alchemist and opera lover. Mr. Flamel, who cele\-brated his six hundred and sixty-fifth birthday last year, enjoys a quiet life in Devon with his wife, Perenelle (six hundred and fifty-eight).\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj\ldblquote See?\rdblquote  said Hermione, when Harry and Ron had finished. \ldblquote The dog must be guarding Flamel\rquote s Sorcerer\rquote s Stone! I bet he asked Dumbledore to keep it safe for him, because they\rquote re friends and he knew someone was after it, that\rquote s why he wanted the Stone moved out of Gringotts!\rdblquote\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote A stone that makes gold and stops you from ever dying!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote No wonder Snape\rquote s after it! \i Anyone \i0 would want it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And no wonder we couldn\rquote t find Flamel in that \i Study of Recent Developments in Wizardry,\rdblquote  \i0 said Ron. \ldblquote He\rquote s not exactly recent if he\rquote s six hundred and sixty-five, is he?\rdblquote\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj The next morning in Defense Against the Dark Arts, while copy\-ing down different ways of treating werewolf bites, Harry and Ron were still discussing what they\rquote d do with a Sorcerer\rquote s Stone if they had one. It wasn\rquote t until Ron said he\rquote d buy his own Quidditch team that Harry remembered about Snape and the coming match.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote I\rquote m going to play,\rdblquote  he told Ron and Hermione. \ldblquote If I don\rquote t, all the Slytherins will think I\rquote m just too scared to face Snape. I\rquote ll show them \'85 it\rquote ll really wipe the smiles off their faces if we win.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Just as long as we\rquote re not wiping you off the field,\rdblquote  said Her\-mione.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj As the match drew nearer, however, Harry became more and more nervous, whatever he told Ron and Hermione. The rest of the team wasn\rquote t too calm, either. The idea of overtaking Slytherin in the House Championship was wonderful, no one had done it for seven years, but would they be allowed to, with such a biased referee?\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Harry didn\rquote t know whether he was imagining it or not, but he seemed to keep running into Snape wherever he went. At times, he even wondered whether Snape was following him, trying to catch him on his own. Potions lessons were turning into a sort of weekly torture, Snape was so horrible to Harry. Could Snape possibly know they\rquote d found out about the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone? Harry didn\rquote t see how he could \emdash  yet he sometimes had the horrible feeling that Snape could read minds.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry knew, when they wished him good luck outside the locker rooms the next afternoon, that Ron and Hermione were wonder\-ing whether they\rquote d ever see him alive again. This wasn\rquote t what you\rquote d call comforting. Harry hardly heard a word of Wood\rquote s pep talk as he pulled on his Quidditch robes and picked up his Nimbus Two Thousand.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Ron and Hermione, meanwhile, had found a place in the stands next to Neville, who couldn\rquote t understand why they looked so grim and worried, or why they had both brought their wands to the match. Little did Harry know that Ron and Hermione had been secretly practicing the Leg-Locker Curse. They\rquote d gotten the idea from Malfoy using it on Neville, and were ready to use it on Snape if he showed any sign of wanting to hurt Harry.\par
\ldblquote Now, don\rquote t forget, it\rquote s \i Locomotor Mortis,\rdblquote\i0  Hermione muttered as Ron slipped his wand up his sleeve.\par
\ldblquote I \i know,\rdblquote\i0  Ron snapped. \ldblquote Don\rquote t nag.\rdblquote\par
Back in the locker room, Wood had taken Harry aside.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t want to pressure you, Potter, but if we ever need an early capture of the Snitch it\rquote s now. Finish the game before Snape can fa\-vor Hufflepuff too much.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The whole school\rquote s out there!\rdblquote  said Fred Weasley, peering out of the door. \ldblquote Even \emdash  blimey \emdash  Dumbledore\rquote s come to watch!\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s heart did a somersault.\par
\i\ldblquote Dumbledore?\rdblquote\i0  he said, dashing to the door to make sure. Fred was right. There was no mistaking that silver beard.\par
Harry could have laughed out loud with relief. He was safe. There was simply no way that Snape would dare to try to hurt him if Dumbledore was watching.\par
Perhaps that was why Snape was looking so angry as the teams marched onto the field, something that Ron noticed, too.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve never seen Snape look so mean,\rdblquote  he told Hermione. \ldblquote Look \emdash  they\rquote re off. Ouch!\rdblquote\par
Someone had poked Ron in the back of the head. It was Malfoy.\par
\ldblquote Oh, sorry, Weasley, didn\rquote t see you there.\rdblquote\par
Malfoy grinned broadly at Crabbe and Goyle.\par
\ldblquote Wonder how long Potter\rquote s going to stay on his broom this time? Anyone want a bet? What about you, Weasley?\rdblquote\par
Ron didn\rquote t answer; Snape had just awarded Hufflepuff a penalty because George Weasley had hit a Bludger at him. Hermione, who had all her fingers crossed in her lap, was squinting fixedly at Harry, who was circling the game like a hawk, looking for the Snitch.\par
\ldblquote You know how I think they choose people for the Gryffindor team?\rdblquote  said Malfoy loudly a few minutes later, as Snape awarded Hufflepuff another penalty for no reason at all. \ldblquote It\rquote s people they feel sorry for. See, there\rquote s Potter, who\rquote s got no parents, then there\rquote s the Weasleys, who\rquote ve got no money \emdash  you should be on the team, Longbottom, you\rquote ve got no brains.\rdblquote\par
Neville went bright red but turned in his seat to face Malfoy.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m worth twelve of you, Malfoy,\rdblquote  he stammered.\par
Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle howled with laughter, but Ron, still not daring to take his eyes from the game, said, \ldblquote You tell him, Neville.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Longbottom, if brains were gold you\rquote d be poorer than Weasley, and that\rquote s saying something.\rdblquote\par
Ron\rquote s nerves were already stretched to the breaking point with anxiety about Harry.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m warning you, Malfoy \emdash  one more word \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ron!\rdblquote  said Hermione suddenly, \ldblquote Harry \emdash  !\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What? Where?\rdblquote\par
Harry had suddenly gone into a spectacular dive, which drew gasps and cheers from the crowd. Hermione stood up, her crossed fingers in her mouth, as Harry streaked toward the ground like a bullet.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re in luck, Weasley, Potter\rquote s obviously spotted some money on the ground!\rdblquote  said Malfoy.\par
Ron snapped. Before Malfoy knew what was happening, Ron was on top of him, wrestling him to the ground. Neville hesitated, then clambered over the back of his seat to help.\par
\ldblquote Come on, Harry!\rdblquote  Hermione screamed, leaping onto her seat to watch as Harry sped straight at Snape \emdash  she didn\rquote t even notice Malfoy and Ron rolling around under her seat, or the scuffles and yelps coming from the whirl of fists that was Neville, Crabbe, and Goyle.\par
Up in the air, Snape turned on his broomstick just in time to see something scarlet shoot past him, missing him by inches \emdash  the next second, Harry had pulled out of the dive, his arm raised in tri\-umph, the Snitch clasped in his hand.\par
The stands erupted; it had to be a record, no one could ever re\-member the Snitch being caught so quickly.\par
\ldblquote Ron! Ron! Where are you? The game\rquote s over! Harry\rquote s won! We\rquote ve won! Gryffindor is in the lead!\rdblquote  shrieked Hermione, dancing up and down on her seat and hugging Parvati Patil in the row in front.\par
Harry jumped off his broom, a foot from the ground. He couldn\rquote t believe it. He\rquote d done it \emdash  the game was over; it had barely lasted five minutes. As Gryffindors came spilling onto the field, he saw Snape land nearby, white-faced and tight-lipped \emdash  then Harry felt a hand on his shoulder and looked up into Dumble\-dore\rquote s smiling face.\par
\ldblquote Well done,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly, so that only Harry could hear. \ldblquote Nice to see you haven\rquote t been brooding about that mirror \'85 been keeping busy \'85 excellent \'85\rdblquote\par
Snape spat bitterly on the ground.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc *   *   *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Harry left the locker room alone some time later, to take his Nim\-bus Two Thousand back to the broomshed. He couldn\rquote t ever re\-member feeling happier. He\rquote d really done something to be proud of now \emdash  no one could say he was just a famous name any more. The evening air had never smelled so sweet. He walked over the damp grass, reliving the last hour in his head, which was a happy blur: Gryffindors running to lift him onto their shoulders; Ron and Hermione in the distance, jumping up and down, Ron cheering through a heavy nosebleed.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Harry had reached the shed. He leaned against the wooden door and looked up at Hogwarts, with its windows glowing red in the setting sun. Gryffindor in the lead. He\rquote d done it, he\rquote d shown Snape. \'85\par
And speaking of Snape \'85\par
A hooded figure came swiftly down the front steps of the castle. Clearly not wanting to be seen, it walked as fast as possible toward the forbidden forest. Harry\rquote s victory faded from his mind as he watched. He recognized the figure\rquote s prowling walk. Snape, sneak\-ing into the forest while everyone else was at dinner \emdash  what was going on?\par
Harry jumped back on his Nimbus Two Thousand and took off. Gliding silently over the castle he saw Snape enter the forest at a run. He followed.\par
The trees were so thick he couldn\rquote t see where Snape had gone. He flew in circles, lower and lower, brushing the top branches of trees until he heard voices. He glided toward them and landed noiselessly in a towering beech tree.\par
He climbed carefully along one of the branches, holding tight to his broomstick, trying to see through the leaves.\par
Below, in a shadowy clearing, stood Snape, but he wasn\rquote t alone. Quirrell was there, too. Harry couldn\rquote t make out the look on his face, but he was stuttering worse than ever. Harry strained to catch what they were saying.\par
\ldblquote\'85 d-don\rquote t know why you wanted t-t-to meet here of all p-places, Severus \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, I thought we\rquote d keep this private,\rdblquote  said Snape, his voice icy. \ldblquote Students aren\rquote t supposed to know about the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone, after all.\rdblquote\par
Harry leaned forward. Quirrell was mumbling something. Snape interrupted him.\par
\ldblquote Have you found out how to get past that beast of Hagrid\rquote s yet?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote B-b-but Severus, I \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t want me as your enemy, Quirrell,\rdblquote  said Snape, taking a step toward him.\par
\ldblquote I-I don\rquote t know what you \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You know perfectly well what I mean.\rdblquote\par
An owl hooted loudly, and Harry nearly fell out of the tree. He steadied himself in time to hear Snape say, \ldblquote\emdash  your little bit of hocus-pocus. I\rquote m waiting.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote B-but I d-d-don\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  Snape cut in. \ldblquote We\rquote ll have another little chat soon, when you\rquote ve had time to think things over and decided where your loyalties lie.\rdblquote\par
He threw his cloak over his head and strode out of the clearing. It was almost dark now, but Harry could see Quirrell, standing quite still as though he was petrified.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc *   *   *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj\ldblquote Harry, where have you \i been?\rdblquote\i0  Hermione squeaked.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\ldblquote We won! You won! We won!\rdblquote  shouted Ron, thumping Harry on the back. \ldblquote And I gave Malfoy a black eye, and Neville tried to take on Crabbe and Goyle single-handed! He\rquote s still out cold but Madam Pomfrey says he\rquote ll be all right \emdash  talk about showing Slytherin! Everyone\rquote s waiting for you in the common room, we\rquote re having a party, Fred and George stole some cakes and stuff from the kitchens.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Never mind that now,\rdblquote  said Harry breathlessly. \ldblquote Let\rquote s find an empty room, you wait \rquote til you hear this. \'85\rdblquote\par
He made sure Peeves wasn\rquote t inside before shutting the door be\-hind them, then he told them what he\rquote d seen and heard.\par
\ldblquote So we were right, it \i is \i0 the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone, and Snape\rquote s trying to force Quirrell to help him get it. He asked if he knew how to get past Fluffy \emdash  and he said something about Quirrell\rquote s \lquote hocus-pocus\rquote  \emdash  I reckon there are other things guarding the stone apart from Fluffy, loads of enchantments, probably, and Quirrell would have done some anti-Dark Arts spell that Snape needs to break through \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So you mean the Stone\rquote s only safe as long as Quirrell stands up to Snape?\rdblquote  said Hermione in alarm.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote ll be gone by next Tuesday,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 14\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Norbert the Norwegian Ridgeback\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\fs24\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Quirrell, however, must have been braver than they\rquote d thought. In the weeks that followed he did seem to be get\-ting paler and thinner, but it didn\rquote t look as though he\rquote d cracked yet.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Every time they passed the third-floor corridor, Harry, Ron, and Hermione would press their ears to the door to check that Fluffy was still growling inside. Snape was sweeping about in his usual bad temper, which surely meant that the Stone was still safe. Whenever Harry passed Quirrell these days he gave him an en\-couraging sort of smile, and Ron had started telling people off for laughing at Quirrell\rquote s stutter.\par
Hermione, however, had more on her mind than the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone. She had started drawing up study schedules and color-coding all her notes. Harry and Ron wouldn\rquote t have minded, but she kept nagging them to do the same.\par
\ldblquote Hermione, the exams are ages away.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ten weeks,\rdblquote  Hermione snapped. \ldblquote That\rquote s not ages, that\rquote s like a second to Nicolas Flamel.\rdblquote\par
