A hundred and fifty points lost. That put Gryffindor in last place. In one night, they\rquote d ruined any chance Gryffindor had had for the House Cup. Harry felt as though the bottom had dropped out of his stomach. How could they ever make up for this?\par
Harry didn\rquote t sleep all night. He could hear Neville sobbing into his pillow for what seemed like hours. Harry couldn\rquote t think of any\-thing to say to comfort him. He knew Neville, like himself, was dreading the dawn. What would happen when the rest of Gryf\-findor found out what they\rquote d done?\par
At first, Gryffindors passing the giant hourglasses that recorded the House points the next day thought there\rquote d been a mistake. How could they suddenly have a hundred and fifty points fewer than yesterday? And then the story started to spread: Harry Potter, the famous Harry Potter, their hero of two Quidditch matches, had lost them all those points, him and a couple of other stupid first years.\par
From being one of the most popular and admired people at the school, Harry was suddenly the most hated. Even Ravenclaws and Hufflepuffs turned on him, because everyone had been longing to see Slytherin lose the House Cup. Everywhere Harry went, people pointed and didn\rquote t trouble to lower their voices as they insulted him. Slytherins, on the other hand, clapped as he walked past them, whistling and cheering, \ldblquote Thanks Potter, we owe you one!\rdblquote\par
Only Ron stood by him.\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ll all forget this in a few weeks. Fred and George have lost loads of points in all the time they\rquote ve been here, and people still like them.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ve never lost a hundred and fifty points in one go, though, have they?\rdblquote  said Harry miserably.\par
\ldblquote Well \emdash  no,\rdblquote  Ron admitted.\par
It was a bit late to repair the damage, but Harry swore to himself not to meddle in things that weren\rquote t his business from now on. He\rquote d had it with sneaking around and spying. He felt so ashamed of himself that he went to Wood and offered to resign from the Quidditch team.\par
\i\ldblquote Resign?\rdblquote\i0  Wood thundered. \ldblquote What good\rquote ll that do? How are we going to get any points back if we can\rquote t win at Quidditch?\rdblquote\par
But even Quidditch had lost its fun. The rest of the team wouldn\rquote t speak to Harry during practice, and if they had to speak about him, they called him \ldblquote the Seeker.\rdblquote\par
Hermione and Neville were suffering, too. They didn\rquote t have as bad a time as Harry, because they weren\rquote t as well-known, but no\-body would speak to them, either. Hermione had stopped drawing attention to herself in class, keeping her head down and working in silence.\par
Harry was almost glad that the exams weren\rquote t far away. All the studying he had to do kept his mind off his misery. He, Ron, and Hermione kept to themselves, working late into the night, trying to remember the ingredients in complicated potions, learn charms and spells by heart, memorize the dates of magical discoveries and goblin rebellions. \'85\par
Then, about a week before the exams were due to start, Harry\rquote s new resolution not to interfere in anything that didn\rquote t concern him was put to an unexpected test. Walking back from the library on his own one afternoon, he heard somebody whimpering from a classroom up ahead. As he drew closer, he heard Quirrell\rquote s voice.\par
\ldblquote No \emdash  no \emdash  not again, please \emdash\rdblquote\par
It sounded as though someone was threatening him. Harry moved closer.\par
\ldblquote All right \emdash  all right \emdash\rdblquote  he heard Quirrell sob.\par
Next second, Quirrell came hurrying out of the classroom straightening his turban. He was pale and looked as though he was about to cry. He strode out of sight; Harry didn\rquote t think Quirrell had even noticed him. He waited until Quirrell\rquote s footsteps had dis\-appeared, then peered into the classroom. It was empty, but a door stood ajar at the other end. Harry was halfway toward it before he remembered what he\rquote d promised himself about not meddling.\par
All the same, he\rquote d have gambled twelve Sorcerer\rquote s Stones that Snape had just left the room, and from what Harry had just heard, Snape would be walking with a new spring in his step \emdash  Quirrell seemed to have given in at last.\par
Harry went back to the library, where Hermione was testing Ron on Astronomy. Harry told them what he\rquote d heard.\par
\ldblquote Snape\rquote s done it, then!\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote If Quirrell\rquote s told him how to break his Anti-Dark Force spell \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s still Fluffy, though,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\par
\ldblquote Maybe Snape\rquote s found out how to get past him without asking Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Ron, looking up at the thousands of books sur\-rounding them. \ldblquote I bet there\rquote s a book somewhere in here telling you how to get past a giant three-headed dog. So what do we do, Harry?\rdblquote\par
The light of adventure was kindling again in Ron\rquote s eyes, but Hermione answered before Harry could.\par
\ldblquote Go to Dumbledore. That\rquote s what we should have done ages ago. If we try anything ourselves we\rquote ll be thrown out for sure.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But we\rquote ve got no \i proof!\rdblquote\i0  said Harry. \ldblquote Quirrell\rquote s too scared to back us up. Snape\rquote s only got to say he doesn\rquote t know how the troll got in at Halloween and that he was nowhere near the third floor \emdash  who do you think they\rquote ll believe, him or us? It\rquote s not exactly a secret we hate him, Dumbledore\rquote ll think we made it up to get him sacked. Filch wouldn\rquote t help us if his life depended on it, he\rquote s too friendly with Snape, and the more students get thrown out, the better, he\rquote ll think. And don\rquote t forget, we\rquote re not supposed to know about the Stone or Fluffy. That\rquote ll take a lot of explaining.\rdblquote\par
Hermione looked convinced, but Ron didn\rquote t.\par
\ldblquote If we just do a bit of poking around \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry flatly, \ldblquote we\rquote ve done enough poking around.\rdblquote\par
He pulled a map of Jupiter toward him and started to learn the names of its moons.\par
