\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj At eleven o\rquote clock that night, they said good-bye to Ron in the common room and went down to the entrance hall with Neville. Filch was already there \emdash  and so was Malfoy. Harry had also for\-gotten that Malfoy had gotten a detention, too.\par
\ldblquote Follow me,\rdblquote  said Filch, lighting a lamp and leading them out\-side.\par
\ldblquote I bet you\rquote ll think twice about breaking a school rule again, won\rquote t you, eh?\rdblquote  he said, leering at them. \ldblquote Oh yes \'85 hard work and pain are the best teachers if you ask me. \'85 It\rquote s just a pity they let the old punishments die out \'85 hang you by your wrists from the ceiling for a few days, I\rquote ve got the chains still in my office, keep \rquote em well oiled in case they\rquote re ever needed. \'85 Right, off we go, and don\rquote t think of running off, now, it\rquote ll be worse for you if you do.\rdblquote\par
They marched off across the dark grounds. Neville kept sniffing. Harry wondered what their punishment was going to be. It must be something really horrible, or Filch wouldn\rquote t be sounding so de\-lighted.\par
The moon was bright, but clouds scudding across it kept throw\-ing them into darkness. Ahead, Harry could see the lighted win\-dows of Hagrid\rquote s hut. Then they heard a distant shout.\par
\ldblquote Is that you, Filch? Hurry up, I want ter get started.\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s heart rose; if they were going to be working with Hagrid it wouldn\rquote t be so bad. His relief must have showed in his face, be\-cause Filch said, \ldblquote I suppose you think you\rquote ll be enjoying yourself with that oaf? Well, think again, boy \emdash  it\rquote s into the forest you\rquote re going and I\rquote m much mistaken if you\rquote ll all come out in one piece.\rdblquote\par
At this, Neville let out a little moan, and Malfoy stopped dead in his tracks.\par
\ldblquote The forest?\rdblquote  he repeated, and he didn\rquote t sound quite as cool as usual. \ldblquote We can\rquote t go in there at night \emdash  there\rquote s all sorts of things in there \emdash  werewolves, I heard.\rdblquote\par
Neville clutched the sleeve of Harry\rquote s robe and made a choking noise.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s your problem, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Filch, his voice cracking with glee. \ldblquote Should\rquote ve thought of them werewolves before you got in trouble, shouldn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
Hagrid came striding toward them out of the dark, Fang at his heel. He was carrying his large crossbow, and a quiver of arrows hung over his shoulder.\par
\ldblquote Abou\rquote  time,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I bin waitin\rquote  fer half an hour already. All right, Harry, Hermione?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I shouldn\rquote t be too friendly to them, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Filch coldly, \ldblquote they\rquote re here to be punished, after all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s why yer late, is it?\rdblquote  said Hagrid, frowning at Filch. \ldblquote Bin lecturin\rquote  them, eh? \rquote Snot your place ter do that. Yeh\rquote ve done yer bit, I\rquote ll take over from here.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be back at dawn,\rdblquote  said Filch, \ldblquote for what\rquote s left of them,\rdblquote  he added nastily, and he turned and started back toward the castle, his lamp bobbing away in the darkness.\par
Malfoy now turned to Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not going in that forest,\rdblquote  he said, and Harry was pleased to hear the note of panic in his voice.\par
\ldblquote Yeh are if yeh want ter stay at Hogwarts,\rdblquote  said Hagrid fiercely. \ldblquote Yeh\rquote ve done wrong an\rquote  now yeh\rquote ve got ter pay fer it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But this is servant stuff, it\rquote s not for students to do. I thought we\rquote d be copying lines or something, if my father knew I was doing this, he\rquote d \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\emdash  tell yer that\rquote s how it is at Hogwarts,\rdblquote  Hagrid growled. \ldblquote Copyin\rquote  lines! What good\rquote s that ter anyone? Yeh\rquote ll do summat use\-ful or yeh\rquote ll get out. If yeh think yer father\rquote d rather you were ex\-pelled, then get back off ter the castle an\rquote  pack. Go on!\rdblquote\par
Malfoy didn\rquote t move. He looked at Hagrid furiously, but then dropped his gaze.\par
\ldblquote Right then,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote now, listen carefully, \rquote cause it\rquote s dan\-gerous what we\rquote re gonna do tonight, an\rquote  I don\rquote  want no one takin\rquote  risks. Follow me over here a moment.\rdblquote\par
He led them to the very edge of the forest. Holding his lamp up high, he pointed down a narrow, winding earth track that disap\-peared into the thick black trees. A light breeze lifted their hair as they looked into the forest.\par
\ldblquote Look there,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote see that stuff shinin\rquote  on the ground? Silvery stuff? That\rquote s unicorn blood. There\rquote s a unicorn in there bin hurt badly by summat. This is the second time in a week. I found one dead last Wednesday. We\rquote re gonna try an\rquote  find the poor thing. We might have ter put it out of its misery.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what if whatever hurt the unicorn finds us first?\rdblquote  said Malfoy, unable to keep the fear out of his voice.\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s nothin\rquote  that lives in the forest that\rquote ll hurt yeh if yer with me or Fang,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote An\rquote  keep ter the path. Right, now, we\rquote re gonna split inter two parties an\rquote  follow the trail in diff\rquote rent directions. There\rquote s blood all over the place, it must\rquote ve bin staggerin\rquote  around since last night at least.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I want Fang,\rdblquote  said Malfoy quickly, looking at Fang\rquote s long teeth.\par
\ldblquote All right, but I warn yeh, he\rquote s a coward,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote So me, Harry, an\rquote  Hermione\rquote ll go one way an\rquote  Draco, Neville, an\rquote  Fang\rquote ll go the other. Now, if any of us finds the unicorn, we\rquote ll send up green sparks, right? Get yer wands out an\rquote  practice now \emdash  that\rquote s it \emdash  an\rquote  if anyone gets in trouble, send up red sparks, an\rquote  we\rquote ll all come an\rquote  find yeh \emdash  so, be careful \emdash  let\rquote s go.\rdblquote\par
The forest was black and silent. A little way into it they reached a fork in the earth path, and Harry, Hermione, and Hagrid took the left path while Malfoy, Neville, and Fang took the right.\par
They walked in silence, their eyes on the ground. Every now and then a ray of moonlight through the branches above lit a spot of silver-blue blood on the fallen leaves.\par
Harry saw that Hagrid looked very worried.\par
\i\ldblquote Could\i0  a werewolf be killing the unicorns?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
\ldblquote Not fast enough,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote It\rquote s not easy ter catch a uni\-corn, they\rquote re powerful magic creatures. I never knew one ter be hurt before.\rdblquote\par
They walked past a mossy tree stump. Harry could hear running water; there must be a stream somewhere close by. There were still spots of unicorn blood here and there along the winding path.\par
\ldblquote You all right, Hermione?\rdblquote  Hagrid whispered. \ldblquote Don\rquote  worry, it can\rquote t\rquote ve gone far if it\rquote s this badly hurt, an\rquote  then we\rquote ll be able ter \emdash  GET BEHIND THAT TREE!\rdblquote\par
Hagrid seized Harry and Hermione and hoisted them off the path behind a towering oak. He pulled out an arrow and fitted it into his crossbow, raising it, ready to fire. The three of them lis\-tened. Something was slithering over dead leaves nearby: it sounded like a cloak trailing along the ground. Hagrid was squint\-ing up the dark path, but after a few seconds, the sound faded away.\par
\ldblquote I knew it,\rdblquote  he murmured. \ldblquote There\rquote s summat in here that shouldn\rquote  be.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A werewolf?\rdblquote  Harry suggested.\par
\ldblquote That wasn\rquote  no werewolf an\rquote  it wasn\rquote  no unicorn, neither,\rdblquote  said Hagrid grimly. \ldblquote Right, follow me, but careful, now.\rdblquote\par
They walked more slowly, ears straining for the faintest sound. Suddenly, in a clearing ahead, something definitely moved.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  Hagrid called. \ldblquote Show yerself \emdash  I\rquote m armed!\rdblquote\par
And into the clearing came \emdash  was it a man, or a horse? To the waist, a man, with red hair and beard, but below that was a horse\rquote s gleaming chestnut body with a long, reddish tail. Harry and Hermione\rquote s jaws dropped.\par
\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s you, Ronan,\rdblquote  said Hagrid in relief. \ldblquote How are yeh?\rdblquote\par
He walked forward and shook the centaur\rquote s hand.\par
\ldblquote Good evening to you, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Ronan. He had a deep, sorrowful voice. \ldblquote Were you going to shoot me?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t be too careful, Ronan,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, patting his crossbow. \ldblquote There\rquote s summat bad loose in this forest. This is Harry Potter an\rquote  Hermione Granger, by the way. Students up at the school. An\rquote  this is Ronan, you two. He\rquote s a centaur.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote d noticed,\rdblquote  said Hermione faintly.\par
\ldblquote Good evening,\rdblquote  said Ronan. \ldblquote Students, are you? And do you learn much, up at the school?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Erm \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A bit,\rdblquote  said Hermione timidly.\par
\ldblquote A bit. Well, that\rquote s something.\rdblquote  Ronan sighed. He flung back his head and stared at the sky. \ldblquote Mars is bright tonight.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, glancing up, too. \ldblquote Listen, I\rquote m glad we\rquote ve run inter yeh, Ronan, \rquote cause there\rquote s a unicorn bin hurt \emdash  you seen anythin\rquote ?\rdblquote\par
Ronan didn\rquote t answer immediately. He stared unblinkingly up\-ward, then sighed again.\par
\ldblquote Always the innocent are the first victims,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote So it has been for ages past, so it is now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote but have yeh seen anythin\rquote , Ronan? Any\-thin\rquote  unusual?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mars is bright tonight,\rdblquote  Ronan repeated, while Hagrid watched him impatiently. \ldblquote Unusually bright.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, but I was meanin\rquote  anythin\rquote  unusual a bit nearer home,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote So yeh haven\rquote t noticed anythin\rquote  strange?\rdblquote\par
Yet again, Ronan took a while to answer. At last, he said, \ldblquote The forest hides many secrets.\rdblquote\par
A movement in the trees behind Ronan made Hagrid raise his bow again, but it was only a second centaur, black-haired and -bodied and wilder-looking than Ronan.\par
\ldblquote Hullo, Bane,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote All right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good evening, Hagrid, I hope you are well?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well enough. Look, I\rquote ve jus\rquote  bin askin\rquote  Ronan, you seen any\-thin\rquote  odd in here lately? There\rquote s a unicorn bin injured \emdash  would yeh know anythin\rquote  about it?\rdblquote\par
Bane walked over to stand next to Ronan. He looked skyward.\par
\ldblquote Mars is bright tonight,\rdblquote  he said simply.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ve heard,\rdblquote  said Hagrid grumpily. \ldblquote Well, if either of you do see anythin\rquote , let me know, won\rquote t yeh? We\rquote ll be off, then.\rdblquote\par
Harry and Hermione followed him out of the clearing, staring over their shoulders at Ronan and Bane until the trees blocked their view.\par
\ldblquote Never,\rdblquote  said Hagrid irritably, \ldblquote try an\rquote  get a straight answer out of a centaur. Ruddy stargazers. Not interested in anythin\rquote  closer\rquote n the moon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Are there many of \i them\i0  in here?\rdblquote  asked Hermione.\par
\ldblquote Oh, a fair few. \'85 Keep themselves to themselves mostly, but they\rquote re good enough about turnin\rquote  up if ever I want a word. They\rquote re deep, mind, centaurs \'85 they know things \'85 jus\rquote  don\rquote  let on much.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote D\rquote you think that was a centaur we heard earlier?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Did that sound like hooves to you? Nah, if yeh ask me, that was what\rquote s bin killin\rquote  the unicorns \emdash  never heard anythin\rquote  like it be\-fore.\rdblquote\par
They walked on through the dense, dark trees. Harry kept look\-ing nervously over his shoulder. He had the nasty feeling they were being watched. He was very glad they had Hagrid and his crossbow with them. They had just passed a bend in the path when Her\-mione grabbed Hagrid\rquote s arm.\par
\ldblquote Hagrid! Look! Red sparks, the others are in trouble!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You two wait here!\rdblquote  Hagrid shouted. \ldblquote Stay on the path, I\rquote ll come back for yeh!\rdblquote\par
They heard him crashing away through the undergrowth and stood looking at each other, very scared, until they couldn\rquote t hear anything but the rustling of leaves around them.\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t think they\rquote ve been hurt, do you?\rdblquote  whispered Hermione.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t care if Malfoy has, but if something\rquote s got Neville \'85 it\rquote s our fault he\rquote s here in the first place.\rdblquote\par
The minutes dragged by. Their ears seemed sharper than usual. Harry\rquote s seemed to be picking up every sigh of the wind, every cracking twig. What was going on? Where were the others?\par
At last, a great crunching noise announced Hagrid\rquote s return. Mal\-foy, Neville, and Fang were with him. Hagrid was fuming. Malfoy, it seemed, had sneaked up behind Neville and grabbed him as a joke. Neville had panicked and sent up the sparks.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ll be lucky ter catch anythin\rquote  now, with the racket you two were makin\rquote . Right, we\rquote re changin\rquote  groups \emdash  Neville, you stay with me an\rquote  Hermione, Harry, you go with Fang an\rquote  this idiot. I\rquote m sorry,\rdblquote  Hagrid added in a whisper to Harry, \ldblquote but he\rquote ll have a harder time frightenin\rquote  you, an\rquote  we\rquote ve gotta get this done.\rdblquote\par
So Harry set off into the heart of the forest with Malfoy and Fang. They walked for nearly half an hour, deeper and deeper into the forest, until the path became almost impossible to follow be\-cause the trees were so thick. Harry thought the blood seemed to be getting thicker. There were splashes on the roots of a tree, as though the poor creature had been thrashing around in pain close by. Harry could see a clearing ahead, through the tangled branches of an ancient oak.\par
\ldblquote Look \emdash\rdblquote  he murmured, holding out his arm to stop Malfoy.\par
Something bright white was gleaming on the ground. They inched closer.\par
It was the unicorn all right, and it was dead. Harry had never seen anything so beautiful and sad. Its long, slender legs were stuck out at odd angles where it had fallen and its mane was spread pearly-white on the dark leaves.\par
Harry had taken one step toward it when a slithering sound made him freeze where he stood. A bush on the edge of the clear\-ing quivered. \'85 Then, out of the shadows, a hooded figure came crawling across the ground like some stalking beast. Harry, Malfoy, and Fang stood transfixed. The cloaked figure reached the unicorn, lowered its head over the wound in the animals side, and began to drink its blood.\par
\ldblquote AAAAAAAAAAARGH!\rdblquote\par
Malfoy let out a terrible scream and bolted \emdash  so did Fang. The hooded figure raised its head and looked right at Harry \emdash  unicorn blood was dribbling down its front. It got to its feet and came swiftly toward Harry \emdash  he couldn\rquote t move for fear.\par
Then a pain like he\rquote d never felt before pierced his head; it was as though his scar were on fire. Half blinded, he staggered backward. He heard hooves behind him, galloping, and something jumped clean over Harry, charging at the figure.\par
The pain in Harry\rquote s head was so bad he fell to his knees. It took a minute or two to pass. When he looked up, the figure had gone. A centaur was standing over him, not Ronan or Bane; this one looked younger; he had white-blond hair and a palomino body.\par
\ldblquote Are you all right?\rdblquote  said the centaur, pulling Harry to his feet.\par
\ldblquote Yes \emdash  thank you \emdash  what \i was\i0  that?\rdblquote\par
The centaur didn\rquote t answer. He had astonishingly blue eyes, like pale sapphires. He looked carefully at Harry, his eyes lingering on the scar that stood out, livid, on Harry\rquote s forehead.\par
\ldblquote You are the Potter boy,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You had better get back to Hagrid. The forest is not safe at this time \emdash  especially for you. Can you ride? It will be quicker this way.\par
\ldblquote My name is Firenze,\rdblquote  he added, as he lowered himself on to his front legs so that Harry could clamber onto his back.\par
There was suddenly a sound of more galloping from the other side of the clearing. Ronan and Bane came bursting through the trees, their flanks heaving and sweaty.\par
\ldblquote Firenze!\rdblquote  Bane thundered. \ldblquote What are you doing? You have a hu\-man on your back! Have you no shame? Are you a common mule?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you realize who this is?\rdblquote  said Firenze. \ldblquote This is the Potter boy. The quicker he leaves this forest, the better.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What have you been telling him?\rdblquote  growled Bane. \ldblquote Remember, Firenze, we are sworn not to set ourselves against the heavens. Have we not read what is to come in the movements of the planets?\rdblquote\par
Ronan pawed the ground nervously. \ldblquote I\rquote m sure Firenze thought he was acting for the best,\rdblquote  he said in his gloomy voice.\par
Bane kicked his back legs in anger.\par
\ldblquote For the best! What is that to do with us? Centaurs are con\-cerned with what has been foretold! It is not our business to run around like donkeys after stray humans in our forest!\rdblquote\par
Firenze suddenly reared on to his hind legs in anger, so that Harry had to grab his shoulders to stay on.\par
\ldblquote Do you not see that unicorn?\rdblquote  Firenze bellowed at Bane. \ldblquote Do you not understand why it was killed? Or have the planets not let you in on that secret? I set myself against what is lurking in this for\-est, Bane, yes, with humans alongside me if I must.\rdblquote\par
And Firenze whisked around; with Harry clutching on as best he could, they plunged off into the trees, leaving Ronan and Bane be\-hind them.\par
Harry didn\rquote t have a clue what was going on.\par
\ldblquote Why\rquote s Bane so angry?\rdblquote  he asked. \ldblquote What was that thing you saved me from, anyway?\rdblquote\par
Firenze slowed to a walk, warned Harry to keep his head bowed in case of low-hanging branches, but did not answer Harry\rquote s ques\-tion. They made their way through the trees in silence for so long that Harry thought Firenze didn\rquote t want to talk to him anymore. They were passing through a particularly dense patch of trees, how\-ever, when Firenze suddenly stopped.\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter, do you know what unicorn blood is used for?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, startled by the odd question. \ldblquote We\rquote ve only used the horn and tail hair in Potions.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That is because it is a monstrous thing, to slay a unicorn,\rdblquote  said Firenze. \ldblquote Only one who has nothing to lose, and everything to gain, would commit such a crime. The blood of a unicorn will keep you alive, even if you are an inch from death, but at a terrible price. You have slain something pure and defenseless to save yourself, and you will have but a half-life, a cursed life, from the moment the blood touches your lips.\rdblquote\par
Harry stared at the back of Firenze\rquote s head, which was dappled silver in the moonlight.\par
