But leaving Neville lying motionless on the floor didn\rquote t feel like a very good omen. In their nervous state, every statue\rquote s shadow looked like Filch, every distant breath of wind sounded like Peeves swooping down on them.\par
At the foot of the first set of stairs, they spotted Mrs. Norris skulking near the top.\par
\ldblquote Oh, let\rquote s kick her, just this once,\rdblquote  Ron whispered in Harry\rquote s ear, but Harry shook his head. As they climbed carefully around her, Mrs. Norris turned her lamplike eyes on them, but didn\rquote t do any\-thing.\par
They didn\rquote t meet anyone else until they reached the staircase up to the third floor. Peeves was bobbing halfway up, loosening the carpet so that people would trip.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  he said suddenly as they climbed toward him. He narrowed his wicked black eyes. \ldblquote Know you\rquote re there, even if I can\rquote t see you. Are you ghoulie or ghostie or wee student beastie?\rdblquote\par
He rose up in the air and floated there, squinting at them.\par
\ldblquote Should call Filch, I should, if something\rquote s a-creeping around unseen.\rdblquote\par
Harry had a sudden idea.\par
\ldblquote Peeves,\rdblquote  he said, in a hoarse whisper, \ldblquote the Bloody Baron has his own reasons for being invisible.\rdblquote\par
Peeves almost fell out of the air in shock. He caught himself in time and hovered about a foot off the stairs.\par
\ldblquote So sorry, your bloodiness, Mr. Baron, sir,\rdblquote  he said greasily. \ldblquote My mistake, my mistake \emdash  I didn\rquote t see you \emdash  of course I didn\rquote t, you\rquote re invisible \emdash  forgive old Peevsie his little joke, sir.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I have business here, Peeves,\rdblquote  croaked Harry. \ldblquote Stay away from this place tonight.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I will, sir, I most certainly will,\rdblquote  said Peeves, rising up in the air again. \ldblquote Hope your business goes well, Baron, I\rquote ll not bother you.\rdblquote\par
And he scooted off.\par
\i\ldblquote Brilliant,\i0  Harry!\rdblquote  whispered Ron.\par
A few seconds later, they were there, outside the third-floor cor\-ridor \emdash  and the door was already ajar.\par
\ldblquote Well, there you are,\rdblquote  Harry said quietly, \ldblquote Snape\rquote s already got past Fluffy.\rdblquote\par
Seeing the open door somehow seemed to impress upon all three of them what was facing them. Underneath the cloak, Harry turned to the other two.\par
\ldblquote If you want to go back, I won\rquote t blame you,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You can take the cloak, I won\rquote t need it now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re coming,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\par
Harry pushed the door open.\par
As the door creaked, low, rumbling growls met their ears. All three of the dog\rquote s noses sniffed madly in their direction, even though it couldn\rquote t see them.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s that at its feet?\rdblquote  Hermione whispered.\par
\ldblquote Looks like a harp,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Snape must have left it there.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It must wake up the moment you stop playing,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well, here goes \'85\rdblquote\par
He put Hagrid\rquote s flute to his lips and blew. It wasn\rquote t really a tune, but from the first note the beast\rquote s eyes began to droop. Harry hardly drew breath. Slowly, the dog\rquote s growls ceased \emdash  it tottered on its paws and fell to its knees, then it slumped to the ground, fast asleep.\par
\ldblquote Keep playing,\rdblquote  Ron warned Harry as they slipped out of the cloak and crept toward the trapdoor. They could feel the dog\rquote s hot, smelly breath as they approached the giant heads.\par
\ldblquote I think we\rquote ll be able to pull the door open,\rdblquote  said Ron, peering over the dog\rquote s back. \ldblquote Want to go first, Hermione?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right.\rdblquote  Ron gritted his teeth and stepped carefully over the dog\rquote s legs. He bent and pulled the ring of the trapdoor, which swung up and open.\par
\ldblquote What can you see?\rdblquote  Hermione said anxiously.\par
\ldblquote Nothing \emdash  just black \emdash  there\rquote s no way of climbing down, we\rquote ll just have to drop.\rdblquote\par
Harry, who was still playing the flute, waved at Ron to get his at\-tention and pointed at himself.\par
\ldblquote You want to go first? Are you sure?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know how deep this thing goes. Give the flute to Hermione so she can keep him asleep.\rdblquote\par
Harry handed the flute over. In the few seconds\rquote  silence, the dog growled and twitched, but the moment Hermione began to play, it fell back into its deep sleep.\par
Harry climbed over it and looked down through the trapdoor. There was no sign of the bottom.\par
He lowered himself through the hole until he was hanging on by his fingertips. Then he looked up at Ron and said, \ldblquote If anything happens to me, don\rquote t follow. Go straight to the owlery and send Hedwig to Dumbledore, right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote See you in a minute, I hope. \'85\rdblquote\par
And Harry let go. Cold, damp air rushed past him as he fell down, down, down and \emdash\par
FLUMP. With a funny, muffled sort of thump he landed on something soft. He sat up and felt around, his eyes not used to the gloom. It felt as though he was sitting on some sort of plant.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s okay!\rdblquote  he called up to the light the size of a postage stamp, which was the open trapdoor, \ldblquote it\rquote s a soft landing, you can jump!\rdblquote\par
Ron followed right away. He landed, sprawled next to Harry.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s this stuff?\rdblquote  were his first words.\par
\ldblquote Dunno, some sort of plant thing. I suppose it\rquote s here to break the fall. Come on, Hermione!\rdblquote\par
The distant music stopped. There was a loud bark from the dog, but Hermione had already jumped. She landed on Harry\rquote s other side.\par
\ldblquote We must be miles under the school,\rdblquote  she said.\par
\ldblquote Lucky this plant thing\rquote s here, really,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\i\ldblquote Lucky!\rdblquote\i0  shrieked Hermione. \ldblquote Look at you both!\rdblquote\par
She leapt up and struggled toward a damp wall. She had to struggle because the moment she had landed, the plant had started to twist snakelike tendrils around her ankles. As for Harry and Ron, their legs had already been bound tightly in long creepers without their noticing.\par
Hermione had managed to free herself before the plant got a firm grip on her. Now she watched in horror as the two boys fought to pull the plant off them, but the more they strained against it, the tighter and faster the plant wound around them.\par
\ldblquote Stop moving!\rdblquote  Hermione ordered them. \ldblquote I know what this is \emdash  it\rquote s Devil\rquote s Snare!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, I\rquote m so glad we know what it\rquote s called, that\rquote s a great help,\rdblquote  snarled Ron, leaning back, trying to stop the plant from curling around his neck.\par
\ldblquote Shut up, I\rquote m trying to remember how to kill it!\rdblquote  said Her\-mione.\par
\ldblquote Well, hurry up, I can\rquote t breathe!\rdblquote  Harry gasped, wrestling with it as it curled around his chest.\par
\ldblquote Devil\rquote s Snare, Devil\rquote s Snare \'85 what did Professor Sprout say? \emdash  it likes the dark and the damp \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So light a fire!\rdblquote  Harry choked.\par
\ldblquote Yes \emdash  of course \emdash  but there\rquote s no wood!\rdblquote  Hermione cried, wringing her hands.\par
\ldblquote HAVE YOU GONE MAD?\rdblquote  Ron bellowed. \ldblquote ARE YOU A WITCH OR NOT?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, right!\rdblquote  said Hermione, and she whipped out her wand, waved it, muttered something, and sent a jet of the same bluebell flames she had used on Snape at the plant. In a matter of seconds, the two boys felt it loosening its grip as it cringed away from the light and warmth. Wriggling and flailing, it unraveled itself from their bodies, and they were able to pull free.\par
\ldblquote Lucky you pay attention in Herbology, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Harry as he joined her by the wall, wiping sweat off his face.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote and lucky Harry doesn\rquote t lose his head in a cri\-sis \emdash  \lquote there\rquote s no wood,\rquote  \i honestly.\rdblquote\i0\par
\ldblquote This way,\rdblquote  said Harry, pointing down a stone passageway, which was the only way forward.\par
All they could hear apart from their footsteps was the gentle drip of water trickling down the walls. The passageway sloped down\-ward, and Harry was reminded of Gringotts. With an unpleasant jolt of the heart, he remembered the dragons said to be guarding vaults in the wizards\rquote  bank. If they met a dragon, a fully-grown dragon \emdash  Norbert had been bad enough \'85\par
\ldblquote Can you hear something?\rdblquote  Ron whispered.\par
Harry listened. A soft rustling and clinking seemed to be com\-ing from up ahead.\par
\ldblquote Do you think it\rquote s a ghost?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know \'85 sounds like wings to me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s light ahead \emdash  I can see something moving.\rdblquote\par
They reached the end of the passageway and saw before them a brilliantly lit chamber, its ceiling arching high above them. It was full of small, jewel-bright birds, fluttering and tumbling all around the room. On the opposite side of the chamber was a heavy wooden door.\par
\ldblquote Do you think they\rquote ll attack us if we cross the room?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Probably,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote They don\rquote t look very vicious, but I sup\-pose if they all swooped down at once \'85 well, there\rquote s no other choice \'85 I\rquote ll run.\rdblquote\par
He took a deep breath, covered his face with his arms, and sprinted across the room. He expected to feel sharp beaks and claws tearing at him any second, but nothing happened. He reached the door untouched. He pulled the handle, but it was locked.\par
The other two followed him. They tugged and heaved at the door, but it wouldn\rquote t budge, not even when Hermione tried her Alohomora Charm.\par
\ldblquote Now what?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote These birds \'85 they can\rquote t be here just for decoration,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\par
They watched the birds soaring overhead, glittering \emdash  \i glitter\-ing?\i0\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re not birds!\rdblquote  Harry said suddenly. \ldblquote They\rquote re \i keys!\i0  Winged keys \emdash  look carefully. So that must mean \'85\rdblquote  he looked around the chamber while the other two squinted up at the flock of keys. \ldblquote\'85 yes \emdash  look! Broomsticks! We\rquote ve got to catch the key to the door!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But there are \i hundreds\i0  of them!\rdblquote\par
Ron examined the lock on the door.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re looking for a big, old-fashioned one \emdash  probably silver, like the handle.\rdblquote\par
They each seized a broomstick and kicked off into the air, soar\-ing into the midst of the cloud of keys. They grabbed and snatched, but the bewitched keys darted and dived so quickly it was almost impossible to catch one.\par
Not for nothing, though, was Harry the youngest Seeker in a century. He had a knack for spotting things other people didn\rquote t. Af\-ter a minute\rquote s weaving about through the whirl of rainbow feathers, he noticed a large silver key that had a bent wing, as if it had al\-ready been caught and stuffed roughly into the keyhole.\par
\ldblquote That one!\rdblquote  he called to the others. \ldblquote That big one \emdash  there \emdash  no, there \emdash  with bright blue wings \emdash  the feathers are all crum\-pled on one side.\rdblquote\par
Ron went speeding in the direction that Harry was pointing, crashed into the ceiling, and nearly fell off his broom.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ve got to close in on it!\rdblquote  Harry called, not taking his eyes off the key with the damaged wing. \ldblquote Ron, you come at it from above \emdash  Hermione, stay below and stop it from going down \emdash  and I\rquote ll try and catch it. Right, NOW!\rdblquote\par
Ron dived, Hermione rocketed upward, the key dodged them both, and Harry streaked after it; it sped toward the wall, Harry leaned forward and with a nasty, crunching noise, pinned it against the stone with one hand. Ron and Hermione\rquote s cheers echoed around the high chamber.\par
They landed quickly, and Harry ran to the door, the key strug\-gling in his hand. He rammed it into the lock and turned \emdash  it worked. The moment the lock had clicked open, the key took flight again, looking very battered now that it had been caught twice.\par
\ldblquote Ready?\rdblquote  Harry asked the other two, his hand on the door han\-dle. They nodded. He pulled the door open.\par
The next chamber was so dark they couldn\rquote t see anything at all. But as they stepped into it, light suddenly flooded the room to re\-veal an astonishing sight.\par
They were standing on the edge of a huge chessboard, behind the black chessmen, which were all taller than they were and carved from what looked like black stone. Facing them, way across the chamber, were the white pieces. Harry, Ron and Hermione shiv\-ered slightly \emdash  the towering white chessmen had no faces.\par
\ldblquote Now what do we do?\rdblquote  Harry whispered.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s obvious, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got to play our way across the room.\rdblquote\par
Behind the white pieces they could see another door.\par
\ldblquote How?\rdblquote  said Hermione nervously.\par
\ldblquote I think,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote we\rquote re going to have to be chessmen.\rdblquote\par
He walked up to a black knight and put his hand out to touch the knights horse. At once, the stone sprang to life. The horse pawed the ground and the knight turned his helmeted head to look down at Ron.\par
\ldblquote Do we \emdash  er \emdash  have to join you to get across?\rdblquote\par
The black knight nodded. Ron turned to the other two.\par
\ldblquote This needs thinking about. \'85\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I suppose we\rquote ve got to take the place of three of the black pieces. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry and Hermione stayed quiet, watching Ron think. Finally he said, \ldblquote Now, don\rquote t be offended or anything, but neither of you are that good at chess \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re not offended,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote Just tell us what to do.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, Harry, you take the place of that bishop, and Hermione, you go there instead of that castle.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m going to be a knight,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
The chessmen seemed to have been listening, because at these words a knight, a bishop, and a castle turned their backs on the white pieces and walked off the board, leaving three empty squares that Harry, Ron, and Hermione took.\par
\ldblquote White always plays first in chess,\rdblquote  said Ron, peering across the board. \ldblquote Yes \'85 look \'85\rdblquote\par
A white pawn had moved forward two squares.\par
Ron started to direct the black pieces. They moved silently wherever he sent them. Harry\rquote s knees were trembling. What if they lost?\par
\ldblquote Harry \emdash  move diagonally four squares to the right.\rdblquote\par
Their first real shock came when their other knight was taken. The white queen smashed him to the floor and dragged him off the board, where he lay quite still, facedown.\par
\ldblquote Had to let that happen,\rdblquote  said Ron, looking shaken. \ldblquote Leaves you free to take that bishop, Hermione, go on.\rdblquote\par
Every time one of their men was lost, the white pieces showed no mercy. Soon there was a huddle of limp black players slumped along the wall. Twice, Ron only just noticed in time that Harry and Hermione were in danger. He himself darted around the board, taking almost as many white pieces as they had lost black ones.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re nearly there,\rdblquote  he muttered suddenly. \ldblquote Let me think \emdash  let me think \'85\rdblquote\par
The white queen turned her blank face toward him.\par
\ldblquote Yes \'85\rdblquote  said Ron softly, \ldblquote it\rquote s the only way \'85 I\rquote ve got to be taken.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote NO!\rdblquote  Harry and Hermione shouted.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s chess!\rdblquote  snapped Ron. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got to make some sacri\-fices! I make my move and she\rquote ll take me \emdash  that leaves you free to checkmate the king, Harry!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you want to stop Snape or not?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ron \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Look, if you don\rquote t hurry up, he\rquote ll already have the Stone!\rdblquote\par
There was no alternative.\par
\ldblquote Ready?\rdblquote  Ron called, his face pale but determined. \ldblquote Here I go \emdash  now, don\rquote t hang around once you\rquote ve won.\rdblquote\par
He stepped forward, and the white queen pounced. She struck Ron hard across the head with her stone arm, and he crashed to the floor \emdash  Hermione screamed but stayed on her square \emdash  the white queen dragged Ron to one side. He looked as if he\rquote d been knocked out.\par
Shaking, Harry moved three spaces to the left.\par
The white king took off his crown and threw it at Harry\rquote s feet. They had won. The chessmen parted and bowed, leaving the door ahead clear. With one last desperate look back at Ron, Harry and Hermione charged through the door and up the next passageway.\par
\ldblquote What if he\rquote s \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote ll be all right,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to convince himself. \ldblquote What do you reckon\rquote s next?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ve had Sprout\rquote s, that was the Devil\rquote s Snare; Flitwick must\rquote ve put charms on the keys; McGonagall transfigured the chessmen to make them alive; that leaves Quirrell\rquote s spell, and Snape\rquote s \'85\rdblquote\par
They had reached another door.\par
\ldblquote All right?\rdblquote  Harry whispered.\par
\ldblquote Go on.\rdblquote\par
Harry pushed it open.\par
A disgusting smell filled their nostrils, making both of them pull their robes up over their noses. Eyes watering, they saw, flat on the floor in front of them, a troll even larger than the one they had tackled, out cold with a bloody lump on its head.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m glad we didn\rquote t have to fight that one,\rdblquote  Harry whispered as they stepped carefully over one of its massive legs. \ldblquote Come on, I can\rquote t breathe.\rdblquote\par
He pulled open the next door, both of them hardly daring to look at what came next \emdash  but there was nothing very frightening in here, just a table with seven differently shaped bottles standing on it in a line.\par
\ldblquote Snape\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote What do we have to do?\rdblquote\par
They stepped over the threshold, and immediately a fire sprang up behind them in the doorway. It wasn\rquote t ordinary fire either; it was purple. At the same instant, black flames shot up in the doorway leading onward. They were trapped.\par
\ldblquote Look!\rdblquote  Hermione seized a roll of paper lying next to the bottles. Harry looked over her shoulder to read it:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li567\i Danger lies before you, while safety lies behind,\i0\par
\i Two of us will help you, whichever you would find,\i0\par
\i One among us seven will let you move ahead,\i0\par
\i Another will transport the drinker back instead,\i0\par
\i Two among our number hold only nettle wine,\i0\par
\i Three of us are killers, waiting hidden in line.\i0\par
\i Choose, unless you wish to stay here forevermore,\i0\par
\i To help you in your choice, we give you these clues four:\i0\par
\i First, however slyly the poison tries to hide\i0\par
\i You will always find some on nettle wine\rquote s left side;\i0\par
\i Second, different are those who stand at either end,\i0\par
\i But if you would move onward, neither is your friend;\i0\par
\i Third, as you see clearly, all are different size,\i0\par
\i Neither dwarf nor giant holds death in their insides;\i0\par
\i Fourth, the second left and the second on the right\i0\par
\i Are twins once you taste them, though different at first sight.\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj Hermione let out a great sigh and Harry, amazed, saw that she was smiling, the very last thing he felt like doing.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i\ldblquote Brilliant,\rdblquote\i0  said Hermione. \ldblquote This isn\rquote t magic \emdash  it\rquote s logic \emdash  a puzzle. A lot of the greatest wizards haven\rquote t got an ounce of logic, they\rquote d be stuck in here forever.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But so will we, won\rquote t we?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course not,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Everything we need is here on this paper. Seven bottles: three are poison; two are wine; one will get us safely through the black fire, and one will get us back through the purple.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But how do we know which to drink?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Give me a minute.\rdblquote\par
Hermione read the paper several times. Then she walked up and down the line of bottles, muttering to herself and pointing at them. At last, she clapped her hands.\par
\ldblquote Got it,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote The smallest bottle will get us through the black fire \emdash  toward the Stone.\rdblquote\par
Harry looked at the tiny bottle.\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s only enough there for one of us,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote That\rquote s hardly one swallow.\rdblquote\par
They looked at each other.\par
\ldblquote Which one will get you back through the purple flames?\rdblquote\par
Hermione pointed at a rounded bottle at the right end of the line.\par
\ldblquote You drink that,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote No, listen, get back and get Ron. Grab brooms from the flying-key room, they\rquote ll get you out of the trapdoor and past Fluffy \emdash  go straight to the owlery and send Hedwig to Dumbledore, we need him. I might be able to hold Snape off for a while, but I\rquote m no match for him, really.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But Harry \emdash  what if You-Know-Who\rquote s with him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well \emdash  I was lucky once, wasn\rquote t I?\rdblquote  said Harry, pointing at his scar. \ldblquote I might get lucky again.\rdblquote\par
Hermione\rquote s lip trembled, and she suddenly dashed at Harry and threw her arms around him.\par
\i\ldblquote Hermione!\rdblquote\par
\i0\ldblquote Harry \emdash  you\rquote re a great wizard, you know.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not as good as you,\rdblquote  said Harry, very embarrassed, as she let go of him.\par
\ldblquote Me!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Books! And cleverness! There are more important things \emdash  friendship and bravery and \emdash  oh Harry \emdash  be \i careful!\rdblquote\i0\par
\ldblquote You drink first,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You are sure which is which, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Positive,\rdblquote  said Hermione. She took a long drink from the round bottle at the end, and shuddered.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not poison?\rdblquote  said Harry anxiously.\par
\ldblquote No \emdash  but it\rquote s like ice.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Quick, go, before it wears off.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good luck \emdash  take care \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote GO!\rdblquote\par
Hermione turned and walked straight through the purple fire.\par
Harry took a deep breath and picked up the smallest bottle. He turned to face the black flames.\par
\ldblquote Here I come,\rdblquote  he said, and he drained the little bottle in one gulp.\par
It was indeed as though ice was flooding his body. He put the bottle down and walked forward; he braced himself, saw the black flames licking his body, but couldn\rquote t feel them \emdash  for a moment he could see nothing but dark fire \emdash  then he was on the other side, in the last chamber.\par
There was already someone there \emdash  but it wasn\rquote t Snape. It wasn\rquote t even Voldemort.\par
